{"title_page": "Hans Lauda", "text_new": "{{short description|Austrian industrialist}}\n{{Use British English| date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Hans Lauda\n| image         = <!-- filename only, no \"File:\" or \"Image:\" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt           = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption       =\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1896|3|25|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[Vienna]], [[Austria-Hungary]]\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1974|1|21|1896|3|25|df=y}}\n| death_place   = Vienna, Austria\n| nationality   = Austrian\n| occupation    = Industrialist\n| years_active  = 1923-1960\n| known_for     = President of [[Federation of Austrian Industries]]\n}}\n\n'''Hans Lauda''' (25 March 1896&nbsp;\u2013 21 January 1974)<ref name=Mun/> was an Austrian industrialist who co-founded the [[Federation of Austrian Industries]] and served as president from 1946 to 1960. He was the paternal grandfather of [[Formula One]] World Champion [[Niki Lauda]].\n\n==Early life==\nHans Lauda was born on 25 March 1896 in [[Vienna]].<ref name=Mun>{{cite web| url= https://www.munzinger.de/search/portrait/Hans+Lauda/0/7284.html| title= Hans Lauda| language=de| publisher=[[Munzinger-Archiv]]| date=30 July 1956| accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref> His father {{ill|Ernst Lauda|de|Ernst Lauda (Techniker)}} worked in [[hydraulic engineering]] and bridge construction.<ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.biographien.ac.at/oebl/oebl_L/Lauda_Ernst_1859_1932.xml| title= Lauda, Ernst Ritter von (1859\u20131932), Wasserbau- und Br\u00fcckenbautechniker| language=de| publisher=[[\u00d6sterreichisches Biographisches Lexikon 1815\u20131950]]| date=1 March 2011| accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref> Lauda studied at the [[Theresianum]],<ref name=Mun/> and the [[University of Vienna]], where he earned a doctorate in law.<ref name=Mun/><ref name=Muller>{{cite book| url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121204002822/http://www.styriabooks.at/files/images/9783222132667_Leseprobe.pdf| type=pdf| title= Niki Lauda: Alles unter eine Kappe| language=de|last=M\u00fcller| first=Stefan| publisher=[[Styria Media Group]]| date=2012| pages=15-21}}</ref> He was known as \"Old Lauda\".<ref name=Muller/> He was interested in Formula One, and drove to the [[N\u00fcrburgring]] and to [[Monaco]] to watch Formula One races.<ref name=Muller/>\n\n==Career==\nDuring the [[First World War]], Lauda served in the Austrian [[artillery]].<ref name=Mun/> After the war, he worked for {{ill|Veitscher|de|Veitscher Magnesitwerke}} as a commercial secretary, between 1923 and 1925.<ref name=Muller/> He then worked for ''\u00d6sterreichisch-Amerikanischen Magnesit AG''.<ref name=Mun/><ref name=Muller/> In 1937, he became the [[general manager]] of Veitscher.<ref name=Muller/><ref name=Kurier>{{cite news| url=https://kurier.at/kultur/geschichten-mit-geschichte/familie-lauda-blaues-blut-und-rotes-kapperl/400502200| title= Familie Lauda: Blaues Blut und rotes Kapperl| last=Markus| first=George| work=[[Kurier]]| date=23 May 2019| accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref> After the [[Anschluss]], Lauda was removed from his position in the company.<ref name=Muller/><ref name=Kurier/> After the [[Second World War]], Lauda was reinstated as general manager of Veitscher,<ref name=Muller/><ref name=Kurier/> and Lauda built a papermaking empire there.<ref>{{cite news| url= https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/21/obituaries/niki-lauda-dead.html| title= Niki Lauda, Formula One Champion Who Pushed Limits, Dies at 70| last=McFadden| first=Robert D.| work=[[The New York Times]]| date=21 May 2019|accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 1946, Lauda co-founded the [[Federation of Austrian Industries]] (IV), and was president of the organisation until 1960.<ref name=Muller/><ref name=IV>{{cite web| url= https://www.iv.at/de/die-iv/geschichte/die-prasidenten-der-iv-von-1946-2012| title= Die Pr\u00e4sidenten der IV von 1946 - 2012| publisher=[[Federation of Austrian Industries]]| date=2012| accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref> In 1949, he was cited in a ''[[New York Times]]'' report on the progress of the [[Marshall Plan]]. He reported that Austria would employ 20,000 former government officials.<ref>{{cite web| url= https://defence-point.com/2019/05/21/niki-lauda-dead-at-70/| title= Niki Lauda dead at 70| publisher=Defence Point| date=21 May 2019| accessdate=23 March 2019}}</ref> He served as chairman of the Association of Industrialists,<ref>{{cite book| url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=3dHVDwAAQBAJ| title=Austria in the Nineteen Fifties| last=Bischof| first=Gunter| publisher=[[Routledge]]| date=2020}}</ref><ref name=US>{{cite book| url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=BLfIebKBmigC| title= Report on Austria| publisher=United States Office of High Commissioner for Austria| date=1951|page=27}}</ref> and in 1951, he proposed a successful bill to freeze  wages, to try and counteract inflation in the country.<ref name=US/> Lauda was also a president of the [[Austrian Red Cross]],<ref name=Muller/> from 1956 to 1974.<ref name=IV/>\n\n==Relationship with Niki Lauda==\nHans Lauda was the paternal grandfather of [[Formula One]] World Champion [[Niki Lauda]].<ref name=Muller/> Aged 10, Niki accused Hans of \"double standards\" after he accepted a medal of honour from socialist mayor of Vienna Felix Slavik, someone that Hans was not fond of.<ref>{{cite book| url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=E5BYDgAAQBAJ| title=The Psychology of the Car: Automobile Admiration, Attachment, and Addiction| last=Gossling| first=Stefan| publisher=[[Elsevier]]| page=196| date=June 2017}}</ref> Hans was critical of Niki's Formula One ambitions, saying that \"A Lauda should be on the economic pages of the newspaper, not the sports pages.\"<ref>{{cite news| url= https://auto.ndtv.com/news/niki-lauda-calculative-resilient-three-time-world-champion-2041425| title= Niki Lauda: Calculative, Resilient, Three-Time World Champion| work=[[NDTV]]| date=22 May 2019| accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 1971, Hans and Niki Lauda had an argument, after Hans vetoed funding for Niki to pay for a drive in the [[1972 Formula One season]] with [[March Engineering]].<ref name=MS>{{cite magazine| url= https://www.motorsportmagazine.com/archive/article/march-2009/41/years-rat| title= The years of the Rat| last=Henry| first=Alan| magazine=[[Motor Sport (magazine)|Motor Sport]]| date=March 2009| accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref> The pair never spoke again.<ref name=Muller/><ref name=MS/> Hans Lauda died in 1974,<ref name=Muller/> shortly before Niki's first Formula One victory at the [[1974 Spanish Grand Prix]].<ref name=Muller/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lauda, Hans}}\n[[Category:Austrian industrialists]]\n[[Category:1896 births]]\n[[Category:1974 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Vienna]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Austrian industrialist}}\n{{Use British English| date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Hans Lauda\n| image         = <!-- filename only, no \"File:\" or \"Image:\" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt           = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption       = \n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1896|3|25|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[Vienna]], [[Austria-Hungary]]\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1974|1|21|1896|3|25|df=y}}\n| death_place   = Vienna, Austria\n| nationality   = Austrian\n| occupation    = Industrialist\n| years_active  = 1923-1960\n| known_for     = President of [[Federation of Austrian Industries]]\n}}\n\n'''Hans Lauda''' (25 March 1896&nbsp;\u2013 21 January 1974)<ref name=Mun/> was an Austrian industrialist who co-founded the [[Federation of Austrian Industries]] and served as president from 1946 to 1960. He was the paternal grandfather of [[Formula One]] World Champion [[Niki Lauda]].\n\n==Early life==\nHans Lauda was born on 25 March 1896 in [[Vienna]].<ref name=Mun>{{cite web| url= https://www.munzinger.de/search/portrait/Hans+Lauda/0/7284.html| title= Hans Lauda| language=de| publisher=[[Munzinger-Archiv]]| date=30 July 1956| accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref> His father {{ill|Ernst Lauda|de|Ernst Lauda (Techniker)}} worked in [[hydraulic engineering]] and bridge construction.<ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.biographien.ac.at/oebl/oebl_L/Lauda_Ernst_1859_1932.xml| title= Lauda, Ernst Ritter von (1859\u20131932), Wasserbau- und Br\u00fcckenbautechniker| language=de| publisher=[[\u00d6sterreichisches Biographisches Lexikon 1815\u20131950]]| date=1 March 2011| accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref> Lauda studied at the [[Theresianum]],<ref name=Mun/> and the [[University of Vienna]], where he earned a doctorate in law.<ref name=Mun/><ref name=Muller>{{cite book| url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121204002822/http://www.styriabooks.at/files/images/9783222132667_Leseprobe.pdf| type=pdf| title= Niki Lauda: Alles unter eine Kappe| language=de|last=M\u00fcller| first=Stefan| publisher=[[Styria Media Group]]| date=2012| pages=15-21}}</ref> He was known as \"Old Lauda\".<ref name=Muller/> He was interested in Formula One, and drove to the [[N\u00fcrburgring]] and to [[Monaco]] to watch Formula One races.<ref name=Muller/>\n\n==Career==\nDuring the [[First World War]], Lauda served in the Austrian [[artillery]].<ref name=Mun/> After the war, he worked for {{ill|Veitscher|de|Veitscher Magnesitwerke}} as a commercial secretary, between 1923 and 1925.<ref name=Muller/> He then worked for ''\u00d6sterreichisch-Amerikanischen Magnesit AG''.<ref name=Mun/><ref name=Muller/> In 1937, he became the [[general manager]] of Veitscher.<ref name=Muller/><ref name=Kurier>{{cite news| url=https://kurier.at/kultur/geschichten-mit-geschichte/familie-lauda-blaues-blut-und-rotes-kapperl/400502200| title= Familie Lauda: Blaues Blut und rotes Kapperl| last=Markus| first=George| work=[[Kurier]]| date=23 May 2019| accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref> After the [[Anschluss]], Lauda was removed from his position in the company.<ref name=Muller/><ref name=Kurier/> After the [[Second World War]], Lauda was reinstated as general manager of Veitscher,<ref name=Muller/><ref name=Kurier/> and Lauda built a papermaking empire there.<ref>{{cite news| url= https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/21/obituaries/niki-lauda-dead.html| title= Niki Lauda, Formula One Champion Who Pushed Limits, Dies at 70| last=McFadden| first=Robert D.| work=[[The New York Times]]| date=21 May 2019|accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 1946, Lauda co-founded the [[Federation of Austrian Industries]] (IV), and was president of the organisation until 1960.<ref name=Muller/><ref name=IV>{{cite web| url= https://www.iv.at/de/die-iv/geschichte/die-prasidenten-der-iv-von-1946-2012| title= Die Pr\u00e4sidenten der IV von 1946 - 2012| publisher=[[Federation of Austrian Industries]]| date=2012| accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref> In 1949, he was cited in a ''[[New York Times]]'' report on the progress of the [[Marshall Plan]]. He reported that Austria would employ 20,000 former government officials.<ref>{{cite web| url= https://defence-point.com/2019/05/21/niki-lauda-dead-at-70/| title= Niki Lauda dead at 70| publisher=Defence Point| date=21 May 2019| accessdate=23 March 2019}}</ref> He served as chairman of the Association of Industrialists,<ref>{{cite book| url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=3dHVDwAAQBAJ| title=Austria in the Nineteen Fifties| last=Bischof| first=Gunter| publisher=[[Routledge]]| date=2020}}</ref><ref name=US>{{cite book| url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=BLfIebKBmigC| title= Report on Austria| publisher=United States Office of High Commissioner for Austria| date=1951|page=27}}</ref> and in 1951, he proposed a successful bill to freeze  wages, to try and counteract inflation in the country.<ref name=US/> Lauda was also a president of the [[Austrian Red Cross]],<ref name=Muller/> from 1956 to 1974.<ref name=IV/>\n\n==Relationship with Niki Lauda==\nHans Lauda was the paternal grandfather of [[Formula One]] World Champion [[Niki Lauda]].<ref name=Muller/> Aged 10, Niki accused Hans of \"double standards\" after he accepted a medal of honour from socialist mayor of Vienna Felix Slavik, someone that Hans was not fond of.<ref>{{cite book| url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=E5BYDgAAQBAJ| title=The Psychology of the Car: Automobile Admiration, Attachment, and Addiction| last=Gossling| first=Stefan| publisher=[[Elsevier]]| page=196| date=June 2017}}</ref> Hans was critical of Niki's Formula One ambitions, saying that \"A Lauda should be on the economic pages of the newspaper, not the sports pages.\"<ref>{{cite news| url= https://auto.ndtv.com/news/niki-lauda-calculative-resilient-three-time-world-champion-2041425| title= Niki Lauda: Calculative, Resilient, Three-Time World Champion| work=[[NDTV]]| date=22 May 2019| accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 1971, Hans and Niki Lauda had an argument, after Hans vetoed funding for Niki to pay for a drive in the [[1972 Formula One season]] with [[March Engineering]].<ref name=MS>{{cite magazine| url= https://www.motorsportmagazine.com/archive/article/march-2009/41/years-rat| title= The years of the Rat| last=Henry| first=Alan| magazine=[[Motor Sport (magazine)|Motor Sport]]| date=March 2009| accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref> The pair never spoke again.<ref name=Muller/><ref name=MS/> Hans Lauda died in 1974,<ref name=Muller/> shortly before Niki's first Formula One victory at the [[1974 Spanish Grand Prix]].<ref name=Muller/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lauda, Hans}}\n[[Category:Austrian industrialists]]\n[[Category:1896 births]]\n[[Category:1974 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Vienna]]\n", "name_user": "GiantSnowman", "label": "safe", "comment": "date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript| Cleaned up usingAutoEd", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hans_Lauda"}
{"title_page": "George Dudley", "text_new": "{{For|the American art director|George Dudley (art director)}}\n{{Short description|Canadian ice hockey administrator}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = George Dudley\n| image       = George Dudley photo at Hockey Hall of Fame.jpg\n| image_upright = 0.8\n| alt         = Black and white of George Dudley dressed in a suit and tie\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|1894|04|19}}\n| birth_place = [[Midland, Ontario]], Canada\n| death_date  = {{Death date and age|1960|05|08|1894|04|19}}\n| death_place = Midland, Ontario, Canada\n| alma_mater  = [[Osgoode Hall Law School]]\n| occupation  = Lawyer, solicitor\n| known_for   = {{hlist|[[Canadian Amateur Hockey Association]]|[[Ontario Hockey Association]]|[[International Ice Hockey Federation]]|[[International Ice Hockey Association]]}}\n| awards      = [[Hockey Hall of Fame]]\n| honours     = [[Dudley Hewitt Cup]]\n}}\n\n'''George Samuel Dudley''' {{Post-nominals|country=CAN|QC}} (April 19, 1894 \u2013 May 8, 1960) was a Canadian [[ice hockey]] administrator. He joined the [[Ontario Hockey Association]] (OHA) executive in 1928, served as its president from 1934 to 1936, and as its secretary-treasurer from 1936 to 1960. He was elected to [[Canadian Amateur Hockey Association]] (CAHA) executive in 1936, served as its president from 1940 to 1942, as its secretary from 1945 to 1947, and as its secretary-manager from 1947 to 1960. He was secretary of the [[International Ice Hockey Association]] from 1945 to 1947, and was later vice-president of the [[International Ice Hockey Federation]] (IIHF) from 1957 to 1960. He was expected to become the next president of the IIHF before his death. He graduated from [[Osgoode Hall Law School]] in 1917 then practiced law for 43 years as the town [[solicitor]] for [[Midland, Ontario]].\n\nDudley and [[W. G. Hardy]] led the way in revising the definition of an amateur hockey player to keep amateur players in Canada and slow the number of Canadians turning professional. Dudley negotiated deals with the [[National Hockey League]] and the [[Ice Hockey UK|British Ice Hockey Association]] to govern the transfer of players internationally. He introduced contracts for [[junior ice hockey]] players, as a means to obtain development payments from professional teams seeking new talent. He supported an alliance between the CAHA and the [[USA Hockey|Amateur Hockey Association of the United States]] (AHAUS), and sought for international recognition of AHAUS as the governing body of ice hockey in the United States. He threatened to withdraw Canada from [[ice hockey at the Olympic Games]] if the [[International Olympic Committee]] did not accept the Canadian definition of amateur, and supported the IIHF hosting its own [[Ice Hockey World Championships]] separate from the Olympics. Dudley's role as secretary-manager of the CAHA made him influential in Canadian hockey since he served as the regular delegate to IIHF meetings, and was in charge of selecting the [[Canada men's national ice hockey team|Canada men's national team]]. He facilitated the first exhibition tour by the [[Soviet Union national ice hockey team|Soviet Union national team]] in Canada, and oversaw [[ice hockey at the 1960 Winter Olympics]] on behalf of the IIHF\n\nDudley was committed to implementing reforms for amateur hockey, believing that they were in the best interest of hockey in Canada. He was opposed to governments funding or controlling amateur sports associations, and supported the continuation of hockey and incorporating [[Royal Canadian Air Force]] teams into the CAHA as a morale boost during [[World War II]]. Dudley was described by Journalist Jack Sullivan as a staunch and shrewd hockey official and a problem solver. Canadian journalist [[Scott Young (writer)|Scott Young]] stated Dudley was a low-key figure at first who grew to prominence by his reputation as being a busy and able volunteer. Young further stated that Dudley was a forward thinker, and had the ability to listen to a conversation and find a compromise without forcing anyone to change his mind. Young credited Dudley for dealing with reforms to amateurism, and regulations on player salaries and transfers, which led to increased interest in hockey.\n\nDudley was inducted to the builder category of the [[Hockey Hall of Fame]] in 1958, and was posthumously inducted into the Midland Sports Hall of Fame in 1996. He was made a life member of both the CAHA and OHA, received the Gold Stick award from the OHA in recognition of service to hockey in Ontario and the AHAUS citation award for service to amateur hockey in the United States. He was named to the selection committee for the Hockey Hall of Fame, and previously sat on the same committee for the [[Original Hockey Hall of Fame]]. He and [[W. A. Hewitt]] were made the namesakes of the [[Dudley Hewitt Cup]], first awarded by the [[Canadian Junior Hockey League]] in 1971.\n\n==Early life and legal career==\n[[File:Historic building in downtown Toronto on an early snowy morning. Ontario courthouse. (25129051345).jpg|thumb|Osgoode Hall Law School in Toronto|alt=Osgoode Hall building]]\n\nGeorge Samuel Dudley was born on April 19, 1894, in [[Midland, Ontario]].<ref name=\"Legends\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hhof.com/LegendsOfHockey/jsp/LegendsMember.jsp?list=ByName&page=bio&mem=B195801|title=Dudley, George \u2013 Biography \u2013 Honoured Builder|website=Legends of Hockey|access-date=February 15, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"elitepro\">{{cite web|url=https://www.eliteprospects.com/staff/39590/george-dudley|title=George Dudley Team Staff Profile|website=Elite Prospects|access-date=February 15, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Ferguson\">''Ferguson, Bob (2005)'', p. 119</ref> His parents were William Thomas Dudley, and Sarah Agnes Dudley (n\u00e9e Brown).<ref name=\"NSGS\">''North Simcoe Geneaology Society (2006)'', pp. 404\u2013405</ref> His father served 37 years on the local [[public utilities commission]].<ref name=\"FreePress-p11\">{{cite news|title=Town solicitor 43 years George Dudley stricken|date=May 11, 1960|newspaper=Midland Free Press|location=Midland, Ontario|page=11}}</ref> Dudley grew up playing [[minor ice hockey]] in Midland,<ref name=\"Ferguson\" /><ref name=\"MOSHOF\">{{cite web|url=https://www.midlandonsportshalloffame.com/portfolio_page/george-s-dudley-qc|title=George S. Dudley QC. (Mr. Hockey) Midland Sports Hall of Fame 1894-1960|year=2015|website=Midland Ontario Sports Hall of Fame|access-date=February 1, 2020}}</ref> but poor eyesight prevented him from a further athletic career.<ref name=\"FreePress-p11\" />\n\nDudley attended [[Georgian Bay District Secondary School|Midland Secondary School]], then graduated from [[Osgoode Hall Law School]] in 1917. While studying law, he served as an [[articled clerk]] for [[William Humphrey Bennett]], the [[Member of Parliament (Canada)|Member of Parliament]] of [[Simcoe East]]. Dudley entered into a law practice in a partnership with [[William Finlayson (Canadian politician)|William Finlayson]] in 1917.<ref name=\"FreePress-p11\" /> They established at Finlayson & Dudley, Barristers and Solicitors at 212 King Street in Midland.<ref>{{cite book|title=Town of Midland Directory|publisher=Vernon Directories Limited|date=1933|location=Midland, Ontario|pages=129, 174, 186}}</ref> Dudley took over the firm upon Finlayson's death in 1943.<ref name=\"FreePress-p11\" /> He practiced law for 43 years as the town's [[solicitor]] until 1960.<ref name=\"CP-obit\">{{cite news|title=Dudley's Death Blow To Hockey|author=[[The Canadian Press]]|date=May 11, 1960|newspaper=[[The Chronicle-Journal|Daily Times-Journal]]|location=Fort William, Ontario|page=8}}</ref><ref name=\"FreePress-p12\">{{cite news|title=Town solicitor 43 years George Dudley stricken (continued)|date=May 11, 1960|newspaper=Midland Free Press|location=Midland, Ontario|page=12}}</ref>\n\n==Early hockey career==\nDudley first attended [[Ontario Hockey Association]] (OHA) meetings in 1925.<ref name=\"Young-p157\">''Young, Scott (1989)'', p. 157</ref> He was elected an executive member of the OHA in November 1928, and urged the OHA to reassert its jurisdiction over all hockey in Ontario and its intention to introduce associate memberships to regulate leagues under its domain.<ref>{{cite news|title=Establish University Scholarship for Hockey Players, O.H.A. Annual|date=November 24, 1928|newspaper=Lethbridge Herald|location=Lethbridge, Alberta|page=3|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-nov-24-1928-1526336/}}{{free access}}</ref> He was an early advocate of professional [[Coach (ice hockey)|hockey coaches]] in the amateur game, and supported the reforms by [[W. A. Hewitt]] to allow them.<ref>''Young, Scott (1989)'', pp. 159\u2013161</ref>\n\nAt the OHA general meeting in 1930, Dudley supported measures to bring attention to rules already in place which did not allow players with an active professional contract in the OHA.<ref name=\"Young-p172\">''Young, Scott (1989)'', p. 172</ref> He successfully campaigned for the construction of a new arena in Midland in 1931, to replace the previous structure lost in 1926.<ref name=\"MOSHOF\" /> Dudley oversaw construction of the Midland Arena Gardens by autumn 1931 during the [[Great Depression]], and it became the only artificial [[ice rink]] between [[Toronto]] and [[Winnipeg]] at the time.<ref name=\"MOSHOF\" />\n\n==OHA president==\n[[File:Olympia Eissportzentrum Garmisch Partenkirchen.jpg|thumb|Dudley pushed for a new definition of amateur, in the wake of Canada not winning the gold medal in ice hockey at the 1936 Winter Olympics hosted in [[Garmisch-Partenkirchen]] ''(Olympic ice sport centre pictured)''.|alt=Olympic Ice Sport Centre in Garmisch Partenkirchen]]\n\nDudley served as president of the OHA from 1934 to 1936.<ref name=\"MOSHOF\" /><ref>''Young, Scott (1989)'', p. 348</ref> In 1934, he advocated for ratification of the first [[Canadian Amateur Hockey Association]] (CAHA) agreement with the [[National Hockey League]] (NHL), regarding player control and compensation to the junior clubs for developing the player. To gain the financial concessions, the CAHA conceded to allow [[Checking (ice hockey)|body checking]] in the neutral zone, and use the same [[ice hockey rules]] as the professional league.<ref>''Young, Scott (1989)'', p. 236</ref> Dudley later introduced a motion at the OHA general meeting to adopt the same playing rules as the NHL.<ref>{{cite news|title=Pro Rules For O.H.A. Planned|date=November 26, 1936|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=16|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-nov-26-1936-1545903/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nAt the CAHA general meeting in 1935, Dudley stated it was important to keep younger players amateurs as long as possible, and prevent professionalism at a young age which excluded them from the OHA. He felt that once a player reached age 21, he would have gained the knowledge to make an informed decision on his future.<ref name=\"Ellison\">''Ellison & Anderson (2018)'', pp. 115\u2013116</ref> Dudley felt that OHA needed to be offer financial opportunities competitive with what was available elsewhere.<ref>''Young, Scott (1989)'', p. 188</ref> He was nominated by CAHA president [[E. A. Gilroy]], to be part of a special committee dealing with the [[Amateur Athletic Union of Canada]] (AAU of C) to discuss the definition of amateur, the cost of player registration cards, and the right for the CAHA to issue its own registration cards.<ref>{{cite news|title=C.A.H.A. To Meet A.A.U.|date=April 13, 1935|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=27|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-apr-13-1935-1545717/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nIn October 1935, Dudley stated that the number of players leaving for the United States was compromising rosters in Canada, and that the rate of exodus was not sustainable. He decreed that the OHA would decline all player transfer requests to the United States, and players not returning to Canada by November 15, would be suspended from the OHA.<ref>{{cite news|title=O.H.A. Rejects Transfers To United States Clubs|date=October 30, 1935|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=14|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-oct-30-1935-1545725/}}{{free access}}</ref> He began to put rules in place for the transfer of players internationally, and stated that, \"It's going to happen. We might as well try to regulate it\". Dudley and CAHA second vice-president [[W. G. Hardy]] negotiated agreements with the NHL, and the [[Ice Hockey UK|British Ice Hockey Association]] (BIHA) to govern the transfer of players and prevent the raiding of Canadian rosters. Limits were placed on the number of allowed transfers, and the organizations agreed to recognize each other's authority and suspensions.<ref name=\"Young-p191\">''Young, Scott (1989)'', p. 191</ref> \n\nDudley and Hardy soon began a campaign to rewrite the definition of amateur, to decrease the number of amateurs from turning professional.<ref>''Young, Scott (1989)'', p. 182</ref> They felt that the requirement to have an AAU of C registration card to play in the OHA, and the Olympic Games, was an obstacle to progress, and made the AAU of C their main target of reforms.<ref name=\"Young-p189\">''Young, Scott (1989)'', p. 189</ref> At the AAU of C general meeting in November 1935, Dudley supported a defeated resolution to drop the word amateur from the AAU of C name.<ref>{{cite news|title=Delegates At Annual Meeting Unanimously Defeat Proposal|last=Merkel|first=Arthur|date=November 22, 1935|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=17|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-nov-22-1935-1545728/}}{{free access}}</ref> At the same meeting, Dudley and Hardy presented \"four points\" to update the definition of amateur, as supported by the CAHA's special committee dealing with the AAU of C.<ref name=\"Young-p190\">''Young, Scott (1989)'', p. 190</ref>  \n\nThe \"four points\" were:<ref name=\"apr-11-1936-part1\" /><ref>''Young, Scott (1989)'', pp. 189\u2013190</ref>\n# Hockey players may capitalize on their ability as hockey players for the purpose of obtaining legitimate employment. \n# Hockey players may accept from their clubs or employers payment for time lost, from work while competing on behalf of their clubs. They will not however, be allowed to hold \"shadow\" jobs under the clause.\n# Amateur hockey teams may play exhibition games against professional teams under such conditions as may be laid down by the individual branches of the CAHA. \n# Professionals in another sport will be allowed to play under the CAHA jurisdiction as amateurs.\n\nThe AAU of C promptly voted down the proposals. At the same meeting, the AAU of C decided upon Canada's representation in [[ice hockey at the 1936 Winter Olympics]]. The [[1935 Allan Cup]] champion [[Halifax Wolverines]] were unable to go, unless financial provisions were made for their families. Since the AAU of C did not condone payment for lost wages while away at competitions, the Allan Cup finalists [[Port Arthur Bearcats]] were chosen. Canada failed to win the Olympic gold medal due to a loss to the [[Great Britain men's national ice hockey team|Great Britain men's national team]].<ref name=\"Young-p190\">''Young, Scott (1989)'', p. 190</ref> Dudley stated that the CAHA should face realities, and that the Canadian public was sympathetic to compensating and supporting its Olympic ice hockey players while overseas.<ref name=\"apr-11-1936-part2\">{{cite news|title=Sweeping Proposals Would End Alliance|date=April 11, 1936|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=29|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-apr-11-1936-1545858/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nAt the 1936 CAHA general meeting, Dudley and Hardy presented the four points, which were adopted by the CAHA. In doing so, the CAHA took its stand against the definition of amateurism, and recognized that players should receive compensation. The stand meant the likelihood of breaking ties with the AAU of C. The ''[[Winnipeg Tribune]]'' reported that support for the \"four points\" was strong, and that the \"old guard\" of amateurism supported by AAU of C president [[W. A. Fry]] would eventually lose.<ref name=\"apr-11-1936-part1\">{{cite news|title=Sweeping Proposals, If Ratified, Would End A.A.U. Alliance|date=April 11, 1936|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=27|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-apr-11-1936-1545857/}}{{free access}}</ref> Dudley stated that common sense had not prevailed in previous AAU of C discussions on the matter. Fry stated that the decision was \"the most important matter ever to come before an amateur body in Canada\", and that \"It would be a sorry day for the AAU of C should it split with its strongest supporter, the CAHA. As a former CAHA president, he sympathized with the resolution, but did not give approval.<ref name=\"apr-11-1936-part2\" />\n\n==CAHA second vice-president==\n[[File:Maple Leaf Gardens 2016.jpg|thumb|Maple Leaf Gardens hosted many hockey matches scheduled by Dudley.|alt=Exterior of Maple Leaf Gardens]]\n\nDudley was elected second vice-president of the CAHA in April 1936.<ref>''Canadian Amateur Hockey Association (1990)'', p. 127</ref> The CAHA decided to go ahead with reforms to the definition of amateur regardless of the outcome of an AAU of C mail-in vote on the matter. In May 1936, Fry decided against holding AAU of C vote on the matter, which led to Dudley referring to Fry as \"Somersault Bill\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Fry Resents \"Somersault Bill\" As Name|last=Dulmage|first=Elmer|date=May 7, 1936|newspaper=Lethbridge Herald|location=Lethbridge, Alberta|page=12|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-may-07-1936-1545872/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nDudley became treasurer of the OHA upon the death of [[John F. Paxton]] on May 12, 1936.<ref>''Young, Scott (1989)'', p. 187</ref> \nFrom 1936 to 1960, he functioned as OHA's secretary-treasurer, in addition to his roles with the CAHA.<ref name=\"Legends\" /><ref name=\"MOSHOF\" /> He reported an operating loss of [[Canadian dollar|C$5]],662 in 1936, due to increased expenses and decreased revenue, after the OHA had experienced many years with a surplus.<ref>''Young, Scott (1989)'', pp. 187\u2013188</ref>\n\nDudley and Hardy presented the \"four points\" again at the 1936 AAU of C general meeting. Dudley and Hardy advocated for broken time payments, since players were reliant on income to support their families, and that being away from work for six weeks at a time for international competition or national playoffs constituted a hardship.<ref name=\"nov-20-1936\">{{cite news|title=Pro. Vs. Amateur Games Approved If Exhibition|date=November 20, 1936|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=1|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-nov-20-1936-1545878/}}{{free access}}</ref> They were committed to change believing that the reforms were in the best interest of hockey in Canada, and were empowered the CAHA executive to act as it saw fit on the matter.<ref>{{cite news|title=Secession Of Hockey, Lacrosse, Basketball From A.A.U. Fold Seen|last=Allen|first=Ralph|date=November 21, 1936|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=25|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-nov-21-1936-1545894/}}{{free access}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Amateur Meeting|last=Allen|first=Ralph|date=November 21, 1936|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=27|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-nov-21-1936-1545896/}}{{free access}}</ref> Journalist [[Ralph Allen (journalist)|Ralph Allen]] stated that public opinion had turned in favour of the proposals, and that the AAU of C were relics of a bygone age.<ref name=\"Young-p190\" /> The AAU of C voted and approved exhibition games between amateurs and professionals, but rejected the other three points.<ref name=\"nov-20-1936\" /> The CAHA status within the AAU of C was left unclear.<ref>{{cite news|title=Jack Hamilton, Regina, Is Named A.A.U. Of C. Leader|last=Edwards|first=Charles|date=November 23, 1936|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=17|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-nov-23-1936-1545899/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nDudley was re-elected second vice-president of the CAHA at the general meeting in April 1937.<ref>{{cite news|title=Cecil Duncan Is Re-elected Head At C.A.H.A. Meet|date=April 21, 1937|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=3 |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-apr-21-1937-1545908/}}{{free access}}</ref> Dudley along with CAHA president [[Cecil Duncan]] and W. A. Hewitt participated in negotiations with the [[Eastern Hockey League|Eastern Amateur Hockey League]] (EAHL) represented by [[Tommy Lockhart]] in August 1937, a result of the [[Amateur Athletic Union]] (AAU) of the United States giving an ultimatum to the EAHL not to have any Canadian players. The EAHL chose to break away from the AAU, similar to the CAHA relationship with the AAU of C, and reached an agreement with the CAHA which limited the number of Canadian players transferring to the league.<ref>{{cite news|title=Eastern U.S. Puck Loops Quits A.A.U.|date=August 31, 1937|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=36|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-aug-31-1937-1545914/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nIn November 1937, Dudley reported that the OHA had returned to a surplus, with an operating profit of $1,422, led by playoffs tickets for the [[Memorial Cup]] playoffs. Dudley signed a five-year agreement with [[Maple Leaf Gardens]] to be the home rink for all Toronto-based teams in the OHA, except for the [[University of Toronto]] teams playing at [[Varsity Arena]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Sign Five-Year Contract With Gardens|date=November 22, 1937|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=17|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-nov-22-1937-1545916/}}{{free access}}</ref> In March 1938, Dudley and W. A. Hewitt met with [[Frank Calder]] to discuss the professional-amateur player agreement with the NHL, in response to a protest over a suspended professional player being placed on an amateur roster.<ref>{{cite news|title=Amateur Solons Will Meet Calder|date=March 3, 1938|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=14|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-mar-03-1938-1545921/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\n==CAHA first vice-president==\n[[File:Drawing Room, Royal Alexandra Hotel, Winnipeg (HS85-10-18226).jpg|thumb|The CAHA's silver jubilee in 1939, was hosted at the Royal Alexandra Hotel ''(drawing room pictured)'' in Winnipeg.|alt=Black and white photo of the drawing Room at the Royal Alexandra Hotel, Winnipeg]]\n\nOn April 18, 1938, Dudley was elected first vice-president of the CAHA. He credited the outgoing president Cecil Duncan for replenishing CAHA financial reserves with more success that his predecessors.<ref>{{cite news|title=New Executive Strength Gives West Louder Voice In Amateur Ice Affairs|date=April 18, 1938|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=14 |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-apr-18-1938-1545933/}}{{free access}}</ref> Dudley was placed in charge of [[Eastern Canada]] playoffs,<ref>{{cite news|title=Changes Announced In Senior Puck Dates|date=March 11, 1939|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=24|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-mar-11-1939-1545942/}}{{free access}}</ref> and appointed chairman of the CAHA resolutions committee.<ref>{{cite news|title=Past Presidents Headline C.A.H.A. Meeting|date=April 11, 1939|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=16|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-apr-11-1939-1545948/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nIn August 1938, he participated in CAHA negotiations with the NHL and Frank Calder to reach a new professional-amateur agreement. Agreements were made on playing rules and recognition of each other's suspensions. The CAHA would disallow international transfers for players on NHL reserve lists, and the NHL agreed not to sign any junior players during active CAHA competition, or without consent of the CAHA club.<ref>{{cite news|title=C.A.H.A. To Deny International Transfers To Amateurs Eyed By National Leaguers|date=August 15, 1938|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=12|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-aug-15-1938-1545937/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nThe CAHA's silver jubilee in 1939, was hosted at the [[Royal Alexandra Hotel]] in Winnipeg. Dudley gave the introductory goodwill [[Toast (honor)|toast]].<ref>{{cite news|title=C.A.H.A. Eulogized at 25th Annual Banquet|date=April 11, 1939|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=16|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-apr-11-1939-1545949/}}{{free access}}</ref> At the general meeting which followed, he presented a resolution to have contracts for [[junior ice hockey]] players.<ref name=\"apr-12-1939\">{{cite news|title=C.A.H.A. Approves Player-Club Tie|date=April 12, 1939|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=15|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-apr-12-1939-1545955/}}{{free access}}</ref> He felt that if a club team had a contract with a player, then it had a legal course of action to request remuneration by way of development fees if the player was signed to a professional team. Lengthy discussion ensued and the idea was approved in principle with a final decision deferred until the 1940 general meeting. Contracts had the added benefit of making professional teams negotiate for amateur services. A signing fee of $500 was proposed, which would be dispersed among the amateur clubs which has developed the player.<ref name=\"apr-12-1939\" />\n\nDudley re-elected first vice-president of the CAHA, on April 12, 1939.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hardy Returned C.A.H.A. Prexy|date=April 12, 1939|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=1|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-apr-12-1939-1545957/}}{{free access}}</ref> In November 1939, he expected changes would be made in the playoff structure and compensation of teams for travel, since the financial situations of the CAHA and OHA had improved since the Great Depression.<ref>{{cite news|title=C.A.H.A. Salts Away $55,000|date=November 27, 1939|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=11|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-nov-27-1939-1545963/}}{{free access}}</ref> In December 1939, he acted as a goodwill emissary to assist the growth of the [[Ladies Ontario Hockey Association]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Girls' Hockey In Durham?|date=December 21, 1939|newspaper=Durham Review|location=Durham, Ontario|page=1|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-dec-21-1939-1545962/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\n==CAHA president==\n===First term===\n[[File:Feature. Red Cross Prisonners of War PKGS BAnQ P48S1P07948.jpg|thumb|Canadian Red Cross volunteers during World War II.|alt=Canadian Red Cross volunteers]]\n\nOn April 15, 1940, the CAHA and the [[USA Hockey|Amateur Hockey Association of the United States]] (AHAUS) agreed to form the [[International Ice Hockey Association]], and invited the BIHA to join. W. G. Hardy became president of the association, and stated that \"the purpose of the new association is to promote the game of hockey among the three [[Anglo-Saxons|Anglo-Saxon]] nations\".<ref>{{cite news|title=New Controlling Body Formed At C.A.H.A. Meet|last=Clarke|first=Robert|date=April 16, 1940|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=15|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-apr-16-1940-1471642/}}{{free access}}</ref> The new organization replaced the [[International Ice Hockey Federation|Ligue Internationale de Hockey sur Glace]] (LIHG) which was inactive due to [[World War II]]. Dudley succeeded Hardy as president of the CAHA on April 17, 1940.<ref>{{cite news|title=Juggling Allan Cup Games When Complaints Made|date=April 17, 1940|newspaper=Brandon Daily Sun|location=Brandon, Manitoba|page=4 |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-apr-17-1940-1546893/}}{{free access}}</ref> After Dudley became president, the CAHA definition of amateur was changed to \"an amateur hockey player is one who has not engaged in, or is not engaged in, organized professional hockey\". The question of whether the [[International Olympic Committee]] (IOC) would accept the new definition, was postponed when the [[1940 Winter Olympics]] were cancelled. Dudley later stated, \"If the Olympics are revived after the war, Canada will want to send a team, of course. But if our rules prove unacceptable to Olympic officials, I guess we'll stay at home\".<ref>''Young, Scott (1989)'', p. 192</ref> The decision was the first of several times that Canada threatened to withdraw from [[ice hockey at the Olympic Games]] or the [[Ice Hockey World Championships]] over regulations on international ice hockey.<ref name=\"Young-p157\" />\n\nIn June 1940, the CAHA executive approved a grant of $10,000 to the [[Government of Canada]] for the war effort. The CAHA chose to continue operations as usual to maintain the morale of Canadians during the war, and would offer any assistance needed for military sports teams.<ref>{{cite news|title=C.A.H.A. Votes $10,000 For War Effort|date=June 20, 1940|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=17|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jun-20-1940-1546903/}}{{free access}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=C.A.H.A. Will Give $10,000 to Aid Canada War Effort|date=June 20, 1940|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=17|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jun-20-1940-1471663/}}{{free access}}</ref> Dudley asked for provincial branches of the CAHA to assist in organizing a national \"hockey night\" to raise funds for patriotic services.<ref>{{cite news|title=Inter-Provincial Set-Up Approved B.C. Hockey Body|date=November 11, 1940|newspaper=Lethbridge Herald|location=Lethbridge, Alberta|page=9|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-nov-11-1940-1546921/}}{{free access}}</ref> He later abandoned plans to benefit the [[Canadian Red Cross]], since it was against Red Cross policy to do promotional work.<ref>{{cite news|title=C.A.H.A. Stops Red Cross Plans|date=January 1, 1941|newspaper=Winnipeg, Manitoba|location=|page=11|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jan-01-1941-1548591/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nIn September 1940, the International Ice Hockey Association and the NHL reached a new professional-amateur agreement. The NHL promised to pay $500 for each amateur player signed, which included $250 at signing, then another $250 after playing in the NHL. Dudley sat on the committee to oversee relations and player movement with the NHL. The agreement included provisions for tryouts without having to commit, and the reinstatement of a former professional player as an amateur if no professional team claimed him.<ref>{{cite news|title=N.H.L. and C.A.H.A. Settle Amateur Feud|date=September 13, 1940|newspaper=Medicine Hat News|location=Medicine Hat, Alberta|page=3|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-sep-13-1940-1546907/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nDudley stated at the CAHA executive meeting in January 1941, called for more consistent interpretation of the playing rules with respect to physical play, which was one of the biggest problems facing amateur hockey in Canada.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hockey Heads Gather For Convention|date=January 3, 1941|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=13 |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jan-03-1941-1548592/}}{{free access}}</ref> He also stressed that supporting the International Ice Hockey Association was a means to protect the CAHA against the positions of other organizations.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rules, Playdowns Discussed At C.A.H.A. Meeting|date=January 4, 1941|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=21|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jan-04-1941-1548593/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nThe 1941 CAHA annual meeting was held in [[Calgary]], in conjunction with the International Ice Hockey Association.<ref>{{cite news|title=C.A.H.A. Begins Annual Meeting In Calgary|date=April 12, 1941|newspaper=Lethbridge Herald|location=Lethbridge, Alberta|page=16|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-apr-12-1941-1548597/}}{{free access}}</ref> The constitution was updated to allow for charitable donations and educational grants, and the CAHA to donate 25 per cent of profits from playoffs to wartime charities. Dudley arranged for bonuses to players from the playoffs profits based on the number of games played. Dudley was granted a $1,000 honorarium for expenses for negotiating agreements with the NHL.<ref>{{cite news|title=Set Time Limits For Replacements|date=April 15, 1941|newspaper=Lethbridge Herald|location=Lethbridge, Alberta|page=10|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-apr-15-1941-1548598/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\n===Second term===\n[[File:Allan Cup.jpg|thumb|Dudley donated a portion of profits from the Allan Cup playoffs (''trophy pictured'') to the Government of Canada for the war effort.|alt=Allan Cup trophy]]\n\nDudley was re-elected president of the CAHA on April 16, 1941.<ref>{{cite news|title=Officers Of C.A.H.A. Re-elected|date=April 16, 1941|newspaper=Lethbridge Herald|location=Lethbridge, Alberta|page=18|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-apr-16-1941-1548599/}}{{free access}}</ref> He and Hardy met with officials from the [[Hockey Qu\u00e9bec|Quebec Amateur Hockey Association]] (QAHA) in June 1941, to approve in principle a new playoff scheme overseen by a new committee for the QAHA, the [[Hockey Eastern Ontario|Ottawa District Hockey Association]], and the [[Maritime Amateur Hockey Association]]. The new committee was proposed to be more financially efficient, give more money to Eastern teams, and to be voted on at the next general meeting.<ref>{{cite news|title=C.A.H.A. Says Okay to New Branch|date=June 9, 1941|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=17|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jun-09-1941-1548607/}}{{free access}}</ref> \n\nThe CAHA executive approved a $10,000 purchase of [[Canada Savings Bond|Victory Bonds]] for the war effort.<ref>{{cite news|title=C.A.H.A. Buys Bonds|date=June 13, 1941|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=17 |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jun-13-1941-1548608/}}{{free access}}</ref> Dudley reiterated that the CAHA would assist the Canadian government where possible, and would bend the agreement with the NHL to allow for younger players to be signed who were not subject to travel restrictions or military service.<ref>{{cite news|title=LaFleche Receives Puckmen|date=September 27, 1941|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=25|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-sep-27-1941-1548611/}}{{free access}}</ref> \n\nWhen NHL players were denied passports, the CAHA asked for permission from the NHL reinstate those players temporarily as amateurs.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ask Temporary Re-Instatement|date=September 27, 1941|newspaper=Medicine Hat Daily News|location=Medicine Hat, Alberta|page=9|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-sep-27-1941-1548610/}}{{free access}}</ref> Dudley advised those who wanted to be reinstated as amateurs due to travel restrictions, needed a release from the NHL.<ref>{{cite news|title=Pros. Must Take Reinstatment Cases To Calder|date=November 6, 1941|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=18|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-nov-06-1941-1548621/}}{{free access}}</ref> The CAHA rules committee formally ratified the NHL rules for use in Canadian amateur leagues, as of October 1941.<ref>{{cite news|title=C.A.H.A. Ratifies N.H.L. Playing Rules|date=October 20, 1941|newspaper=Lethbridge Herald|location=Lethbridge, Alberta|page=10|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-oct-20-1941-1548613/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nDudley estimated that registration in the CAHA was 25 per cent less than before the war, but stated that the Canadian government still supported the continuation of hockey as a morale boost.<ref>{{cite news|title=C.A.H.A. Plans To Carry On, States Dudley|date=January 9, 1942|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=5 |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jan-09-1942-1551432/}}{{free access}}</ref> He urged for clubs in Canada to have special games to raise funds for war organizations, and for the CAHA branches to incorporate military teams into schedules where possible. In January 1942, the CAHA donated an additional $10,000 to the government for the war effort.<ref>{{cite news|title=Memorial Cup Final Here If Manitoba Wins Western Junior Puck Crown|date=January 12, 1942|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=12 |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jan-12-1942-1551462/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nDudley anticipated a greater demand by the NHL for junior players due to the war, and wished to co-operate.<ref name=\"apr-20-1942\">{{cite news|title=Hockey Association Adopts Wartime Economy Programme|date=April 20, 1942|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=15|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-apr-20-1942-1552272/}}{{free access}}</ref> He expected difficulty in operating [[senior ice hockey]] next season, and speculated that season schedules and playoffs may need to be shortened due to lack of players, but was committed to continuing hockey.<ref>{{cite news|title=War Will Smack Seniors Next Year|date=March 26, 1942|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=14|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-mar-26-1942-1551498/}}{{free access}}</ref> He defended the CAHA policy of reinstating former professionals as amateurs, despite it strengthening [[Royal Canadian Air Force]] (RCAF) teams compared to club teams during the wartime.<ref>{{cite news|title=George Dudley Answers Critics|date=March 28, 1942|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=22 |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-mar-28-1942-1552173/}}{{free access}}</ref> During the war he stated, \"young men capable of playing hockey are capable of either being in the armed services or in some necessary industry\".<ref>{{cite news|title=No More Pay-For-Play Puck Chasing|date=April 17, 1942|newspaper=Lethbridge Herald|location=Lethbridge, Alberta|page=3|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-apr-17-1942-1552230/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nBy April 1942, the CAHA and its branches combined donated over $50,000 to the war effort, which included proceeds from [[Allan Cup]] and Memorial Cup playoffs, and exhibition games.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hockey's Aid To War Effort Over $50,000|date=April 20, 1942|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=7|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-apr-20-1942-1552270/}}{{free access}}</ref> To save money, the CAHA reduced travel and hospital allowances, and eliminated playoffs series which would not be profitable.<ref name=\"apr-20-1942\" />\n\n==CAHA past-president==\n[[File:Memorial Cup at the 2015 championship.jpg|thumb|Dudley served as a trustee of the Memorial Cup after he was CAHA president.<ref name=\"Legends\" />|alt=The Memorial Cup trophy]]\n\nDudley assumed the role of CAHA past-president, when he was succeeded by [[Frank F. Sargent]] as president in April 1942.<ref name=\"CAHA-p117\">''Canadian Amateur Hockey Association (1990)'', p. 117</ref> Dudley sat on the relations committee with the NHL, which agreed in principle that an amateur may turn professional at any time due to wartime conditions.<ref>{{cite news|title=May Turn Pro. At Any Time|last=Young|first=Scott|author-link=Scott Young (writer)|date=August 22, 1942|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=19 |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-aug-22-1942-1552360/}}{{free access}}</ref> In August, he announced plans by [[Lionel Conacher]], the sports director for the RCAF to have teams play in senior ice hockey leagues, based at all RCAF commands across Canada. Dudley was hopeful that the [[Canadian Army]] and the [[Royal Canadian Navy]] would do the same.<ref>{{cite news|title=Air Force Plans Hockey Teams Across Canada|date=August 8, 1942|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=18|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-aug-08-1942-1552325/}}{{free access}}</ref> \n\nIn April 1943, Dudley recommended that payments from the NHL for signing amateurs be deferred until players lost due to the wartime enlistments return to professional hockey. He suggested the adjustment in light of many players enlisting recently after becoming professional.<ref>{{cite news|title=$38,000 Profit In Puck Series|date=April 26, 1943|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=16|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-apr-26-1943-1552919/}}{{free access}}</ref> Due to the war, 75 per cent of the amateurs signed by the NHL ended up in the armed services. The CAHA filled out rosters with amateurs exempt from military service who were married men over age 30. The professional-amateur agreement was renegotiated and the NHL agreed to pay a flat rate of $500 to the CAHA. Dudley conceded that the deal was not as good as before, but it was adequate due to the war.<ref>''Young, Scott (1989)'', pp. 198\u2013199</ref>\n\nIn June 1943, Dudley and Frank Sargent met with the Canadian armed services to discuss future organization of military ice hockey teams in Canada.<ref>{{cite news|title=May Change Service Setup|date=June 14, 1943|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=15|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jun-14-1943-1552923/}}{{free access}}</ref> The RCAF withdrew its teams from the CAHA in January 1944, despite attempts to negotiate a delayed withdrawal at the end of the season.<ref>{{cite news|title=Edict On Hockey Expected Today|date=January 6, 1944|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=10 |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jan-06-1944-1552992/}}{{free access}}</ref> He reported that despite the withdrawal due to a change in armed services policies, praise was given to the CAHA for its assistance.<ref>{{cite news|title=27,271 Players Registered|date=April 11, 1944|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=25 |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-apr-11-1944-1552993/}}{{free access}}</ref> He expected there to be no military service teams competing within the CAHA during the 1944\u201345 season.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dudley Says Hockey Outlook Not Bright|date=June 28, 1944|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=32|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jun-28-1944-1552995/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nIn April 1944, Dudley and W. G. Hardy considered the International Ice Hockey Association overseeing international senior ice hockey championships between the CAHA and AHAUS.<ref>{{cite news|title=C.A.H.A. Plans New Replacement Rule|date=April 13, 1944|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=33|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-apr-13-1944-1552994/}}{{free access}}</ref> In August 1944, [[the Canadian Press]] reported Dudley as having \"considerable support\" to replace [[Red Dutton]] as president of the NHL.<ref>{{cite news|title=N.H.L. Seeks New Leader|date=August 24, 1944|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=19|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-aug-24-1944-1552996/}}{{free access}}</ref> Similar rumors surfaced again by the Canadian Press in May 1945.<ref>{{cite news|title=Canadian Sport Snapshorts|last=Thomas|first=Syd|date=May 22, 1945|newspaper=Brandon Daily Sun|location=Brandon, Manitoba|page=3|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-may-22-1945-1553008/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nIn November 1944, Dudley attempted to mediate a dispute between the [[Quebec Senior Hockey League]] (QSHL) which operated outside of CAHA jurisdiction, and the Ottawa District Hockey Association which denied permission for a team from [[Hull, Quebec]] to play in the QSHL. He decided that no players would be suspended from the CAHA while talks were ongoing.<ref>{{cite news|title=Early Solution in League Dispute is Likelihood Soon|date=November 6, 1944|newspaper=Brandon Daily Sun|location=Brandon, Manitoba|page=4|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-nov-06-1944-1552997/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\n==CAHA secretary==\n[[File:International Hockey Hall of Fame.jpg|thumb|In 1945, Dudley announced CAHA contributions towards the construction of a facility for the Original Hockey Hall of Fame.<ref name=\"apr-17-1945\">{{cite news|title=Nova Scotia Man New Puck Prexy|date=April 17, 1945|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=12|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-apr-17-1945-1553004/}}{{free access}}</ref> The building ''(pictured)'' opened in 1965, in [[Kingston, Ontario]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.originalhockeyhalloffame.com/about/|title=The History of the Original Hockey Hall of Fame|year=2020|website=Original Hockey Hall of Fame|access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>|alt=Original Hockey Hall of Fame building]]\n\nOn April 17, 1945, Dudley was elected secretary of the International Ice Hockey Association.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hanson Dowell Heads C.A.H.A.|date=April 17, 1945|newspaper=Lethbridge Herald|location=Lethbridge, Alberta|page=8 |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-apr-17-1945-1475471/}}{{free access}}</ref> On the same day, Dudley was elected secretary of the CAHA to succeed [[F. H. Marples]]. Dudley's role as past-president was filled by Frank Sargent, when [[Hanson Dowell]] became president. The CAHA arranged to give 25 per cent of its annual proceeds towards building a facility for the [[Original Hockey Hall of Fame]], and Dudley expected that amount to be $4,000 to $5,000.<ref name=\"apr-17-1945\" />\n\nAfter the war ended, Dudley announced that the CAHA and the NHL would revert to the pre-war agreement not to sign any junior players without permission. He also stated that tryout contracts must be honoured, and junior-aged players on NHL reserve lists must be reinstated as amateurs to return to the CAHA. The wartime practice of the NHL borrowing amateur players for three games or less was discontinued.<ref>{{cite news|title=Pros Agree Not To Sign Juniors|date=September 19, 1945|newspaper=Medicine Hat Daily News|location=Medicine Hat, Alberta|page=5|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-sep-19-1945-1553012/}}{{free access}}</ref> Dudley participated in discussions to update the financial terms of the agreement. The NHL offered a flat payment of $20,000 to signing amateurs, which Dudley felt it was too low.<ref>{{cite news|title=C.A.H.A. Wants Best Deal Possible|date=May 17, 1946|newspaper=Lethbridge Herald|location=Lethbridge, Alberta|page=11|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-may-17-1971-1526358/}}{{free access}}</ref> The CAHA ultimately accepted the lump sum payment, preferring not to break its alliance with the NHL.<ref>{{cite news|title=C.A.H.A. and N.H.L. Reach Hockey Player Agreement|date=June 20, 1946|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=16|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jun-20-1946-1553878/}}{{free access}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=C.A.H.A. Not Satisfied|date=December 30, 1946|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=20|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-dec-30-1946-1553933/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nDudley co-operated with transfers to assist European ice hockey associations which struggled to find players after the war. The BIHA did not expect to operate in 1946\u201347 season, but the [[Scottish Ice Hockey|Scottish Ice Hockey Association]] planned to operate with the CAHA loaning players.<ref>''McKinley, Michael (2014)'', p. 77</ref> In December 1946, discussions continued for a proposed merger of the International Ice Hockey Association with the LIHG. Dudley felt that any new organization formed should be predominantly Canadian to have more say in international hockey matters. The CAHA sought to have W. G. Hardy nominated as vice-president of the new governing body, and Dudley as its secretary.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dowell Will Attend Hockey Merger Parley|date=December 28, 1946|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=29|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-dec-28-1946-1553923/}}{{free access}}</ref> The merger was agreed to and CAHA president [[Allan Pickard]] stated that the CAHA and AHAUS would operate with autonomy.<ref>{{cite news|title=Harmony Prevails On Hockey Front|last=Clarke|first=Robert|date=May 6, 1947|newspaper=Medicine Hat Daily News|location=Medicine Hat, Alberta|page=3|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-may-06-1947-1462597/}}{{free access}}</ref> The LIHG recognized AHAUS as the governing body of hockey in the United States instead of the [[Amateur Athletic Union]] (AAU). The CAHA was permitted to have its own definition of amateur as long as teams at the Olympic games adhered to existing LIHG rules.<ref>{{cite news|title=C.A.H.A. Gains Few Points At Prague Hockey Confab|date=March 22, 1947|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune |location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=33|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-mar-22-1947-1462563/}}{{free access}}</ref> The new organization was later renamed to the [[International Ice Hockey Federation]] (IIHF).<ref>{{cite news|title=Prof. George Hardy: Author-Educationist |last=Trimmer|first=Bob|date=September 21, 1963|newspaper=Lethbridge Herald|location=Lethbridge, Alberta|page=5 |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-sep-21-1963-1461284/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Ice Hockey World Championships]] resumed in 1947, but Dudley had difficulties finding any team willing to represent Canada. He invited the champions and finalists of both the [[1946 Allan Cup]] and [[1946 Memorial Cup]], but all four teams declined. In addition, the [[Winnipeg Monarchs (MJHL)|Winnipeg Monarchs]] declined the CAHA invite for a European tour. Dudley settled on the Edmonton Junior Canadians, who were the Western Canada junior finalists.<ref>{{cite news|title=Now It's Edmonton|date=December 11, 1946|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=29|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-dec-11-1946-1553918/}}{{free access}}</ref> In December 1946, the CAHA gave an ultimatum to the [[Canadian Olympic Committee|Canadian Olympic Association]] to accept the team put forth under the CAHA definition of amateur, or look to another organization for a team. Dudley said there should be no \"[[pussy]]footing\" on the matter, and reiterated that lost salaries by players was a valid concern.<ref>{{cite news|title=Issue Ultimatum To Olympic Body|date=December 28, 1946|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=16|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-dec-28-1946-1553926/}}{{free access}}</ref> No resolution was found, and Canada did not participate in the [[1947 Ice Hockey World Championships]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hockeyarchives.info/mondial1947.htm|title=Championnats du monde 1947|website=Hockey Archives|language=fr|access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==CAHA secretary-manager==\nThe CAHA added the title of manager to the secretary's role in 1947, and Dudley served as secretary-manager of the CAHA until 1960.<ref name=\"CAHA-p117\" /> The new role made Dudley more influential in Canadian hockey since he served as the regular delegate to IIHF meetings, and was in charge of selecting the [[Canada men's national ice hockey team|Canada men's national team]] and making its travel arrangements to the Ice Hockey World Championships and the Olympic Games.<ref>''Young, Scott (1989)'', p. 218</ref><ref>''Oliver, Greg (2017)'', p. 32</ref> He was named first vice-president of the IIHF and chairman of the North American delegation on July 12, 1957,<ref>{{cite news|title=Dudley Named|date=July 12, 1957|newspaper=Lethbridge Herald|location=Lethbridge, Alberta|page=6 |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jul-12-1957-1562358/}}{{free access}}</ref> and facilitated the first exhibition tours for Soviet teams in Canada.<ref name=\"Legends\" />\n\nDudley was named to the selection committee for two hockey halls of fame. In January 1948, the Original Hockey Hall of Fame increased its board of governors from 9 to 16 people to give better representation across North America, and Dudley was chosen as a new board member.<ref>{{cite news|title=New Shrine Governors Are Named|date=January 31, 1948|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=18|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jan-31-1948-1554404/}}{{free access}}</ref> In January 1958, he was named as one of the nine persons on the selection committee for the [[Hockey Hall of Fame]] in Toronto. The announcement was made after the NHL chose to recognize the Toronto institution instead of the Original Hockey Hall of Fame in Kingston.<ref>{{cite news|title=CNE to Operate Hockey Hall of Fame: Pick Committee to Select NHL Stars|date=January 31, 1958|newspaper=Medicine Hat Daily News|location=Medicine Hat, Alberta|page=9|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jan-31-1958-1563390/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\n===1948 Winter Olympics===\n[[File:RCAF Flyers 1948.JPG|thumb|The Ottawa RCAF Flyers team was the CAHA's answer to the IOC's definition of amateur for ice hockey at the 1948 Winter Olympics.|alt=1948 Ottawa RCAF Flyers team photo]]\n\nDudley was faced with a dilemma in choosing the Canadian representative [[ice hockey at the 1948 Winter Olympics]]. The Canadian Olympic Association wanted an ice hockey team that suited the IOC definition of amateur. He felt obliged to offer the chance to the [[1947 Allan Cup]] champions [[Royal Montreal Hockey Club|Montreal Royals]], would not fit the IOC definition of amateur.<ref>{{cite news|title=Must Conform to I.O.C. Definition to Amateurism|date=July 10, 1947|newspaper=Medicine Hat Daily News|location=Medicine Hat, Alberta|page=3|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jul-10-1947-1554276/}}{{free access}}</ref> In September 1947, he formally invited the Royals to represent Canada, but was unsure if the team would accept.<ref>{{cite news|title=Invited To Olympic Games|date=September 3, 1947|newspaper=Medicine Hat Daily News|location=Medicine Hat, Alberta|page=3 |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-sep-03-1947-1554292/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nDudley attended the IIHF meeting in September to discuss hockey at the Olympics using the IOC definition of amateur, or hosting its own World Championships separate from the Winter Olympics.<ref>{{cite news|title=Olympic Hockey Question Soon Will Be Decided|date=July 5, 1947|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=15|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jul-05-1947-1554275/}}{{free access}}</ref> He remained adamant against the IOC definition and said, \"We decided in Canada 11 years ago that there is too much hypocrisy about amateurism and we've seen no reason to change our view\". IIHF president [[Fritz Kraatz]] reportedly agreed to the IOC definition, if the AHAUS team was recognized by the organizing committee of the Olympics. Since hockey would be the most profitable event at the Olympics, Dudley felt that the Swiss organizing committee would agree to anything as long as the IOC approved.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hockey Politics Are Rampant In Zurich|date=September 10, 1947|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=18|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-sep-10-1947-1554322/}}{{free access}}</ref> To protect the interests of the CAHA, Dudley successfully passed a motion at the IIHF meeting which prevented any Canadian team being accepted at the Olympics without the approval of the CAHA.<ref name=\"sep-17-1947\">{{cite news|title=\"U\" Puckmen May Represent Canada|date=September 17, 1947|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=18|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-sep-17-1947-1554332/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nThe Swiss organizing committee decided that any team sent must adhere to IOC definition of amateur, and live up to the [[Olympic Oath]].<ref name=\"oct-22-1947\">{{cite news|title=Puck Moguls Rapped For R.C.A.F. Choice|date=October 22, 1947|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=17|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-oct-22-1947-1554335/}}{{free access}}</ref> The Canadian Olympic Association wanted to send a team of college hockey players to represent Canada, instead of a club team.<ref name=\"sep-17-1947\" /> The CAHA went to the RCAF for a solution, and invited its [[Ottawa RCAF Flyers]] team to represent Canada. The choice was criticized by Dave Dryburgh of the ''[[Regina Leader-Post]]'' who wrote that it would a third-rate team and said, \"Any time Canada cannot send its best hockey team to the Olympics it shouldn't send one at all\".<ref name=\"oct-22-1947\" /> Dudley sought reinforcements to strengthen the team before they sailed to Europe on January 1948, and stated the CAHA would pay to fly players to Switzerland if necessary.<ref>{{cite news|title=R.C.A.F. Puck Team Seeks Reinforcements|date=December 18, 1947|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=18 |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-dec-18-1947-1554349/}}{{free access}}</ref> Eight players were eventually added to the team, and Dudley felt they would adequately represent Canada, even if they might not be as strong as previous Canadian national teams.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hockey Official Views Olympic Team Line-Up|date=January 8, 1948|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=3|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jan-08-1948-1554394/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 102-00789, St. Moritz, Eisstadion.jpg|thumb|Outdoor stadium used for ice hockey at the 1948 Winter Olympics in [[St. Moritz]]|alt=Olympic ice rink in St. Moritz]]\n\nThe status of ice hockey at the 1948 Winter Olympics was threatened when the [[United States Olympic & Paralympic Committee|United States Olympic Committee]] led by [[Avery Brundage]] threatened to boycott the Olympics if an AHAUS team was recognized instead of an AAU team.<ref>{{cite news|title=Yank Puck Bodies Are Feudin' And Fightin'|date=November 8, 1947|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=22|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-nov-08-1947-1554343/}}{{free access}}</ref><ref name=\"dec-04-1947\">{{cite news|title=Brundage Bluffing, Charges Ahearne|date=December 4, 1947|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=19|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-dec-04-1947-1554347/}}{{free access}}</ref> The IIHF executive met again and agreed that its teams would not play against a team chosen by the AAU.<ref name=\"dec-04-1947\" /> Dudley again stated that the IIHF should host its own World Championships separate from the Olympics if differences could not be resolved. He was assured by the IIHF that such a tournament could be arranged on 48 hours' notice.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dudley Agrees To Federation Title Proposal|date=January 7, 1948|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=26|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jan-07-1948-1554391/}}{{free access}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Bitter, Long-Drawn Out Olympic Hockey Controversy Still Rages|date=January 27, 1948|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=12|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jan-27-1948-1554401/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nThe night before the Olympics began, it was decided to allow the AHAUS team to play in the tournament, but the IOC declared that games played by the United States team would not count in the standings.<ref>{{cite news|title='Squawk' Valley Hassles 'Duck Soup'|last=Sullivan|first=Jack|date=February 23, 1960|newspaper=Brandon Sun|location=Brandon, Manitoba|page=7 |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-feb-23-1960-1536343/}}{{free access}}</ref> The day before the tournament ended, the IOC decided that the winner would be recognized as Olympic champion, except for the United States team. Dudley felt that the winner would have been recognized as a world champion, whether or not the IOC recognized it.<ref>{{cite news|title=Czech-Flyers Tied: Olympic Heads To Recognize Puck Games|date=February 7, 1948|newspaper=Lethbridge Herald|location=Lethbridge, Alberta|page=17 |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-feb-07-1948-1554410/}}{{free access}}</ref> The Ottawa RCAF Flyers completed the tournament with seven wins and a draw, to capture the gold medal for Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hockeyarchives.info/JO1948.htm|title=Jeux Olympiques de Saint-Moritz 1948|website=Hockey Archives|language=fr|access-date=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter the Olympics, Dudley arranged for the Ottawa RCAF Flyers to complete an exhibition game schedule to raise funds to cover travel expenses.<ref>{{cite news|title=Flyers To Sail March 31|date=March 2, 1948|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune |location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=14|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-mar-02-1948-1554415/}}{{free access}}</ref> He stated that the 1948 Olympic hockey tournament was played in \"ridiculous weather conditions\" with poor [[Official (ice hockey)|refereeing]]. He advocated to only attended international events on artificial ice, which would showcase Canada's true abilities. He felt that the IOC should be composed of members appointed by national sports bodies who would be more knowledgeable of sport, instead of a person who was disconnected from the game appointing his or her own replacement.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dudley Scorns Olympic Hockey|date=March 20, 1948|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=18|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-mar-20-1948-1554419/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\n===1949 to 1951===\n[[File:1954 Topps Danny Lewicki.JPG|thumb|Danny Lewicki|alt=Danny Lewicki]]\n\nIn January 1949, the Canadian Olympic Association sought government grants towards the development of amateur sport. Dudley was opposed the use of tax dollars to fund sports, on the premise that the government would be in control of the sports associations, instead of those persons directly involved in the sport.<ref>{{cite news|title=Blasts Rock Discussion|date=January 8, 1949|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=17|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jan-08-1949-1554814/}}{{free access}}</ref> He also felt that politicians would inevitably use sport for political advantage.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sports Leaders Want Government To Give|date=January 10, 1949|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=16|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jan-10-1949-1554824/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Sudbury Wolves]] were chosen to represent Canada at the [[1949 Ice Hockey World Championships]], and placed second to the [[Czechoslovakia men's national ice hockey team]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hockeyarchives.info/mondial1949.htm|title=Championnats du monde 1949|website=Hockey Archives|language=fr|access-date=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn April 1949, [[Danny Lewicki]] was the focus of whether or not a minor can be signed to a contract known as a \"C\" form, and it be enforced when he became 18 years old. Dudley stated that if the player refused to report to an amateur club chosen by the professional club, he could then be offered a professional contract. Refusal of the professional contract would result in his suspension from the CAHA, as per agreements with the NHL.<ref>{{cite news|title=Lewicki Case Starts C Clause Talk Anew|date=April 7, 1949|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=20|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-apr-07-1949-1554882/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nIn response to accusations by the [[Canadian Teachers' Federation]] in August 1949, that the CAHA was wrecking high school hockey and placing youths away from home away from parental control, Dudley stated that the claims were nonsense, that he had received no complaints from parents, and asked for the claims to be substantiated.<ref>{{cite news|title=\"Tyranny\" Charges Face Hockey|date=August 12, 1949|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=15|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-aug-12-1949-1554939/}}{{free access}}</ref> A survey later that year by the [[Canadian Education Association]], concluded that the effect of hockey on education was not a national problem. Dudley opted to participated in discussions to minimize any effects of hockey on education.<ref>{{cite news|title=Schools Have Hockey Not \"Hookey\" Trouble|date=November 24, 1949|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=23|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-nov-24-1949-1554951/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Edmonton Mercurys]] were chosen to represent Canada at the [[1950 Ice Hockey World Championships]], and went undefeated to win the title.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hockeyarchives.info/mondial1950.htm|title=Championnats du monde 1950|website=Hockey Archives|language=fr|access-date=March 19, 2020}}</ref> The [[Lethbridge Maple Leafs]] represented Canada at the [[1951 Ice Hockey World Championships]], and were also undefeated in defending Canada's world title.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hockeyarchives.info/mondial1951.htm|title=Championnats du monde 1951|website=Hockey Archives|language=fr|access-date=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nEarly in 1951, the OHA was faced with a mutiny in senior ice hockey in Kingston. Dudley recommended an inquiry into why a group of six players wanted to transfer from an existing new to a new team, along with the coach. After an inquiry, he and fellow OHA executives [[Jack Roxburgh]], [[Frank Buckland (ice hockey)|Frank Buckland]] and W. A. Hewitt, handed out a lifetime suspension to [[George Patterson (ice hockey)|George Patterson]] who coached Kingston's senior B-level team, for conspiring to deliberately lose a playoff series to avoid moving into a higher-level of playoffs, rather than staying in a lower level and potentially make more profits at home playoff games than on the road.<ref>''Young, Scott (1989)'', pp. 205\u2013209</ref> \n\nIn June 1951, Dudley confirmed that the [[Hockey Newfoundland and Labrador|Newfoundland Amateur Hockey Association]] wanted to join the CAHA as its own branch, instead of part of the Maritime Amateur Hockey Association. No agreement was reached, and Dudley sought continued discussion.<ref>{{cite news|title=Newfoundland Not Interested In C.A.H.A. Tie|date=June 1, 1951|newspaper=Corner Brook Western Star|location=Corner Brook, Newfoundland |page=17|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jun-01-1951-1556002/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\n===1952 Winter Olympics===\n[[File:Jersey of the Edmonton Mercurys.jpg|thumb|The Edmonton Mercurys ''(team jersey pictured)'' represented Canada in ice hockey at the 1952 Winter Olympics.|alt=Edmonton Mercurys hockey jersey]]\n\nDiscussions began in 1950, whether or not ice hockey would be included in the [[1952 Winter Olympics]] hosted in [[Oslo]]. The IOC sought assurance that participating teams would adhere to its amateur code rather than what was accepted by the IIHF, and also wanted to exclude IIHF president Fritz Kraatz from negotiations. Dudley and W. G. Hardy agreed there would be no negotiations on those terms, nor would they repudiate Kraatz. Dudley referred to the IOC as dictatorial and undemocratic, and expected the IIHF to discuss having its own 1952 Ice Hockey World Championships instead. He further stated that the Olympics would be a financial failure without the inclusion of hockey.<ref>{{cite news|title=International Puck Bodies Widely Split|date=May 18, 1950|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=17|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-may-18-1950-1555023/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\n[[Ice hockey at the 1952 Winter Olympics]] ultimately went ahead, and the Edmonton Mercurys represented Canada again by winning the gold medal.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hockeyarchives.info/JO1952.htm|title=Jeux Olympiques d'Oslo 1952|website=Hockey Archives|language=fr|access-date=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===1952 to 1953===\nDudley supported a resolution at the 1952 CAHA general meeting which prevented the eastward transfer of players, to prevent rosters in Western Canada from being depleted by clubs in the more populated areas of Eastern Canada. He wanted to have protective measures in place, before renegotiating the professional-amateur agreement.<ref>{{cite news|title=Pro-Amateur Contract To Be Reviewed Today|date=June 17, 1952|newspaper=Medicine Hat News|location=Medicine Hat, Alberta|page=3|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jun-17-1952-1556012/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nCanada did not participate in the [[1953 Ice Hockey World Championships]]. On January 12, 1953, CAHA president [[W. B. George]] stated that, \"Every year we spend $10,000 to send a Canadian hockey team to Europe to play 40 exhibition games. All these games are played to packed houses that only enrich European hockey coffers. In return we are subjected to constant, unnecessary abuse over our Canadian style of play\".<ref>''Duplacey, James (1998)'', p. [https://archive.org/details/totalhockeyoffic0000unse/page/503 503]</ref>  \n\nIn March 1953, the CAHA suspended the QAHA after a dispute stemming from a Quebec registration certificate being issued a player who was under suspension by the CAHA. An ultimatum was given to teams in leagues affiliated with the QAHA to follow the CAHA if they wished to participate in playoffs for national championships, or remain under QAHA jurisdiction.<ref name=\"mar-13-1953\">{{cite news|title=All Quebec Leagues Are Suspended|date=March 13, 1953|newspaper=Brandon Daily Sun|location=Brandon, Manitoba|page=11 |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-mar-13-1953-1559042/}}{{free access}}</ref> Dudley published newspaper advertisements on behalf of the CAHA to notify of the decision.<ref name=\"mar-09-1953\">{{cite news|title=Quebec Senior Loop To Operate Independently|date=March 9, 1953|newspaper=Lethbridge Herald|location=Lethbridge, Alberta|page=7 |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-mar-09-1953-1559036/}}{{free access}}</ref> After the deadline, Dudley announced the suspension of all leagues and teams affiliated with the QAHA,<ref name=\"mar-13-1953\" /> except for the QSHL which resigned its provincial affiliation to operate independently of the QAHA and the CAHA.<ref name=\"mar-09-1953\" /> \n\nDudley was confident that issues could be resolved at the 1953 CAHA general meeting.<ref>{{cite news|title=Puck Groups Gather To Try End Divorce|last=Wheatley|first=W. R.|date=May 11, 1953|newspaper=Lethbridge Herald|location=Lethbridge, Alberta|page=6 |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-may-11-1953-1559073/}}{{free access}}</ref> He wanted the QAHA to return without any punitive damages, but with assurance there would be no recurrence of the infraction.<ref>{{cite news|title=Chastised Quebec Coming 'Home'|date=May 12, 1953|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=20|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-may-12-1953-1559075/}}{{free access}}</ref> The QAHA was reinstated, and Dudley urged for the CAHA executive to follow the rules consistently when it came to player replacements in playoffs, instead of making arbitrary decisions.<ref>{{cite news|title=CAHA Makes Some Rule Changes|last=Wheatley|first=W. R.|date=May 13, 1953|newspaper=Lethbridge Herald |location=Lethbridge, Alberta|page=10|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-may-13-1953-1559079/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\n===1954 World Championships===\n[[File:1954 World Ice Hockey Championships Canada vs Soviet.jpg|thumb|Canada versus the Soviet Union at the 1954 Ice Hockey World Championships|alt=Hockey action photo]]\n\nThe CAHA planned on returning to the Ice Hockey World Championships in 1954, but Dudley had difficulties again in finding a team willing to represent Canada. He eventually arranged for the [[East York Lyndhursts]] from a senior B-level league in Ontario to attend the [[1954 Ice Hockey World Championships]], after several A-level senior teams declined due to the financial strain of travel, and players being away from work. The announcement was made in October 1953, and received little press coverage at the time.<ref>''Young, Scott (1989)'', pp. 218\u2013219</ref> In January 1954, he sent reinforcements from higher-level senior teams to strengthen the roster, including [[Don Lockhart]], [[Eric Unger]], [[Tom Jamieson]], and [[Bill Shill]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Lyndhursts Whip Germany Reinforcements On Way|date=January 15, 1954|newspaper=Medicine Hat News|location=Medicine Hat, Alberta|page=16|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jan-15-1954-1560208/}}{{free access}}</ref> Dudley said that choosing the national representative was an annual problem, and the cost of sending A-level teams was getting prohibitive. He arranged an exhibition schedule in Europe to acclimatize the team to the international rules of play, and raise funds from tickets to exhibition games to cover travel costs. The 1954 Ice Hockey World Championships was the first time the [[Soviet Union national ice hockey team|Soviet Union national team]] would participate, and he speculated they would finish no better than fourth place.<ref>{{cite news|title=Thistles To Tour In Japan|date=January 11, 1954|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=14|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jan-11-1954-1560194/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nCanada lost in the final game by a 7\u20132 score to the Soviets. The loss was described as a \"black eye\" to Canada, a \"catastrophe\" and \"a national calamity\". The CAHA and Dudley were highly criticized by the media in Canada for sending a B-level senior team to international competition. Dudley invited suggestions on how to better form the team, and reiterated the prohibitive costs of sending A-level teams. He stated that the timing of the world championships coincided with playoffs in Canada, and that no A-level team would agree to leave at a critical team in their season. He also said that the profits from the Allan Cup and Memorial Cup playoffs would not sustain the annual cost of flying a team to Europe to shorten the time away from playing in Canada.<ref>{{cite news|title=CAHA Comes Under Brisk Criticism|date=March 9, 1954|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=18|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-mar-09-1954-1560227/}}{{free access}}</ref> He also considered inviting the Soviet Union national ice hockey team to tour Canada as a goodwill gesture, and since increased interest in seeing the Soviet team play would make it profitable.<ref>{{cite news|title=Red Invasion Possible: Players May Tour Canada|date=March 10, 1954|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=1|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-mar-10-1954-1560234/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\n===1955 World Championships===\n[[Image:IIHFChampionshipTrophy19531959.jpg|right|thumb|upright=0.7|Trophy awarded for winning the Ice Hockey World Championships during the 1950s|alt=World Championship trophy]]\n\nIn July 1954, Dudley was confident the criticism of choosing the national team would end, after he announced that the [[1954 Allan Cup]] champion [[Penticton Vees (senior)|Penticton Vees]] were chosen to represent Canada at the [[1955 Ice Hockey World Championships]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Penticton V's To Represent Canada In World Hockey|date=July 19, 1954|newspaper=Brandon Daily Sun|location=Brandon, Manitoba|page=4|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jul-19-1954-1560313/}}{{free access}}</ref> He predicted that Penticton would win regain the championship for Canada, and that there would be more pressure on the Soviet team than Canada's team.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dudley Says That Russians Have to Win, or Else|date=September 27, 1954 |newspaper=Lethbridge Herald|location=Lethbridge, Alberta|page=6|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-sep-27-1954-1560320/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nIn November 1954, the CAHA received an invitation for a Canadian team to tour the Soviet Union. Dudley said the request came too late to change existing schedules to accommodate the request.<ref>{{cite news|title=Find Too Late Change Schedule|date=November 24, 1954|newspaper=Medicine Hat News|location=Medicine Hat, Alberta|page=5|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-nov-24-1954-1560330/}}{{free access}}</ref> The CAHA deferred the proposal of a Canadian tour of the Soviet Union until after the World Championships which was a higher priority, despite the willingness of the [[Winnipeg Maroons (ice hockey)|Winnipeg Maroons]] to accept the Soviet invitation.<ref>{{cite news|title=CAHA Not Interested|date=December 17, 1954|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=33|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-dec-17-1954-1560341/}}{{free access}}</ref> The Penticton Vees won all eight played the 1955 Ice Hockey World Championships to regain the title for Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hockeyarchives.info/mondial1955.htm|title=Championnats du monde 1955|website=Hockey Archives|language=fr|access-date=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAt the CAHA general meeting in May 1955, Dudley proposed regulations to include television broadcasts rights in addition to the radio broadcast fees the CAHA collects for amateur games.<ref>{{cite news|title=CAHA To Govern Minor Hockey TV|date=May 23, 1955|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=15|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-may-23-1955-1561496/}}{{free access}}</ref> He proposed a 10 cent-per-ticket fee for all games in Canada towards the national team's fund. He reported interest by private company to sponsor the team, and that the CAHA's insurance company proposed to sponsor the printing of CAHA rule books. Dudley said he was not enthusiastic about sending teams to international events, but felt obligated to send a team to the upcoming Winter Olympics.<ref>{{cite news|title=CAHA Cuts Expected Olympic Help Seen |last=Hanright|first=Don|date=May 24, 1955|newspaper=Medicine Hat News|location=Medicine Hat, Alberta|page=6 |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-may-24-1955-1561505/}}{{free access}}</ref> In regards to whether the IOC would accept a Canadian senior team, he mentioned it was possible to have university and college players quickly registered with the CAHA if needed.<ref>{{cite news|title=Canadian Olympic Team Has Problems|date=May 27, 1955|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=33|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-may-27-1955-1561563/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\n===1956 Winter Olympics===\nIn August 1955, Dudley announced that the [[1955 Allan Cup]] champions [[Berlin Dutchmen|Kitchener-Waterloo Dutchmen]] were selected to represent Canada in [[ice hockey at the 1956 Winter Olympics]]. The customary exhibition tour would be omitted, and the team would fly to Europe. Plans to finance the trip included a national hockey week in Canada during the Olympics, in which 10 cents from each ticket sold would go to the CAHA.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dutchmen Get Olympic Berth|date=August 22, 1955|newspaper=Lethbridge Herald|location=Lethbridge, Alberta|page=6|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-aug-22-1955-1561587/}}{{free access}}</ref> The Soviets invited Canada to play an exhibition series in Moscow after the Olympics, and Dudley replied that the Soviet Union would need to pay more of Canada's expenses to make it worthwhile.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dutchies Interested In Playing In Soviet|date=January 14, 1956|newspaper=Lethbridge Herald|location=Lethbridge, Alberta|page=6|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jan-14-1956-1562001/}}{{free access}}</ref> The Dutchmen won six games during the Olympic hockey tournament, but losses to the Soviet Union and the United States earned a bronze medal for Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hockeyarchives.info/JO1956.htm|title=Jeux Olympiques de Cortina d'Ampezzo 1956|website=Hockey Archives|language=fr|access-date=March 19, 2020}}</ref> Despite the result, Dudley felt that the Dutchmen were the best team Canada had sent to the Olympics since World War II. In response to calls for an all-star team being sent instead, he stated that 90 per cent of senior hockey teams in Canada operated at a deficit, and taking away their best players for an all-star team would be detrimental to their ticket sales. He again mentioned the possibility of hosting the Soviet national team on a tour of Canada.<ref>{{cite news|title=CAHA May Ask Reds Tour Canada in '56|date=February 6, 1956|newspaper=Lethbridge Herald|location=Lethbridge, Alberta|page=7|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-feb-06-1956-1562018/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\n===1956 to 1957===\n[[File:Szent Istv\u00e1n k\u00f6r\u00fat a Falk Miksa (N\u00e9phadsereg) utca fel\u0151l a Honv\u00e9d utca fel\u00e9 n\u00e9zve. A szovjet csapatok ideiglenes kivonul\u00e1sa 1956. okt\u00f3ber 31-\u00e9n. Fortepan 24787.jpg|thumb|Soviet invasion of Hungary in October 1956|alt=Soviet tanks in Budapest]]\n\nAt the May 1956 general meeting of the CAHA, Dudley stated that development fees received from the NHL amounted to $27,000 in the past season. He encouraged the provincial branches to set aside their differences in the playing rules, as per agreements with the NHL to use similar rules as the professionals.<ref>{{cite news|title=Icing Rule Change Stalls CAHA Meet|date=May 23, 1956|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=26|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-may-23-1956-1562048/}}{{free access}}</ref> The CAHA agreed to send a team to the next Winter Olympics, as long as it was not burdened with the whole cost.<ref>{{cite news|title=Canada Will Be Represented If CAHA Not Saddled with Expense|date=May 24, 1956|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=24|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-may-24-1956-1562055/}}{{free access}}</ref> An agreement was reached in principle to send an all-star team to the 1957 World Championships, based on a core of players from the [[1956 Allan Cup]] champion [[Vernon Canadians]].<ref name=\"may-25-1956\">{{cite news|title=CAHA to Send All-Star Team to Olympic Games|date=May 25, 1956|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=37|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-may-25-1956-1562112/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nDudley felt it was important that Canadians agreed the best possible team was being sent, and that the CAHA should negotiate the best financial arrangements to play abroad.<ref name=\"may-25-1956\" /> He believed an all-star team from senior teams would give the best results at the Olympics and the World Championships, but funding was an issue. A sponsored team based in one city was more cost efficient than combining players from different cities. In an interview with the ''[[Toronto Telegram]]'' he said, \"If we could get the Allan Cup team of the previous year as a nucleus that would be even better, but we'd have to pry the best players loose from other clubs\".<ref>''Oliver, Greg (2017)'', p. 30</ref>\n\nThe CAHA sought $75,000 for training and travel costs for a full-time national team, which Dudley hoped a private sector sponsorship would cover.<ref>{{cite news|title=$75,000 Needed For Puck Meet Expenses|date=August 31, 1956|newspaper=Lethbridge Herald|location=Lethbridge, Alberta|page=6|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-aug-31-1956-1562153/}}{{free access}}</ref> In September 1956, Dudley stated that the offer by a private company was withdrawn.<ref>{{cite news|title=CAHA Has No Sponsor|date=September 8, 1956|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=43|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-sep-08-1956-1562170/}}{{free access}}</ref> The CAHA appealed for donations of $100 from 750 sportspersons to cover the costs.<ref>{{cite news|title=CAHA Seeks Donations|date=September 12, 1956|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=24|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-sep-12-1956-1562177/}}{{free access}}</ref> Dudley stated in October 1956, that fundraising was delayed due to searching for a sponsor.<ref>{{cite news|title=CAHA Asks For Funds|date=October 17, 1956|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=34|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-oct-17-1956-1562183/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nDudley made the announcement in November 1956, that Canada would not send its national team to the 1957 Ice Hockey World Championships due to recent changes in international affairs.<ref>{{cite news|title=Canada To Miss Tourney|date=November 14, 1956|newspaper=Medicine Hat News|location=Medicine Hat, Alberta|page=1|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-nov-14-1956-1562201/}}{{free access}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Canada Out of World Tourney|date=November 15, 1956|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=36|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-nov-15-1956-1562204/}}{{free access}}</ref> Canada and the United States boycotted the World Championships due to the [[Hungarian Revolution of 1956|1956 Soviet invasion of Hungary]].<ref>''McKinley, Michael (2014)'', p. 115</ref>\n\nDudley attended the 1957 IIHF summer congress and made arrangements for a Soviet national team tour of Canada during November and December 1957. The CAHA agreed to pay Soviet travel within Canada and return fare, and a reciprocal Canadian tour of the Soviet Union in 1958.<ref>{{cite news|title=Red Pucksters To Tour Canada|date=August 26, 1957|newspaper=Medicine Hat News|location= Medicine Hat, Alberta|page=7|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-aug-26-1957-1562362/}}{{free access}}</ref> Dudley announced the tour would be seven games played under international rules,<ref>{{cite news|title=Canadian Press Sports Camera|last=Andrews|first=Ron|date=November 20, 1957|newspaper=Drumheller Mail|location=Drumheller, Alberta|page=14 |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-nov-20-1957-1562383/}}{{free access}}</ref> and only include cities in Ontario and Quebec due to limits on the Soviet's available travel time.<ref>{{cite news|title=Soviet Puck Team Unable Play In West|date=October 9, 1957|newspaper=Lethbridge Herald|location=Lethbridge, Alberta|page=10|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-oct-09-1957-1562366/}}{{free access}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Expect Large Crowd For Soviet Debut In Canada|last=Sullivan|first=Jack|date=October 10, 1957|newspaper=Lethbridge Herald|location=Lethbridge, Alberta|page=7 |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-oct-10-1957-1562368/}}{{free access}}</ref> He expected a sold-out crowd at Maple Leaf Gardens for the first game of the tour, and thought the Soviet team might be stronger than its Olympic version.<ref>{{cite news|title=Russian Pucksters Should Get Record Amateur Crowd|last=Sullivan|first=Jack|date=October 5, 1957|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=42|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-oct-05-1957-1562365/}}{{free access}}</ref> The tour reached on 62,000 in attendance. Dudley he felt the Soviets displayed a different way in which hockey could be played scientifically with sportsmanship. He wanted to see games in Western Canada on future tours, and mentioned the possibility of inviting Swedish or Czechoslovakian teams. He felt the event was good for international hockey, despite existing political differences.<ref>{{cite news|title=221 Teams Entered In MAHA Playoffs|date=January 14, 1958|newspaper=Brandon Daily Sun|location=Brandon, Manitoba|page=11|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jan-14-1958-1563387/}}{{free access}}</ref> The CAHA profited more than $22,000 from the Soviet tour.<ref name=\"may-19-1958\">{{cite news|title=Canadian Hockey Teams Go to Russia, Olympics|date=May 19, 1958|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=15|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-may-19-1958-1563408/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\n===1958 to 1959===\n[[Image:Belleville Memorial Arena.JPG|thumb|The Belleville Memorial Arena (''pictured'') was home to the McFarlands, and its facade displays the 1958 Allan Cup and 1959 World Championship teams.|alt=Belleville Memorial Arena facade]]\n\nThe CAHA chose to participate in the [[1958 Ice Hockey World Championships]], and Dudley announced that the [[1957 Allan Cup]] champions [[Whitby Dunlops]] would represent Canada and play a European exhibition schedule.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dunlops Will Sail January 29|date=August 17, 1957|newspaper=Lethbridge Herald|location=Lethbridge, Alberta|page=6 |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-aug-17-1957-1562360/}}{{free access}}</ref> Whitby won all seven games played at the World Championships to give Canada the title.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hockeyarchives.info/mondial1958.htm|title=Championnats du monde 1958|website=Hockey Archives|language=fr|access-date=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nDudley advocated for using the profits from the Soviet tour of Canada to send team on a reciprocal tour of the Soviet Union. In May 1958, the CAHA approved sending its first Canadian team on an exhibition tour of the Soviet Union.<ref name=\"may-19-1958\" /> The 1958 Allan Cup finalists [[Kelowna Packers]] were chosen for the five-game tour, and Dudley arranged for three subsequent games in Sweden.<ref>{{cite news|title=Kelowna To Play 5 Games, Red Capital|date=October 11, 1958|newspaper=Lethbridge Herald|location=Lethbridge, Alberta|page=9|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-oct-11-1958-1563453/}}{{free access}}</ref> He hoped that the Kelowna tour would promote future cultural exchanges with Eastern Europe.<ref name=\"may-18-1959\">{{cite news|title=International Hockey OK: Japanese Team Coming|date=May 18, 1959|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=15 |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-may-18-1959-1563507/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nDudley reported in May 1958, that the CAHA and NHL were close to signing a new deal. The previous professional-amateur agreement had expired in 1955, and the groups had operated on a gentleman's agreement since.<ref name=\"may-21-1958\">{{cite news|title=Allan Cup Champions To Defend World Ice Crown|last=Sullivan|first=Jack|date=May 21, 1958|newspaper=Brandon Daily Sun|location=Brandon, Manitoba|page=11|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-may-21-1958-1563414/}}{{free access}}</ref> He announced a new agreement in January 1959, in which the NHL contribution increased to $40,000 from $27,000. The agreement set out rules for negotiation lists and reserve lists, and professional teams agreed to an earlier deadline to decide which players might be moved from a junior team to a professional team. The CAHA agreed that amateurs aged 17 and older would use same rules as the professionals except for [[Overtime (ice hockey)|overtime]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Pro-Amateur Agreement Reached|date=January 3, 1959|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=38|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jan-03-1959-1563481/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nThe [[1958 Allan Cup]] champions [[Belleville McFarlands]] were chosen to represent Canada at the [[1959 Ice Hockey World Championships]].<ref name=\"may-21-1958\" /> In the exhibition tour before the championships, Finnish newspaper ''[[Helsingin Sanomat]]'' published that Canada showed poor sportsmanship. Dudley's response was to advise the team to use discretion in future games and to avoid incidents.<ref>{{cite news|title=Canadian Hockey Circles Worried By Newspapers|date=February 21, 1959|newspaper=St. John's Daily News|location=St. John's, Newfoundland|page=8|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-feb-21-1959-1563496/}}{{free access}}</ref> The McFarlands won seven of eight games played at the 1959 Ice Hockey World Championships to retain the world title for Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hockeyarchives.info/mondial1959.htm|title=Championnats du monde 1959|website=Hockey Archives|language=fr|access-date=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nDudley scheduled the May 1959 CAHA general meeting to be hosted in [[Detroit]], in conjunction with the AHAUS general meeting. He said that no CAHA branch offered to host delegates, which would typically cost $1,000.<ref>{{cite news|title='Punch' Wants No Part Of Lady Byng Winners|last=Sullivan|first=Jack|date=May 6, 1959|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=26 |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-may-06-1959-1563503/}}{{free access}}</ref> The Kitchener-Waterloo Dutchmen had been chosen to represent Canada at the upcoming Olympics, and Dudley announced that CAHA would pay for uniforms, and traveling expenses.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dutchies To Represent Canada At Squaw Valley|date=January 3, 1959|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=38|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jan-03-1959-1563483/}}{{free access}}</ref> At the meeting, the CAHA approved an increase in the roster size for the national team. It allowed the Dutchmen to take an additional 10 players from other teams, and would assist the teams which loaned players by granting roster replacements and $500 compensation.<ref name=\"may-20-1959\">{{cite news|title=Canada Plans Hold Tight To World Amateur Hockey Title|date=May 20, 1959|newspaper=Lethbridge Herald|location=Lethbridge, Alberta|page=12|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-may-20-1959-1563514/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\n===1960 Winter Olympics===\n[[File:Squaw-Valley-Blyth-Arena-1960.jpg|thumb|Blyth Arena at the Squaw Valley Ski Resort|alt=Blyth Arena]]\n\nDudley arranged a tour of Canada in January and February 1960 for the Russian Selects, an all-star team of players from clubs in Moscow.<ref>{{cite news|title=Russian Team Tours Canada|date=January 6, 1960|newspaper=St. John's Daily News|location=St. John's, Newfoundland and Labrador|page=8|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jan-06-1960-1536257/}}{{free access}}</ref> He stated the CAHA would decide at the upcoming general meeting whether to send a team on a reciprocal tour of Russia next winter. The CAHA was invited to send a team by the coach of the Russian Selects.<ref>{{cite news|title=Canadian To Tour Russia|date=January 19, 1960|newspaper=St. John's Daily News|location=St. John's, Newfoundland and Labrador|page=11|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jan-19-1960-1536272/}}{{free access}}</ref> Dudley also arranged a [[Japan men's national ice hockey team|Japan men's national team]] tour in Canada prior to the Olympics.<ref name=\"may-18-1959\" />\n\nDudley oversaw [[ice hockey at the 1960 Winter Olympics]] on behalf of the IIHF.<ref name=\"Legends\" /><ref name=\"Ferguson\" /><ref name=\"MOSHOF\" /> He arranged a qualification round to determine whether the [[Germany men's national ice hockey team|West Germany]] or [[East Germany national ice hockey team|East Germany national team]] would play in the Olympic tournament, hosted at the [[Blyth Arena]] at the [[Squaw Valley Ski Resort]] in California. The [[Australia men's national ice hockey team|Australia men's national team]] made its Olympic debut at the tournament, in which the [[United States men's national ice hockey team|United States men's national team]] won its first gold medal in hockey.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hockeyarchives.info/JO1960.htm|title=Jeux Olympiques de Squaw Valley 1960|website=Hockey Archives|language=fr|access-date=February 3, 2020}}</ref> After the games, Dudley stated that the Kitchener-Waterloo Dutchmen who won the silver medal representing Canada \"cannot be blamed for not winning the title\". He also hoped for the national consciousness of Canada to awake before the 1964 games, to avoid similar disappointments of not winning the gold medal in hockey.<ref>{{cite news|title=CAHA Heads Praise K-W|date=February 29, 1960|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=14|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-feb-29-1960-1536352/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nIn April 1960, Dudley stated that Europeans were anxious to see Canadian teams play tours abroad, despite comments by [[Arnold Heeney]] the [[List of ambassadors of Canada to the United States|Canadian Ambassador to the United States]], who said that Canada was unpopular in Olympic hockey.<ref>{{cite news|title=Canada's Ambassador To United States Hardly Has Good Will Of Hockey Men|last=Sullivan|first=Jack|date=April 26, 1960|newspaper=Brandon Sun|location=Brandon, Manitoba|page=7 |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-apr-26-1960-1544697/}}{{free access}}</ref> In May 1960, Dudley wished to see a new method for choosing the Canadian national team which had less of an impact on domestic leagues, but produced results.<ref>{{cite news|title=Juckes Against All-Star Idea|date=May 2, 1960|newspaper=Lethbridge Herald|location=Lethbridge, Alberta|page=7|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-may-02-1960-1544701/}}{{free access}}</ref> He stated of the Canadian roster that, \"Ours are the best 17 after 500 have gone to supply the needs to the pro leagues in Canada and the United States, and at the Olympics another 500 are eliminated because they are reinstated professionals\".<ref>''Oliver, Greg (2017)'', p. 33</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nDudley became a member of Caledonian Lodge 249, the local [[Masonic lodge]] in 1915.<ref name=\"FreePress-p7\">{{cite news|title=Court, hockey officials, MPP pay tribute to G. S. Dudley|date=May 11, 1960|newspaper=Midland Free Press|location=Midland, Ontario|page=7}}</ref> He married Lulu Gidley in 1921.<ref name=\"CP-obit\" /><ref name=\"may-09-1960\">{{cite news|title=George Dudley, Known As Mr. Hockey, Dies|date=May 9, 1960|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=25|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-may-09-1960-1545603}}{{free access}}</ref> The couple never had children.<ref name=\"FreePress-p11\" /> He served 49 years on the [[Simcoe East]] riding association, and was affiliated with the [[Progressive Conservative Party of Ontario]].<ref name=\"FreePress-p12\" /> He was a member of St. Paul's United Church in Midland, a member of the [[Orange Order in Canada]], and chairman of the local Victory Bond committee in 1945.<ref name=\"FreePress-p11\" />\n\n==Death==\n[[File:George S Dudley grave stone.jpg|thumb|Dudley family gravestone at Lakeview Cemetery in Midland|alt=Dudley's gravestone]]\n\nDudley had a stroke on May 6, 1960. He died on May 8, at St. Andrew's hospital in Midland.<ref name=\"FreePress-p11\" /><ref name=\"may-09-1960\" /> He was interred in the family plot at Lakeview Cemetery in Midland, with his parents.<ref>{{Citation|title=Interment Directory|place=Midland, Ontario|publisher=Lakeview Cemetery|year=2019}}</ref>\n\nAt the time of his death, Dudley was expected to become the next president of the IIHF.<ref name=\"MOSHOF\" /><ref name=\"FreePress-p12\" /> [[Robert Lebel (ice hockey)|Robert Lebel]] who was a past-president of the CAHA, succeeded Dudley and became president of the IIHF in July 1960.<ref>{{cite news|title=Name Canuck Hockey Prexy|newspaper=Lethbridge Herald|location=Lethbridge, Alberta|date=July 27, 1960|page=14|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jul-27-1960-734440/}}{{free access}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iihf.com/iihf-home/history/the-iihf/presidents/|title=History of IIHF Presidents|website=International Ice Hockey Federation|access-date=June 26, 2018}}</ref> [[Gordon Juckes]] who was the current CAHA president, succeeded Dudley as secretary-manager of the CAHA when the position became a full-time paid role.<ref name=\"CAHA-p117\" /><ref>{{cite news|title=CAHA Flourishes Under Gordon Juckes' Guidance|date=January 23, 1968|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=18|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jan-23-1968-1526436/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\n==Honours and awards==\nDudley was made a life member of the CAHA in November 1944.<ref>{{cite news|title=Canadian Sport Snapshorts|last=Thomas|first=Syd|date=November 11, 1944|newspaper=Brandon Daily Sun|location=Brandon, Manitoba|page=4|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-nov-11-1944-1553000/}}{{free access}}</ref> He received the OHA Gold Stick award in 1949, in recognition of service to hockey in Ontario.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ohahockey.ca/view/oha/about-us/association-awards/gold-stick|title=Gold Stick|year=2018|website=Ontario Hockey Association|access-date=February 16, 2019}}</ref> He received the AHAUS citation award in 1950 for service to amateur hockey in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usahockey.com/layout_container/show_layout_tab?layout_container_id=27569776&page_node_id=837446&tab_element_id=54968|title=Citation Award|website=USA Hockey|access-date=February 1, 2019}}</ref> Dudley and W. A. Hewitt were honoured with a dinner by the OHA in December 1950, and Dudley received a silver tea service in recognition of 26 years of service to the OHA.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hockey Officials Honored|date=December 6, 1950|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=24|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-dec-06-1950-1555518/}}{{free access}}</ref> He was made a life member of the OHA in 1952.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ohahockey.ca/view/oha/about-us/association-awards/oha-life-members|title=OHA Life Members|year=2018|website=Ontario Hockey Association|access-date=February 16, 2019}}</ref> He was inducted to the builder category of the Hockey Hall of Fame in 1958.<ref name=\"Legends\" /><ref>{{cite news|title=Puck Hall of Fame Officially Open|last=Sullivan|first=Jack|date=April 28, 1958|newspaper=Medicine Hat News|location=Medicine Hat, Alberta|page=12|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-apr-28-1958-1563396/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nAfter his death in 1960, the CAHA observed a moment of silence at that year's general meeting.<ref>{{cite news|title=CAHA Honors George Dudley|date=May 24, 1960|newspaper=Brandon Sun|location=Brandon, Manitoba|page=6|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-may-24-1960-1545656/}}{{free access}}</ref> He was posthumously inducted into the Midland Sports Hall of Fame on October 12, 1996.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.midlandonsportshalloffame.com/builders-2|title=Builders|website=Midland Sports Hall of Fame|access-date=February 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n[[File:Dudley Hewitt Cup.png|thumb|Dudley Hewitt Cup|alt=Dudley Hewitt Cup trophy]]\n\nDudley was known as Mr. Hockey.<ref name=\"MOSHOF\" /><ref name=\"CP-obit\" /><ref name=\"may-09-1960\" /> He and W. A. Hewitt are the namesakes of the [[Dudley Hewitt Cup]]. It was first awarded by the [[Canadian Junior Hockey League]] in 1971 to the Central Canada Junior A champion team, who moves on to the national [[Centennial Cup]] competition.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thunderbaybusiness.ca/article/the-dudley-hewitt-cup--and-the-business--of-hockey-416.asp|title=The Dudley Hewitt Cup and the Business of Hockey|last=Aalto|first=Sherry|year=2012|website=Thunder Bay Business|access-date=February 18, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"CCC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.centralcanadianchampionship.com/view/dudleyhewitt/about-the-cup-3|title=Dudley Hewitt Cup|website=Canadian Junior Hockey League|access-date=February 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\nDudley's death led to multiple tributes from the hockey community. CAHA president Gordon Juckes stated, \"to sportsmen national and internationally, his death will mean the personal loss of an experienced, impartial and able administrator\". CAHA vice-president Jack Roxburgh described him as, \"the best man hockey ever knew\". Toronto Maple Leafs coach [[Punch Imlach]] said that, \"he did more for hockey than any living man\".<ref name=\"CP-obit\" /><ref name=\"FreePress-p7\" /> Journalist Jack Sullivan described Dudley as a staunch and shrewd hockey official, a problem solver, and a slow-talking person who stayed away from the limelight.<ref>{{cite news|title=George Dudley Is Laid To Rest: Hockey Loses Valuable Official|last=Sullivan|first=Jack|date=May 13, 1960|newspaper=Lethbridge Herald|location=Lethbridge, Alberta|page=9|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-may-13-1960-1545620/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nCanadian journalist and hockey historian [[Scott Young (writer)|Scott Young]] mentioned Dudley frequently in the book, ''100 Years of Dropping the Puck: A History of the OHA''. Young described Dudley as a low-key figure at first who grew to prominence by his reputation as being one the busiest and most able volunteers in the OHA.<ref name=\"Young-p157\" /><ref>''Young, Scott (1989)'', p. 290</ref> Young further stated that Dudley was a forward thinker,<ref>''Young, Scott (1989)'', p. 158</ref> a man who always had a solution to problems in hockey,<ref>''Young, Scott (1989)'', p. 156</ref> and had the ability to listen to a conversation and find a compromise without forcing anyone to change his mind.<ref name=\"Young-p172\" /> Young credited Dudley for dealing with reforms to amateurism, and regulations on player salaries and transfers, which led to increased interest in hockey.<ref name=\"Young-p191\" /> Young also credited Dudley's management skills as a primary factor in the improvement of OHA finances during the 1950s.<ref>''Young, Scott (1989)'', p. 217</ref>\n\n==References==\n'''General'''\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Ellison|first1=Jenny|last2=Anderson|first2=Jennifer|title=Hockey: Challenging Canada\u2019s Game|publisher=Canadian Museum of History|date=2018|location=Ottawa, Ontario|pages=116|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=BeBVDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA116|isbn=978-0-7766-2771-7|via=Google Books}}\n*{{cite book|last=Oliver|first=Greg|title=Father Bauer and the Great Experiment: The Genesis of Canadian Olympic Hockey|publisher=ECW Press|date=2017|location=Toronto, Ontario|isbn=978-1-77041-249-1}}\n*{{Citation|last=Ladouceur|first=Denise & John|title=Lakeview Cemetery Tombstone Index|place=Midland, Ontario|publisher=North Simcoe Geneaology Society|year=2006|series=Midland 125 Cemetery Project}}\n*{{cite book|last=McKinley|first=Michael|title=It's Our Game: Celebrating 100 Years Of Hockey Canada|publisher=Viking|date=2014|location=Toronto, Ontario|isbn=978-0-670-06817-3}}\n*{{cite book|last=Duplacey|first=James|title=Total Hockey: The official encyclopedia of the National Hockey League|year=1998|publisher=Total Sports|isbn=0-8362-7114-9|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/totalhockeyoffic0000unse/page/503}}\n*{{cite book|last=Ferguson|first=Bob|title=Who's Who in Canadian Sport, Volume 4|publisher=Fitzhenry & Whiteside Ltd.|date=2005|location=Markham, Ontario|isbn=1-55041-855-6}}\n*{{cite book|last=Young|first=Scott|author-link1=Scott Young (writer)|title=100 Years of Dropping the Puck|publisher=McClelland & Stewart Inc.|date=1989|location=Toronto, Ontario|isbn=0-7710-9093-5}}\n*{{cite book|title=Constitution, By-laws, Regulations, History|publisher=Canadian Amateur Hockey Association|date=May 1990|location=Gloucester, Ontario}}\n{{refend}}\n\n'''Specific'''\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dudley, George}}\n[[Category:1894 births]]\n[[Category:1960 deaths]]\n[[Category:Burials in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Canadian Amateur Hockey Association presidents]]\n[[Category:Canadian Freemasons]]\n[[Category:Canadian Queen's Counsel]]\n[[Category:Hockey Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:Ice hockey people from Ontario]]\n[[Category:International Ice Hockey Federation executives]]\n[[Category:Lawyers in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Members of the Orange Order]]\n[[Category:Ontario Hockey Association executives]]\n[[Category:Osgoode Hall Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Midland, Ontario]]\n[[Category:Solicitors]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the American art director|George Dudley (art director)}}\n{{Short description|Canadian ice hockey administrator}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = George Dudley\n| image       = George Dudley photo at Hockey Hall of Fame.jpg\n| image_upright = 0.8\n| alt         = Black and white of George Dudley dressed in a suit and tie\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|1894|04|19}}\n| birth_place = [[Midland, Ontario]], Canada\n| death_date  = {{Death date and age|1960|05|08|1894|04|19}}\n| death_place = Midland, Ontario, Canada\n| alma_mater  = [[Osgoode Hall Law School]]\n| occupation  = Lawyer, solicitor\n| known_for   = {{hlist|[[Canadian Amateur Hockey Association]]|[[Ontario Hockey Association]]|[[International Ice Hockey Federation]]|[[International Ice Hockey Association]]}}\n| awards      = [[Hockey Hall of Fame]]\n| honours     = [[Dudley Hewitt Cup]]\n}}\n\n'''George Samuel Dudley''' {{Post-nominals|country=CAN|QC}} (April 19, 1894 \u2013 May 8, 1960) was a Canadian [[ice hockey]] administrator. He joined the [[Ontario Hockey Association]] (OHA) executive in 1928, served as its president from 1934 to 1936, and as its secretary-treasurer from 1936 to 1960. He was elected to [[Canadian Amateur Hockey Association]] (CAHA) executive in 1936, served as its president from 1940 to 1942, as its secretary from 1945 to 1947, and as its secretary-manager from 1947 to 1960. He was secretary of the [[International Ice Hockey Association]] from 1945 to 1947, and was later vice-president of the [[International Ice Hockey Federation]] (IIHF) from 1957 to 1960. He was expected to become the next president of the IIHF before his death. He graduated from [[Osgoode Hall Law School]] in 1917 then practiced law for 43 years as the town [[solicitor]] for [[Midland, Ontario]].\n\nDudley and [[W. G. Hardy]] led the way in revising the definition of an amateur hockey player to keep amateur players in Canada and slow the number of Canadians turning professional. Dudley negotiated deals with the [[National Hockey League]] and the [[Ice Hockey UK|British Ice Hockey Association]] to govern the transfer of players internationally. He introduced contracts for [[junior ice hockey]] players, as a means to obtain development payments from professional teams seeking new talent. He supported an alliance between the CAHA and the [[USA Hockey|Amateur Hockey Association of the United States]] (AHAUS), and sought for international recognition of AHAUS as the governing body of ice hockey in the United States. He threatened to withdraw Canada from [[ice hockey at the Olympic Games]] if the [[International Olympic Committee]] did not accept the Canadian definition of amateur, and supported the IIHF hosting its own [[Ice Hockey World Championships]] separate from the Olympics. Dudley's role as secretary-manager of the CAHA made him influential in Canadian hockey since he served as the regular delegate to IIHF meetings, and was in charge of selecting the [[Canada men's national ice hockey team|Canada men's national team]]. He facilitated the first exhibition tour by the [[Soviet Union national ice hockey team|Soviet Union national team]] in Canada, and oversaw [[ice hockey at the 1960 Winter Olympics]] on behalf of the IIHF\n\nDudley was committed to implementing reforms for amateur hockey, believing that they were in the best interest of hockey in Canada. He was opposed to governments funding or controlling amateur sports associations, and supported the continuation of hockey and incorporating [[Royal Canadian Air Force]] teams into the CAHA as a morale boost during [[World War II]]. Dudley was described by Journalist Jack Sullivan as a staunch and shrewd hockey official and a problem solver. Canadian journalist [[Scott Young (writer)|Scott Young]] stated Dudley was a low-key figure at first who grew to prominence by his reputation as being a busy and able volunteer. Young further stated that Dudley was a forward thinker, and had the ability to listen to a conversation and find a compromise without forcing anyone to change his mind. Young credited Dudley for dealing with reforms to amateurism, and regulations on player salaries and transfers, which led to increased interest in hockey.\n\nDudley was inducted to the builder category of the [[Hockey Hall of Fame]] in 1958, and was posthumously inducted into the Midland Sports Hall of Fame in 1996. He was made a life member of both the CAHA and OHA, received the Gold Stick award from the OHA in recognition of service to hockey in Ontario and the AHAUS citation award for service to amateur hockey in the United States. He was named to the selection committee for the Hockey Hall of Fame, and previously sat on the same committee for the [[Original Hockey Hall of Fame]]. He and [[W. A. Hewitt]] were made the namesakes of the [[Dudley Hewitt Cup]], first awarded by the [[Canadian Junior Hockey League]] in 1971.\n\n==Early life and legal career==\n[[File:Historic building in downtown Toronto on an early snowy morning. Ontario courthouse. (25129051345).jpg|thumb|Osgoode Hall Law School in Toronto|alt=Osgoode Hall building]]\n\nGeorge Samuel Dudley was born on April 19, 1894, in [[Midland, Ontario]].<ref name=\"Legends\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hhof.com/LegendsOfHockey/jsp/LegendsMember.jsp?list=ByName&page=bio&mem=B195801|title=Dudley, George \u2013 Biography \u2013 Honoured Builder|website=Legends of Hockey|access-date=2019-02-15}}</ref><ref name=\"elitepro\">{{cite web|url=https://www.eliteprospects.com/staff/39590/george-dudley|title=George Dudley Team Staff Profile|website=Elite Prospects|access-date=2019-02-15}}</ref><ref name=\"Ferguson\">''Ferguson, Bob (2005)'', p. 119</ref> His parents were William Thomas Dudley, and Sarah Agnes Dudley (n\u00e9e Brown).<ref name=\"NSGS\">''North Simcoe Geneaology Society (2006)'', pp. 404\u2013405</ref> His father served 37 years on the local [[public utilities commission]].<ref name=\"FreePress-p11\">{{cite news|title=Town solicitor 43 years George Dudley stricken|date=May 11, 1960|newspaper=Midland Free Press|location=Midland, Ontario|page=11}}</ref> Dudley grew up playing [[minor ice hockey]] in Midland,<ref name=\"Ferguson\" /><ref name=\"MOSHOF\">{{cite web|url=https://www.midlandonsportshalloffame.com/portfolio_page/george-s-dudley-qc|title=George S. Dudley QC. (Mr. Hockey) Midland Sports Hall of Fame 1894-1960|year=2015|website=Midland Ontario Sports Hall of Fame|access-date=2020-02-01}}</ref> but poor eyesight prevented him from a further athletic career.<ref name=\"FreePress-p11\" />\n\nDudley attended [[Georgian Bay District Secondary School|Midland Secondary School]], then graduated from [[Osgoode Hall Law School]] in 1917. While studying law, he served as an [[articled clerk]] for [[William Humphrey Bennett]], the [[Member of Parliament (Canada)|Member of Parliament]] of [[Simcoe East]]. Dudley entered into a law practice in a partnership with [[William Finlayson (Canadian politician)|William Finlayson]] in 1917.<ref name=\"FreePress-p11\" /> They established at Finlayson & Dudley, Barristers and Solicitors at 212 King Street in Midland.<ref>{{cite book|title=Town of Midland Directory|publisher=Vernon Directories Limited|date=1933|location=Midland, Ontario|pages=129, 174, 186}}</ref> Dudley took over the firm upon Finlayson's death in 1943.<ref name=\"FreePress-p11\" /> He practiced law for 43 years as the town's [[solicitor]] until 1960.<ref name=\"CP-obit\">{{cite news|title=Dudley's Death Blow To Hockey|author=[[The Canadian Press]]|date=May 11, 1960|newspaper=[[The Chronicle-Journal|Daily Times-Journal]]|location=Fort William, Ontario|page=8}}</ref><ref name=\"FreePress-p12\">{{cite news|title=Town solicitor 43 years George Dudley stricken (continued)|date=May 11, 1960|newspaper=Midland Free Press|location=Midland, Ontario|page=12}}</ref>\n\n==Early hockey career==\nDudley first attended [[Ontario Hockey Association]] (OHA) meetings in 1925.<ref name=\"Young-p157\">''Young, Scott (1989)'', p. 157</ref> He was elected an executive member of the OHA in November 1928, and urged the OHA to reassert its jurisdiction over all hockey in Ontario and its intention to introduce associate memberships to regulate leagues under its domain.<ref>{{cite news|title=Establish University Scholarship for Hockey Players, O.H.A. Annual|date=November 24, 1928|newspaper=Lethbridge Herald|location=Lethbridge, Alberta|page=3|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-nov-24-1928-1526336/}}{{free access}}</ref> He was an early advocate of professional [[Coach (ice hockey)|hockey coaches]] in the amateur game, and supported the reforms by [[W. A. Hewitt]] to allow them.<ref>''Young, Scott (1989)'', pp. 159\u2013161</ref>\n\nAt the OHA general meeting in 1930, Dudley supported measures to bring attention to rules already in place which did not allow players with an active professional contract in the OHA.<ref name=\"Young-p172\">''Young, Scott (1989)'', p. 172</ref> He successfully campaigned for the construction of a new arena in Midland in 1931, to replace the previous structure lost in 1926.<ref name=\"MOSHOF\" /> Dudley oversaw construction of the Midland Arena Gardens by autumn 1931 during the [[Great Depression]], and it became the only artificial [[ice rink]] between [[Toronto]] and [[Winnipeg]] at the time.<ref name=\"MOSHOF\" />\n\n==OHA president==\n[[File:Olympia Eissportzentrum Garmisch Partenkirchen.jpg|thumb|Dudley pushed for a new definition of amateur, in the wake of Canada not winning the gold medal in ice hockey at the 1936 Winter Olympics hosted in [[Garmisch-Partenkirchen]] ''(Olympic ice sport centre pictured)''.|alt=Olympic Ice Sport Centre in Garmisch Partenkirchen]]\n\nDudley served as president of the OHA from 1934 to 1936.<ref name=\"MOSHOF\" /><ref>''Young, Scott (1989)'', p. 348</ref> In 1934, he advocated for ratification of the first [[Canadian Amateur Hockey Association]] (CAHA) agreement with the [[National Hockey League]] (NHL), regarding player control and compensation to the junior clubs for developing the player. To gain the financial concessions, the CAHA conceded to allow [[Checking (ice hockey)|body checking]] in the neutral zone, and use the same [[ice hockey rules]] as the professional league.<ref>''Young, Scott (1989)'', p. 236</ref> Dudley later introduced a motion at the OHA general meeting to adopt the same playing rules as the NHL.<ref>{{cite news|title=Pro Rules For O.H.A. Planned|date=November 26, 1936|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=16|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-nov-26-1936-1545903/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nAt the CAHA general meeting in 1935, Dudley stated it was important to keep younger players amateurs as long as possible, and prevent professionalism at a young age which excluded them from the OHA. He felt that once a player reached age 21, he would have gained the knowledge to make an informed decision on his future.<ref name=\"Ellison\">''Ellison & Anderson (2018)'', pp. 115\u2013116</ref> Dudley felt that OHA needed to be offer financial opportunities competitive with what was available elsewhere.<ref>''Young, Scott (1989)'', p. 188</ref> He was nominated by CAHA president [[E. A. Gilroy]], to be part of a special committee dealing with the [[Amateur Athletic Union of Canada]] (AAU of C) to discuss the definition of amateur, the cost of player registration cards, and the right for the CAHA to issue its own registration cards.<ref>{{cite news|title=C.A.H.A. To Meet A.A.U.|date=April 13, 1935|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=27|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-apr-13-1935-1545717/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nIn October 1935, Dudley stated that the number of players leaving for the United States was compromising rosters in Canada, and that the rate of exodus was not sustainable. He decreed that the OHA would decline all player transfer requests to the United States, and players not returning to Canada by November 15, would be suspended from the OHA.<ref>{{cite news|title=O.H.A. Rejects Transfers To United States Clubs|date=October 30, 1935|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=14|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-oct-30-1935-1545725/}}{{free access}}</ref> He began to put rules in place for the transfer of players internationally, and stated that, \"It's going to happen. We might as well try to regulate it\". Dudley and CAHA second vice-president [[W. G. Hardy]] negotiated agreements with the NHL, and the [[Ice Hockey UK|British Ice Hockey Association]] (BIHA) to govern the transfer of players and prevent the raiding of Canadian rosters. Limits were placed on the number of allowed transfers, and the organizations agreed to recognize each other's authority and suspensions.<ref name=\"Young-p191\">''Young, Scott (1989)'', p. 191</ref> \n\nDudley and Hardy soon began a campaign to rewrite the definition of amateur, to decrease the number of amateurs from turning professional.<ref>''Young, Scott (1989)'', p. 182</ref> They felt that the requirement to have an AAU of C registration card to play in the OHA, and the Olympic Games, was an obstacle to progress, and made the AAU of C their main target of reforms.<ref name=\"Young-p189\">''Young, Scott (1989)'', p. 189</ref> At the AAU of C general meeting in November 1935, Dudley supported a defeated resolution to drop the word amateur from the AAU of C name.<ref>{{cite news|title=Delegates At Annual Meeting Unanimously Defeat Proposal|last=Merkel|first=Arthur|date=November 22, 1935|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=17|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-nov-22-1935-1545728/}}{{free access}}</ref> At the same meeting, Dudley and Hardy presented \"four points\" to update the definition of amateur, as supported by the CAHA's special committee dealing with the AAU of C.<ref name=\"Young-p190\">''Young, Scott (1989)'', p. 190</ref>  \n\nThe \"four points\" were:<ref name=\"apr-11-1936-part1\" /><ref>''Young, Scott (1989)'', pp. 189\u2013190</ref>\n# Hockey players may capitalize on their ability as hockey players for the purpose of obtaining legitimate employment. \n# Hockey players may accept from their clubs or employers payment for time lost, from work while competing on behalf of their clubs. They will not however, be allowed to hold \"shadow\" jobs under the clause.\n# Amateur hockey teams may play exhibition games against professional teams under such conditions as may be laid down by the individual branches of the CAHA. \n# Professionals in another sport will be allowed to play under the CAHA jurisdiction as amateurs.\n\nThe AAU of C promptly voted down the proposals. At the same meeting, the AAU of C decided upon Canada's representation in [[ice hockey at the 1936 Winter Olympics]]. The [[1935 Allan Cup]] champion [[Halifax Wolverines]] were unable to go, unless financial provisions were made for their families. Since the AAU of C did not condone payment for lost wages while away at competitions, the Allan Cup finalists [[Port Arthur Bearcats]] were chosen. Canada failed to win the Olympic gold medal due to a loss to the [[Great Britain men's national ice hockey team|Great Britain men's national team]].<ref name=\"Young-p190\">''Young, Scott (1989)'', p. 190</ref> Dudley stated that the CAHA should face realities, and that the Canadian public was sympathetic to compensating and supporting its Olympic ice hockey players while overseas.<ref name=\"apr-11-1936-part2\">{{cite news|title=Sweeping Proposals Would End Alliance|date=April 11, 1936|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=29|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-apr-11-1936-1545858/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nAt the 1936 CAHA general meeting, Dudley and Hardy presented the four points, which were adopted by the CAHA. In doing so, the CAHA took its stand against the definition of amateurism, and recognized that players should receive compensation. The stand meant the likelihood of breaking ties with the AAU of C. The ''[[Winnipeg Tribune]]'' reported that support for the \"four points\" was strong, and that the \"old guard\" of amateurism supported by AAU of C president [[W. A. Fry]] would eventually lose.<ref name=\"apr-11-1936-part1\">{{cite news|title=Sweeping Proposals, If Ratified, Would End A.A.U. Alliance|date=April 11, 1936|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=27|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-apr-11-1936-1545857/}}{{free access}}</ref> Dudley stated that common sense had not prevailed in previous AAU of C discussions on the matter. Fry stated that the decision was \"the most important matter ever to come before an amateur body in Canada\", and that \"It would be a sorry day for the AAU of C should it split with its strongest supporter, the CAHA. As a former CAHA president, he sympathized with the resolution, but did not give approval.<ref name=\"apr-11-1936-part2\" />\n\n==CAHA second vice-president==\n[[File:Maple Leaf Gardens 2016.jpg|thumb|Maple Leaf Gardens hosted many hockey matches scheduled by Dudley.|alt=Exterior of Maple Leaf Gardens]]\n\nDudley was elected second vice-president of the CAHA in April 1936.<ref>''Canadian Amateur Hockey Association (1990)'', p. 127</ref> The CAHA decided to go ahead with reforms to the definition of amateur regardless of the outcome of an AAU of C mail-in vote on the matter. In May 1936, Fry decided against holding AAU of C vote on the matter, which led to Dudley referring to Fry as \"Somersault Bill\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Fry Resents \"Somersault Bill\" As Name|last=Dulmage|first=Elmer|date=May 7, 1936|newspaper=Lethbridge Herald|location=Lethbridge, Alberta|page=12|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-may-07-1936-1545872/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nDudley became treasurer of the OHA upon the death of [[John F. Paxton]] on May 12, 1936.<ref>''Young, Scott (1989)'', p. 187</ref> \nFrom 1936 to 1960, he functioned as OHA's secretary-treasurer, in addition to his roles with the CAHA.<ref name=\"Legends\" /><ref name=\"MOSHOF\" /> He reported an operating loss of [[Canadian dollar|C$5]],662 in 1936, due to increased expenses and decreased revenue, after the OHA had experienced many years with a surplus.<ref>''Young, Scott (1989)'', pp. 187\u2013188</ref>\n\nDudley and Hardy presented the \"four points\" again at the 1936 AAU of C general meeting. Dudley and Hardy advocated for broken time payments, since players were reliant on income to support their families, and that being away from work for six weeks at a time for international competition or national playoffs constituted a hardship.<ref name=\"nov-20-1936\">{{cite news|title=Pro. Vs. Amateur Games Approved If Exhibition|date=November 20, 1936|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=1|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-nov-20-1936-1545878/}}{{free access}}</ref> They were committed to change believing that the reforms were in the best interest of hockey in Canada, and were empowered the CAHA executive to act as it saw fit on the matter.<ref>{{cite news|title=Secession Of Hockey, Lacrosse, Basketball From A.A.U. Fold Seen|last=Allen|first=Ralph|date=November 21, 1936|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=25|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-nov-21-1936-1545894/}}{{free access}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Amateur Meeting|last=Allen|first=Ralph|date=November 21, 1936|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=27|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-nov-21-1936-1545896/}}{{free access}}</ref> Journalist [[Ralph Allen (journalist)|Ralph Allen]] stated that public opinion had turned in favour of the proposals, and that the AAU of C were relics of a bygone age.<ref name=\"Young-p190\" /> The AAU of C voted and approved exhibition games between amateurs and professionals, but rejected the other three points.<ref name=\"nov-20-1936\" /> The CAHA status within the AAU of C was left unclear.<ref>{{cite news|title=Jack Hamilton, Regina, Is Named A.A.U. Of C. Leader|last=Edwards|first=Charles|date=November 23, 1936|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=17|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-nov-23-1936-1545899/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nDudley was re-elected second vice-president of the CAHA at the general meeting in April 1937.<ref>{{cite news|title=Cecil Duncan Is Re-elected Head At C.A.H.A. Meet|date=April 21, 1937|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=3 |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-apr-21-1937-1545908/}}{{free access}}</ref> Dudley along with CAHA president [[Cecil Duncan]] and W. A. Hewitt participated in negotiations with the [[Eastern Hockey League|Eastern Amateur Hockey League]] (EAHL) represented by [[Tommy Lockhart]] in August 1937, a result of the [[Amateur Athletic Union]] (AAU) of the United States giving an ultimatum to the EAHL not to have any Canadian players. The EAHL chose to break away from the AAU, similar to the CAHA relationship with the AAU of C, and reached an agreement with the CAHA which limited the number of Canadian players transferring to the league.<ref>{{cite news|title=Eastern U.S. Puck Loops Quits A.A.U.|date=August 31, 1937|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=36|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-aug-31-1937-1545914/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nIn November 1937, Dudley reported that the OHA had returned to a surplus, with an operating profit of $1,422, led by playoffs tickets for the [[Memorial Cup]] playoffs. Dudley signed a five-year agreement with [[Maple Leaf Gardens]] to be the home rink for all Toronto-based teams in the OHA, except for the [[University of Toronto]] teams playing at [[Varsity Arena]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Sign Five-Year Contract With Gardens|date=November 22, 1937|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=17|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-nov-22-1937-1545916/}}{{free access}}</ref> In March 1938, Dudley and W. A. Hewitt met with [[Frank Calder]] to discuss the professional-amateur player agreement with the NHL, in response to a protest over a suspended professional player being placed on an amateur roster.<ref>{{cite news|title=Amateur Solons Will Meet Calder|date=March 3, 1938|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=14|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-mar-03-1938-1545921/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\n==CAHA first vice-president==\n[[File:Drawing Room, Royal Alexandra Hotel, Winnipeg (HS85-10-18226).jpg|thumb|The CAHA's silver jubilee in 1939, was hosted at the Royal Alexandra Hotel ''(drawing room pictured)'' in Winnipeg.|alt=Black and white photo of the drawing Room at the Royal Alexandra Hotel, Winnipeg]]\n\nOn April 18, 1938, Dudley was elected first vice-president of the CAHA. He credited the outgoing president Cecil Duncan for replenishing CAHA financial reserves with more success that his predecessors.<ref>{{cite news|title=New Executive Strength Gives West Louder Voice In Amateur Ice Affairs|date=April 18, 1938|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=14 |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-apr-18-1938-1545933/}}{{free access}}</ref> Dudley was placed in charge of [[Eastern Canada]] playoffs,<ref>{{cite news|title=Changes Announced In Senior Puck Dates|date=March 11, 1939|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=24|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-mar-11-1939-1545942/}}{{free access}}</ref> and appointed chairman of the CAHA resolutions committee.<ref>{{cite news|title=Past Presidents Headline C.A.H.A. Meeting|date=April 11, 1939|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=16|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-apr-11-1939-1545948/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nIn August 1938, he participated in CAHA negotiations with the NHL and Frank Calder to reach a new professional-amateur agreement. Agreements were made on playing rules and recognition of each other's suspensions. The CAHA would disallow international transfers for players on NHL reserve lists, and the NHL agreed not to sign any junior players during active CAHA competition, or without consent of the CAHA club.<ref>{{cite news|title=C.A.H.A. To Deny International Transfers To Amateurs Eyed By National Leaguers|date=August 15, 1938|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=12|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-aug-15-1938-1545937/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nThe CAHA's silver jubilee in 1939, was hosted at the [[Royal Alexandra Hotel]] in Winnipeg. Dudley gave the introductory goodwill [[Toast (honor)|toast]].<ref>{{cite news|title=C.A.H.A. Eulogized at 25th Annual Banquet|date=April 11, 1939|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=16|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-apr-11-1939-1545949/}}{{free access}}</ref> At the general meeting which followed, he presented a resolution to have contracts for [[junior ice hockey]] players.<ref name=\"apr-12-1939\">{{cite news|title=C.A.H.A. Approves Player-Club Tie|date=April 12, 1939|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=15|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-apr-12-1939-1545955/}}{{free access}}</ref> He felt that if a club team had a contract with a player, then it had a legal course of action to request remuneration by way of development fees if the player was signed to a professional team. Lengthy discussion ensued and the idea was approved in principle with a final decision deferred until the 1940 general meeting. Contracts had the added benefit of making professional teams negotiate for amateur services. A signing fee of $500 was proposed, which would be dispersed among the amateur clubs which has developed the player.<ref name=\"apr-12-1939\" />\n\nDudley re-elected first vice-president of the CAHA, on April 12, 1939.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hardy Returned C.A.H.A. Prexy|date=April 12, 1939|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=1|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-apr-12-1939-1545957/}}{{free access}}</ref> In November 1939, he expected changes would be made in the playoff structure and compensation of teams for travel, since the financial situations of the CAHA and OHA had improved since the Great Depression.<ref>{{cite news|title=C.A.H.A. Salts Away $55,000|date=November 27, 1939|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=11|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-nov-27-1939-1545963/}}{{free access}}</ref> In December 1939, he acted as a goodwill emissary to assist the growth of the [[Ladies Ontario Hockey Association]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Girls' Hockey In Durham?|date=December 21, 1939|newspaper=Durham Review|location=Durham, Ontario|page=1|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-dec-21-1939-1545962/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\n==CAHA president==\n===First term===\n[[File:Feature. Red Cross Prisonners of War PKGS BAnQ P48S1P07948.jpg|thumb|Canadian Red Cross volunteers during World War II.|alt=Canadian Red Cross volunteers]]\n\nOn April 15, 1940, the CAHA and the [[USA Hockey|Amateur Hockey Association of the United States]] (AHAUS) agreed to form the [[International Ice Hockey Association]], and invited the BIHA to join. W. G. Hardy became president of the association, and stated that \"the purpose of the new association is to promote the game of hockey among the three [[Anglo-Saxons|Anglo-Saxon]] nations\".<ref>{{cite news|title=New Controlling Body Formed At C.A.H.A. Meet|last=Clarke|first=Robert|date=April 16, 1940|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=15|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-apr-16-1940-1471642/}}{{free access}}</ref> The new organization replaced the [[International Ice Hockey Federation|Ligue Internationale de Hockey sur Glace]] (LIHG) which was inactive due to [[World War II]]. Dudley succeeded Hardy as president of the CAHA on April 17, 1940.<ref>{{cite news|title=Juggling Allan Cup Games When Complaints Made|date=April 17, 1940|newspaper=Brandon Daily Sun|location=Brandon, Manitoba|page=4 |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-apr-17-1940-1546893/}}{{free access}}</ref> After Dudley became president, the CAHA definition of amateur was changed to \"an amateur hockey player is one who has not engaged in, or is not engaged in, organized professional hockey\". The question of whether the [[International Olympic Committee]] (IOC) would accept the new definition, was postponed when the [[1940 Winter Olympics]] were cancelled. Dudley later stated, \"If the Olympics are revived after the war, Canada will want to send a team, of course. But if our rules prove unacceptable to Olympic officials, I guess we'll stay at home\".<ref>''Young, Scott (1989)'', p. 192</ref> The decision was the first of several times that Canada threatened to withdraw from [[ice hockey at the Olympic Games]] or the [[Ice Hockey World Championships]] over regulations on international ice hockey.<ref name=\"Young-p157\" />\n\nIn June 1940, the CAHA executive approved a grant of $10,000 to the [[Government of Canada]] for the war effort. The CAHA chose to continue operations as usual to maintain the morale of Canadians during the war, and would offer any assistance needed for military sports teams.<ref>{{cite news|title=C.A.H.A. Votes $10,000 For War Effort|date=June 20, 1940|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=17|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jun-20-1940-1546903/}}{{free access}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=C.A.H.A. Will Give $10,000 to Aid Canada War Effort|date=June 20, 1940|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=17|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jun-20-1940-1471663/}}{{free access}}</ref> Dudley asked for provincial branches of the CAHA to assist in organizing a national \"hockey night\" to raise funds for patriotic services.<ref>{{cite news|title=Inter-Provincial Set-Up Approved B.C. Hockey Body|date=November 11, 1940|newspaper=Lethbridge Herald|location=Lethbridge, Alberta|page=9|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-nov-11-1940-1546921/}}{{free access}}</ref> He later abandoned plans to benefit the [[Canadian Red Cross]], since it was against Red Cross policy to do promotional work.<ref>{{cite news|title=C.A.H.A. Stops Red Cross Plans|date=January 1, 1941|newspaper=Winnipeg, Manitoba|location=|page=11|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jan-01-1941-1548591/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nIn September 1940, the International Ice Hockey Association and the NHL reached a new professional-amateur agreement. The NHL promised to pay $500 for each amateur player signed, which included $250 at signing, then another $250 after playing in the NHL. Dudley sat on the committee to oversee relations and player movement with the NHL. The agreement included provisions for tryouts without having to commit, and the reinstatement of a former professional player as an amateur if no professional team claimed him.<ref>{{cite news|title=N.H.L. and C.A.H.A. Settle Amateur Feud|date=September 13, 1940|newspaper=Medicine Hat News|location=Medicine Hat, Alberta|page=3|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-sep-13-1940-1546907/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nDudley stated at the CAHA executive meeting in January 1941, called for more consistent interpretation of the playing rules with respect to physical play, which was one of the biggest problems facing amateur hockey in Canada.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hockey Heads Gather For Convention|date=January 3, 1941|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=13 |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jan-03-1941-1548592/}}{{free access}}</ref> He also stressed that supporting the International Ice Hockey Association was a means to protect the CAHA against the positions of other organizations.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rules, Playdowns Discussed At C.A.H.A. Meeting|date=January 4, 1941|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=21|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jan-04-1941-1548593/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nThe 1941 CAHA annual meeting was held in [[Calgary]], in conjunction with the International Ice Hockey Association.<ref>{{cite news|title=C.A.H.A. Begins Annual Meeting In Calgary|date=April 12, 1941|newspaper=Lethbridge Herald|location=Lethbridge, Alberta|page=16|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-apr-12-1941-1548597/}}{{free access}}</ref> The constitution was updated to allow for charitable donations and educational grants, and the CAHA to donate 25 per cent of profits from playoffs to wartime charities. Dudley arranged for bonuses to players from the playoffs profits based on the number of games played. Dudley was granted a $1,000 honorarium for expenses for negotiating agreements with the NHL.<ref>{{cite news|title=Set Time Limits For Replacements|date=April 15, 1941|newspaper=Lethbridge Herald|location=Lethbridge, Alberta|page=10|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-apr-15-1941-1548598/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\n===Second term===\n[[File:Allan Cup.jpg|thumb|Dudley donated a portion of profits from the Allan Cup playoffs (''trophy pictured'') to the Government of Canada for the war effort.|alt=Allan Cup trophy]]\n\nDudley was re-elected president of the CAHA on April 16, 1941.<ref>{{cite news|title=Officers Of C.A.H.A. Re-elected|date=April 16, 1941|newspaper=Lethbridge Herald|location=Lethbridge, Alberta|page=18|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-apr-16-1941-1548599/}}{{free access}}</ref> He and Hardy met with officials from the [[Hockey Qu\u00e9bec|Quebec Amateur Hockey Association]] (QAHA) in June 1941, to approve in principle a new playoff scheme overseen by a new committee for the QAHA, the [[Hockey Eastern Ontario|Ottawa District Hockey Association]], and the [[Maritime Amateur Hockey Association]]. The new committee was proposed to be more financially efficient, give more money to Eastern teams, and to be voted on at the next general meeting.<ref>{{cite news|title=C.A.H.A. Says Okay to New Branch|date=June 9, 1941|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=17|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jun-09-1941-1548607/}}{{free access}}</ref> \n\nThe CAHA executive approved a $10,000 purchase of [[Canada Savings Bond|Victory Bonds]] for the war effort.<ref>{{cite news|title=C.A.H.A. Buys Bonds|date=June 13, 1941|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=17 |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jun-13-1941-1548608/}}{{free access}}</ref> Dudley reiterated that the CAHA would assist the Canadian government where possible, and would bend the agreement with the NHL to allow for younger players to be signed who were not subject to travel restrictions or military service.<ref>{{cite news|title=LaFleche Receives Puckmen|date=September 27, 1941|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=25|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-sep-27-1941-1548611/}}{{free access}}</ref> \n\nWhen NHL players were denied passports, the CAHA asked for permission from the NHL reinstate those players temporarily as amateurs.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ask Temporary Re-Instatement|date=September 27, 1941|newspaper=Medicine Hat Daily News|location=Medicine Hat, Alberta|page=9|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-sep-27-1941-1548610/}}{{free access}}</ref> Dudley advised those who wanted to be reinstated as amateurs due to travel restrictions, needed a release from the NHL.<ref>{{cite news|title=Pros. Must Take Reinstatment Cases To Calder|date=November 6, 1941|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=18|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-nov-06-1941-1548621/}}{{free access}}</ref> The CAHA rules committee formally ratified the NHL rules for use in Canadian amateur leagues, as of October 1941.<ref>{{cite news|title=C.A.H.A. Ratifies N.H.L. Playing Rules|date=October 20, 1941|newspaper=Lethbridge Herald|location=Lethbridge, Alberta|page=10|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-oct-20-1941-1548613/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nDudley estimated that registration in the CAHA was 25 per cent less than before the war, but stated that the Canadian government still supported the continuation of hockey as a morale boost.<ref>{{cite news|title=C.A.H.A. Plans To Carry On, States Dudley|date=January 9, 1942|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=5 |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jan-09-1942-1551432/}}{{free access}}</ref> He urged for clubs in Canada to have special games to raise funds for war organizations, and for the CAHA branches to incorporate military teams into schedules where possible. In January 1942, the CAHA donated an additional $10,000 to the government for the war effort.<ref>{{cite news|title=Memorial Cup Final Here If Manitoba Wins Western Junior Puck Crown|date=January 12, 1942|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=12 |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jan-12-1942-1551462/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nDudley anticipated a greater demand by the NHL for junior players due to the war, and wished to co-operate.<ref name=\"apr-20-1942\">{{cite news|title=Hockey Association Adopts Wartime Economy Programme|date=April 20, 1942|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=15|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-apr-20-1942-1552272/}}{{free access}}</ref> He expected difficulty in operating [[senior ice hockey]] next season, and speculated that season schedules and playoffs may need to be shortened due to lack of players, but was committed to continuing hockey.<ref>{{cite news|title=War Will Smack Seniors Next Year|date=March 26, 1942|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=14|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-mar-26-1942-1551498/}}{{free access}}</ref> He defended the CAHA policy of reinstating former professionals as amateurs, despite it strengthening [[Royal Canadian Air Force]] (RCAF) teams compared to club teams during the wartime.<ref>{{cite news|title=George Dudley Answers Critics|date=March 28, 1942|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=22 |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-mar-28-1942-1552173/}}{{free access}}</ref> During the war he stated, \"young men capable of playing hockey are capable of either being in the armed services or in some necessary industry\".<ref>{{cite news|title=No More Pay-For-Play Puck Chasing|date=April 17, 1942|newspaper=Lethbridge Herald|location=Lethbridge, Alberta|page=3|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-apr-17-1942-1552230/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nBy April 1942, the CAHA and its branches combined donated over $50,000 to the war effort, which included proceeds from [[Allan Cup]] and Memorial Cup playoffs, and exhibition games.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hockey's Aid To War Effort Over $50,000|date=April 20, 1942|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=7|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-apr-20-1942-1552270/}}{{free access}}</ref> To save money, the CAHA reduced travel and hospital allowances, and eliminated playoffs series which would not be profitable.<ref name=\"apr-20-1942\" />\n\n==CAHA past-president==\n[[File:Memorial Cup at the 2015 championship.jpg|thumb|Dudley served as a trustee of the Memorial Cup after he was CAHA president.<ref name=\"Legends\" />|alt=The Memorial Cup trophy]]\n\nDudley assumed the role of CAHA past-president, when he was succeeded by [[Frank F. Sargent]] as president in April 1942.<ref name=\"CAHA-p117\">''Canadian Amateur Hockey Association (1990)'', p. 117</ref> Dudley sat on the relations committee with the NHL, which agreed in principle that an amateur may turn professional at any time due to wartime conditions.<ref>{{cite news|title=May Turn Pro. At Any Time|last=Young|first=Scott|author-link=Scott Young (writer)|date=August 22, 1942|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=19 |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-aug-22-1942-1552360/}}{{free access}}</ref> In August, he announced plans by [[Lionel Conacher]], the sports director for the RCAF to have teams play in senior ice hockey leagues, based at all RCAF commands across Canada. Dudley was hopeful that the [[Canadian Army]] and the [[Royal Canadian Navy]] would do the same.<ref>{{cite news|title=Air Force Plans Hockey Teams Across Canada|date=August 8, 1942|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=18|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-aug-08-1942-1552325/}}{{free access}}</ref> \n\nIn April 1943, Dudley recommended that payments from the NHL for signing amateurs be deferred until players lost due to the wartime enlistments return to professional hockey. He suggested the adjustment in light of many players enlisting recently after becoming professional.<ref>{{cite news|title=$38,000 Profit In Puck Series|date=April 26, 1943|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=16|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-apr-26-1943-1552919/}}{{free access}}</ref> Due to the war, 75 per cent of the amateurs signed by the NHL ended up in the armed services. The CAHA filled out rosters with amateurs exempt from military service who were married men over age 30. The professional-amateur agreement was renegotiated and the NHL agreed to pay a flat rate of $500 to the CAHA. Dudley conceded that the deal was not as good as before, but it was adequate due to the war.<ref>''Young, Scott (1989)'', pp. 198\u2013199</ref>\n\nIn June 1943, Dudley and Frank Sargent met with the Canadian armed services to discuss future organization of military ice hockey teams in Canada.<ref>{{cite news|title=May Change Service Setup|date=June 14, 1943|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=15|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jun-14-1943-1552923/}}{{free access}}</ref> The RCAF withdrew its teams from the CAHA in January 1944, despite attempts to negotiate a delayed withdrawal at the end of the season.<ref>{{cite news|title=Edict On Hockey Expected Today|date=January 6, 1944|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=10 |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jan-06-1944-1552992/}}{{free access}}</ref> He reported that despite the withdrawal due to a change in armed services policies, praise was given to the CAHA for its assistance.<ref>{{cite news|title=27,271 Players Registered|date=April 11, 1944|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=25 |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-apr-11-1944-1552993/}}{{free access}}</ref> He expected there to be no military service teams competing within the CAHA during the 1944\u201345 season.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dudley Says Hockey Outlook Not Bright|date=June 28, 1944|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=32|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jun-28-1944-1552995/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nIn April 1944, Dudley and W. G. Hardy considered the International Ice Hockey Association overseeing international senior ice hockey championships between the CAHA and AHAUS.<ref>{{cite news|title=C.A.H.A. Plans New Replacement Rule|date=April 13, 1944|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=33|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-apr-13-1944-1552994/}}{{free access}}</ref> In August 1944, [[the Canadian Press]] reported Dudley as having \"considerable support\" to replace [[Red Dutton]] as president of the NHL.<ref>{{cite news|title=N.H.L. Seeks New Leader|date=August 24, 1944|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=19|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-aug-24-1944-1552996/}}{{free access}}</ref> Similar rumors surfaced again by the Canadian Press in May 1945.<ref>{{cite news|title=Canadian Sport Snapshorts|last=Thomas|first=Syd|date=May 22, 1945|newspaper=Brandon Daily Sun|location=Brandon, Manitoba|page=3|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-may-22-1945-1553008/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nIn November 1944, Dudley attempted to mediate a dispute between the [[Quebec Senior Hockey League]] (QSHL) which operated outside of CAHA jurisdiction, and the Ottawa District Hockey Association which denied permission for a team from [[Hull, Quebec]] to play in the QSHL. He decided that no players would be suspended from the CAHA while talks were ongoing.<ref>{{cite news|title=Early Solution in League Dispute is Likelihood Soon|date=November 6, 1944|newspaper=Brandon Daily Sun|location=Brandon, Manitoba|page=4|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-nov-06-1944-1552997/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\n==CAHA secretary==\n[[File:International Hockey Hall of Fame.jpg|thumb|In 1945, Dudley announced CAHA contributions towards the construction of a facility for the Original Hockey Hall of Fame.<ref name=\"apr-17-1945\">{{cite news|title=Nova Scotia Man New Puck Prexy|date=April 17, 1945|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=12|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-apr-17-1945-1553004/}}{{free access}}</ref> The building ''(pictured)'' opened in 1965, in [[Kingston, Ontario]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.originalhockeyhalloffame.com/about/|title=The History of the Original Hockey Hall of Fame|year=2020|website=Original Hockey Hall of Fame|access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>|alt=Original Hockey Hall of Fame building]]\n\nOn April 17, 1945, Dudley was elected secretary of the International Ice Hockey Association.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hanson Dowell Heads C.A.H.A.|date=April 17, 1945|newspaper=Lethbridge Herald|location=Lethbridge, Alberta|page=8 |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-apr-17-1945-1475471/}}{{free access}}</ref> On the same day, Dudley was elected secretary of the CAHA to succeed [[F. H. Marples]]. Dudley's role as past-president was filled by Frank Sargent, when [[Hanson Dowell]] became president. The CAHA arranged to give 25 per cent of its annual proceeds towards building a facility for the [[Original Hockey Hall of Fame]], and Dudley expected that amount to be $4,000 to $5,000.<ref name=\"apr-17-1945\" />\n\nAfter the war ended, Dudley announced that the CAHA and the NHL would revert to the pre-war agreement not to sign any junior players without permission. He also stated that tryout contracts must be honoured, and junior-aged players on NHL reserve lists must be reinstated as amateurs to return to the CAHA. The wartime practice of the NHL borrowing amateur players for three games or less was discontinued.<ref>{{cite news|title=Pros Agree Not To Sign Juniors|date=September 19, 1945|newspaper=Medicine Hat Daily News|location=Medicine Hat, Alberta|page=5|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-sep-19-1945-1553012/}}{{free access}}</ref> Dudley participated in discussions to update the financial terms of the agreement. The NHL offered a flat payment of $20,000 to signing amateurs, which Dudley felt it was too low.<ref>{{cite news|title=C.A.H.A. Wants Best Deal Possible|date=May 17, 1946|newspaper=Lethbridge Herald|location=Lethbridge, Alberta|page=11|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-may-17-1971-1526358/}}{{free access}}</ref> The CAHA ultimately accepted the lump sum payment, preferring not to break its alliance with the NHL.<ref>{{cite news|title=C.A.H.A. and N.H.L. Reach Hockey Player Agreement|date=June 20, 1946|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=16|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jun-20-1946-1553878/}}{{free access}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=C.A.H.A. Not Satisfied|date=December 30, 1946|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=20|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-dec-30-1946-1553933/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nDudley co-operated with transfers to assist European ice hockey associations which struggled to find players after the war. The BIHA did not expect to operate in 1946\u201347 season, but the [[Scottish Ice Hockey|Scottish Ice Hockey Association]] planned to operate with the CAHA loaning players.<ref>''McKinley, Michael (2014)'', p. 77</ref> In December 1946, discussions continued for a proposed merger of the International Ice Hockey Association with the LIHG. Dudley felt that any new organization formed should be predominantly Canadian to have more say in international hockey matters. The CAHA sought to have W. G. Hardy nominated as vice-president of the new governing body, and Dudley as its secretary.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dowell Will Attend Hockey Merger Parley|date=December 28, 1946|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=29|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-dec-28-1946-1553923/}}{{free access}}</ref> The merger was agreed to and CAHA president [[Allan Pickard]] stated that the CAHA and AHAUS would operate with autonomy.<ref>{{cite news|title=Harmony Prevails On Hockey Front|last=Clarke|first=Robert|date=May 6, 1947|newspaper=Medicine Hat Daily News|location=Medicine Hat, Alberta|page=3|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-may-06-1947-1462597/}}{{free access}}</ref> The LIHG recognized AHAUS as the governing body of hockey in the United States instead of the [[Amateur Athletic Union]] (AAU). The CAHA was permitted to have its own definition of amateur as long as teams at the Olympic games adhered to existing LIHG rules.<ref>{{cite news|title=C.A.H.A. Gains Few Points At Prague Hockey Confab|date=March 22, 1947|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune |location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=33|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-mar-22-1947-1462563/}}{{free access}}</ref> The new organization was later renamed to the [[International Ice Hockey Federation]] (IIHF).<ref>{{cite news|title=Prof. George Hardy: Author-Educationist |last=Trimmer|first=Bob|date=September 21, 1963|newspaper=Lethbridge Herald|location=Lethbridge, Alberta|page=5 |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-sep-21-1963-1461284/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Ice Hockey World Championships]] resumed in 1947, but Dudley had difficulties finding any team willing to represent Canada. He invited the champions and finalists of both the [[1946 Allan Cup]] and [[1946 Memorial Cup]], but all four teams declined. In addition, the [[Winnipeg Monarchs (MJHL)|Winnipeg Monarchs]] declined the CAHA invite for a European tour. Dudley settled on the Edmonton Junior Canadians, who were the Western Canada junior finalists.<ref>{{cite news|title=Now It's Edmonton|date=December 11, 1946|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=29|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-dec-11-1946-1553918/}}{{free access}}</ref> In December 1946, the CAHA gave an ultimatum to the [[Canadian Olympic Committee|Canadian Olympic Association]] to accept the team put forth under the CAHA definition of amateur, or look to another organization for a team. Dudley said there should be no \"[[pussy]]footing\" on the matter, and reiterated that lost salaries by players was a valid concern.<ref>{{cite news|title=Issue Ultimatum To Olympic Body|date=December 28, 1946|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=16|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-dec-28-1946-1553926/}}{{free access}}</ref> No resolution was found, and Canada did not participate in the [[1947 Ice Hockey World Championships]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hockeyarchives.info/mondial1947.htm|title=Championnats du monde 1947|website=Hockey Archives|language=fr|access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==CAHA secretary-manager==\nThe CAHA added the title of manager to the secretary's role in 1947, and Dudley served as secretary-manager of the CAHA until 1960.<ref name=\"CAHA-p117\" /> The new role made Dudley more influential in Canadian hockey since he served as the regular delegate to IIHF meetings, and was in charge of selecting the [[Canada men's national ice hockey team|Canada men's national team]] and making its travel arrangements to the Ice Hockey World Championships and the Olympic Games.<ref>''Young, Scott (1989)'', p. 218</ref><ref>''Oliver, Greg (2017)'', p. 32</ref> He was named first vice-president of the IIHF and chairman of the North American delegation on July 12, 1957,<ref>{{cite news|title=Dudley Named|date=July 12, 1957|newspaper=Lethbridge Herald|location=Lethbridge, Alberta|page=6 |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jul-12-1957-1562358/}}{{free access}}</ref> and facilitated the first exhibition tours for Soviet teams in Canada.<ref name=\"Legends\" />\n\nDudley was named to the selection committee for two hockey halls of fame. In January 1948, the Original Hockey Hall of Fame increased its board of governors from 9 to 16 people to give better representation across North America, and Dudley was chosen as a new board member.<ref>{{cite news|title=New Shrine Governors Are Named|date=January 31, 1948|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=18|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jan-31-1948-1554404/}}{{free access}}</ref> In January 1958, he was named as one of the nine persons on the selection committee for the [[Hockey Hall of Fame]] in Toronto. The announcement was made after the NHL chose to recognize the Toronto institution instead of the Original Hockey Hall of Fame in Kingston.<ref>{{cite news|title=CNE to Operate Hockey Hall of Fame: Pick Committee to Select NHL Stars|date=January 31, 1958|newspaper=Medicine Hat Daily News|location=Medicine Hat, Alberta|page=9|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jan-31-1958-1563390/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\n===1948 Winter Olympics===\n[[File:RCAF Flyers 1948.JPG|thumb|The Ottawa RCAF Flyers team was the CAHA's answer to the IOC's definition of amateur for ice hockey at the 1948 Winter Olympics.|alt=1948 Ottawa RCAF Flyers team photo]]\n\nDudley was faced with a dilemma in choosing the Canadian representative [[ice hockey at the 1948 Winter Olympics]]. The Canadian Olympic Association wanted an ice hockey team that suited the IOC definition of amateur. He felt obliged to offer the chance to the [[1947 Allan Cup]] champions [[Royal Montreal Hockey Club|Montreal Royals]], would not fit the IOC definition of amateur.<ref>{{cite news|title=Must Conform to I.O.C. Definition to Amateurism|date=July 10, 1947|newspaper=Medicine Hat Daily News|location=Medicine Hat, Alberta|page=3|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jul-10-1947-1554276/}}{{free access}}</ref> In September 1947, he formally invited the Royals to represent Canada, but was unsure if the team would accept.<ref>{{cite news|title=Invited To Olympic Games|date=September 3, 1947|newspaper=Medicine Hat Daily News|location=Medicine Hat, Alberta|page=3 |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-sep-03-1947-1554292/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nDudley attended the IIHF meeting in September to discuss hockey at the Olympics using the IOC definition of amateur, or hosting its own World Championships separate from the Winter Olympics.<ref>{{cite news|title=Olympic Hockey Question Soon Will Be Decided|date=July 5, 1947|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=15|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jul-05-1947-1554275/}}{{free access}}</ref> He remained adamant against the IOC definition and said, \"We decided in Canada 11 years ago that there is too much hypocrisy about amateurism and we've seen no reason to change our view\". IIHF president [[Fritz Kraatz]] reportedly agreed to the IOC definition, if the AHAUS team was recognized by the organizing committee of the Olympics. Since hockey would be the most profitable event at the Olympics, Dudley felt that the Swiss organizing committee would agree to anything as long as the IOC approved.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hockey Politics Are Rampant In Zurich|date=September 10, 1947|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=18|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-sep-10-1947-1554322/}}{{free access}}</ref> To protect the interests of the CAHA, Dudley successfully passed a motion at the IIHF meeting which prevented any Canadian team being accepted at the Olympics without the approval of the CAHA.<ref name=\"sep-17-1947\">{{cite news|title=\"U\" Puckmen May Represent Canada|date=September 17, 1947|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=18|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-sep-17-1947-1554332/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nThe Swiss organizing committee decided that any team sent must adhere to IOC definition of amateur, and live up to the [[Olympic Oath]].<ref name=\"oct-22-1947\">{{cite news|title=Puck Moguls Rapped For R.C.A.F. Choice|date=October 22, 1947|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=17|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-oct-22-1947-1554335/}}{{free access}}</ref> The Canadian Olympic Association wanted to send a team of college hockey players to represent Canada, instead of a club team.<ref name=\"sep-17-1947\" /> The CAHA went to the RCAF for a solution, and invited its [[Ottawa RCAF Flyers]] team to represent Canada. The choice was criticized by Dave Dryburgh of the ''[[Regina Leader-Post]]'' who wrote that it would a third-rate team and said, \"Any time Canada cannot send its best hockey team to the Olympics it shouldn't send one at all\".<ref name=\"oct-22-1947\" /> Dudley sought reinforcements to strengthen the team before they sailed to Europe on January 1948, and stated the CAHA would pay to fly players to Switzerland if necessary.<ref>{{cite news|title=R.C.A.F. Puck Team Seeks Reinforcements|date=December 18, 1947|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=18 |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-dec-18-1947-1554349/}}{{free access}}</ref> Eight players were eventually added to the team, and Dudley felt they would adequately represent Canada, even if they might not be as strong as previous Canadian national teams.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hockey Official Views Olympic Team Line-Up|date=January 8, 1948|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=3|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jan-08-1948-1554394/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 102-00789, St. Moritz, Eisstadion.jpg|thumb|Outdoor stadium used for ice hockey at the 1948 Winter Olympics in [[St. Moritz]]|alt=Olympic ice rink in St. Moritz]]\n\nThe status of ice hockey at the 1948 Winter Olympics was threatened when the [[United States Olympic & Paralympic Committee|United States Olympic Committee]] led by [[Avery Brundage]] threatened to boycott the Olympics if an AHAUS team was recognized instead of an AAU team.<ref>{{cite news|title=Yank Puck Bodies Are Feudin' And Fightin'|date=November 8, 1947|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=22|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-nov-08-1947-1554343/}}{{free access}}</ref><ref name=\"dec-04-1947\">{{cite news|title=Brundage Bluffing, Charges Ahearne|date=December 4, 1947|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=19|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-dec-04-1947-1554347/}}{{free access}}</ref> The IIHF executive met again and agreed that its teams would not play against a team chosen by the AAU.<ref name=\"dec-04-1947\" /> Dudley again stated that the IIHF should host its own World Championships separate from the Olympics if differences could not be resolved. He was assured by the IIHF that such a tournament could be arranged on 48 hours' notice.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dudley Agrees To Federation Title Proposal|date=January 7, 1948|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=26|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jan-07-1948-1554391/}}{{free access}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Bitter, Long-Drawn Out Olympic Hockey Controversy Still Rages|date=January 27, 1948|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=12|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jan-27-1948-1554401/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nThe night before the Olympics began, it was decided to allow the AHAUS team to play in the tournament, but the IOC declared that games played by the United States team would not count in the standings.<ref>{{cite news|title='Squawk' Valley Hassles 'Duck Soup'|last=Sullivan|first=Jack|date=February 23, 1960|newspaper=Brandon Sun|location=Brandon, Manitoba|page=7 |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-feb-23-1960-1536343/}}{{free access}}</ref> The day before the tournament ended, the IOC decided that the winner would be recognized as Olympic champion, except for the United States team. Dudley felt that the winner would have been recognized as a world champion, whether or not the IOC recognized it.<ref>{{cite news|title=Czech-Flyers Tied: Olympic Heads To Recognize Puck Games|date=February 7, 1948|newspaper=Lethbridge Herald|location=Lethbridge, Alberta|page=17 |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-feb-07-1948-1554410/}}{{free access}}</ref> The Ottawa RCAF Flyers completed the tournament with seven wins and a draw, to capture the gold medal for Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hockeyarchives.info/JO1948.htm|title=Jeux Olympiques de Saint-Moritz 1948|website=Hockey Archives|language=fr|access-date=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter the Olympics, Dudley arranged for the Ottawa RCAF Flyers to complete an exhibition game schedule to raise funds to cover travel expenses.<ref>{{cite news|title=Flyers To Sail March 31|date=March 2, 1948|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune |location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=14|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-mar-02-1948-1554415/}}{{free access}}</ref> He stated that the 1948 Olympic hockey tournament was played in \"ridiculous weather conditions\" with poor [[Official (ice hockey)|refereeing]]. He advocated to only attended international events on artificial ice, which would showcase Canada's true abilities. He felt that the IOC should be composed of members appointed by national sports bodies who would be more knowledgeable of sport, instead of a person who was disconnected from the game appointing his or her own replacement.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dudley Scorns Olympic Hockey|date=March 20, 1948|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=18|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-mar-20-1948-1554419/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\n===1949 to 1951===\n[[File:1954 Topps Danny Lewicki.JPG|thumb|Danny Lewicki|alt=Danny Lewicki]]\n\nIn January 1949, the Canadian Olympic Association sought government grants towards the development of amateur sport. Dudley was opposed the use of tax dollars to fund sports, on the premise that the government would be in control of the sports associations, instead of those persons directly involved in the sport.<ref>{{cite news|title=Blasts Rock Discussion|date=January 8, 1949|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=17|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jan-08-1949-1554814/}}{{free access}}</ref> He also felt that politicians would inevitably use sport for political advantage.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sports Leaders Want Government To Give|date=January 10, 1949|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=16|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jan-10-1949-1554824/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Sudbury Wolves]] were chosen to represent Canada at the [[1949 Ice Hockey World Championships]], and placed second to the [[Czechoslovakia men's national ice hockey team]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hockeyarchives.info/mondial1949.htm|title=Championnats du monde 1949|website=Hockey Archives|language=fr|access-date=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn April 1949, [[Danny Lewicki]] was the focus of whether or not a minor can be signed to a contract known as a \"C\" form, and it be enforced when he became 18 years old. Dudley stated that if the player refused to report to an amateur club chosen by the professional club, he could then be offered a professional contract. Refusal of the professional contract would result in his suspension from the CAHA, as per agreements with the NHL.<ref>{{cite news|title=Lewicki Case Starts C Clause Talk Anew|date=April 7, 1949|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=20|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-apr-07-1949-1554882/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nIn response to accusations by the [[Canadian Teachers' Federation]] in August 1949, that the CAHA was wrecking high school hockey and placing youths away from home away from parental control, Dudley stated that the claims were nonsense, that he had received no complaints from parents, and asked for the claims to be substantiated.<ref>{{cite news|title=\"Tyranny\" Charges Face Hockey|date=August 12, 1949|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=15|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-aug-12-1949-1554939/}}{{free access}}</ref> A survey later that year by the [[Canadian Education Association]], concluded that the effect of hockey on education was not a national problem. Dudley opted to participated in discussions to minimize any effects of hockey on education.<ref>{{cite news|title=Schools Have Hockey Not \"Hookey\" Trouble|date=November 24, 1949|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=23|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-nov-24-1949-1554951/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Edmonton Mercurys]] were chosen to represent Canada at the [[1950 Ice Hockey World Championships]], and went undefeated to win the title.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hockeyarchives.info/mondial1950.htm|title=Championnats du monde 1950|website=Hockey Archives|language=fr|access-date=March 19, 2020}}</ref> The [[Lethbridge Maple Leafs]] represented Canada at the [[1951 Ice Hockey World Championships]], and were also undefeated in defending Canada's world title.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hockeyarchives.info/mondial1951.htm|title=Championnats du monde 1951|website=Hockey Archives|language=fr|access-date=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nEarly in 1951, the OHA was faced with a mutiny in senior ice hockey in Kingston. Dudley recommended an inquiry into why a group of six players wanted to transfer from an existing new to a new team, along with the coach. After an inquiry, he and fellow OHA executives [[Jack Roxburgh]], [[Frank Buckland (ice hockey)|Frank Buckland]] and W. A. Hewitt, handed out a lifetime suspension to [[George Patterson (ice hockey)|George Patterson]] who coached Kingston's senior B-level team, for conspiring to deliberately lose a playoff series to avoid moving into a higher-level of playoffs, rather than staying in a lower level and potentially make more profits at home playoff games than on the road.<ref>''Young, Scott (1989)'', pp. 205\u2013209</ref> \n\nIn June 1951, Dudley confirmed that the [[Hockey Newfoundland and Labrador|Newfoundland Amateur Hockey Association]] wanted to join the CAHA as its own branch, instead of part of the Maritime Amateur Hockey Association. No agreement was reached, and Dudley sought continued discussion.<ref>{{cite news|title=Newfoundland Not Interested In C.A.H.A. Tie|date=June 1, 1951|newspaper=Corner Brook Western Star|location=Corner Brook, Newfoundland |page=17|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jun-01-1951-1556002/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\n===1952 Winter Olympics===\n[[File:Jersey of the Edmonton Mercurys.jpg|thumb|The Edmonton Mercurys ''(team jersey pictured)'' represented Canada in ice hockey at the 1952 Winter Olympics.|alt=Edmonton Mercurys hockey jersey]]\n\nDiscussions began in 1950, whether or not ice hockey would be included in the [[1952 Winter Olympics]] hosted in [[Oslo]]. The IOC sought assurance that participating teams would adhere to its amateur code rather than what was accepted by the IIHF, and also wanted to exclude IIHF president Fritz Kraatz from negotiations. Dudley and W. G. Hardy agreed there would be no negotiations on those terms, nor would they repudiate Kraatz. Dudley referred to the IOC as dictatorial and undemocratic, and expected the IIHF to discuss having its own 1952 Ice Hockey World Championships instead. He further stated that the Olympics would be a financial failure without the inclusion of hockey.<ref>{{cite news|title=International Puck Bodies Widely Split|date=May 18, 1950|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=17|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-may-18-1950-1555023/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\n[[Ice hockey at the 1952 Winter Olympics]] ultimately went ahead, and the Edmonton Mercurys represented Canada again by winning the gold medal.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hockeyarchives.info/JO1952.htm|title=Jeux Olympiques d'Oslo 1952|website=Hockey Archives|language=fr|access-date=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===1952 to 1953===\nDudley supported a resolution at the 1952 CAHA general meeting which prevented the eastward transfer of players, to prevent rosters in Western Canada from being depleted by clubs in the more populated areas of Eastern Canada. He wanted to have protective measures in place, before renegotiating the professional-amateur agreement.<ref>{{cite news|title=Pro-Amateur Contract To Be Reviewed Today|date=June 17, 1952|newspaper=Medicine Hat News|location=Medicine Hat, Alberta|page=3|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jun-17-1952-1556012/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nCanada did not participate in the [[1953 Ice Hockey World Championships]]. On January 12, 1953, CAHA president [[W. B. George]] stated that, \"Every year we spend $10,000 to send a Canadian hockey team to Europe to play 40 exhibition games. All these games are played to packed houses that only enrich European hockey coffers. In return we are subjected to constant, unnecessary abuse over our Canadian style of play\".<ref>''Duplacey, James (1998)'', p. [https://archive.org/details/totalhockeyoffic0000unse/page/503 503]</ref>  \n\nIn March 1953, the CAHA suspended the QAHA after a dispute stemming from a Quebec registration certificate being issued a player who was under suspension by the CAHA. An ultimatum was given to teams in leagues affiliated with the QAHA to follow the CAHA if they wished to participate in playoffs for national championships, or remain under QAHA jurisdiction.<ref name=\"mar-13-1953\">{{cite news|title=All Quebec Leagues Are Suspended|date=March 13, 1953|newspaper=Brandon Daily Sun|location=Brandon, Manitoba|page=11 |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-mar-13-1953-1559042/}}{{free access}}</ref> Dudley published newspaper advertisements on behalf of the CAHA to notify of the decision.<ref name=\"mar-09-1953\">{{cite news|title=Quebec Senior Loop To Operate Independently|date=March 9, 1953|newspaper=Lethbridge Herald|location=Lethbridge, Alberta|page=7 |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-mar-09-1953-1559036/}}{{free access}}</ref> After the deadline, Dudley announced the suspension of all leagues and teams affiliated with the QAHA,<ref name=\"mar-13-1953\" /> except for the QSHL which resigned its provincial affiliation to operate independently of the QAHA and the CAHA.<ref name=\"mar-09-1953\" /> \n\nDudley was confident that issues could be resolved at the 1953 CAHA general meeting.<ref>{{cite news|title=Puck Groups Gather To Try End Divorce|last=Wheatley|first=W. R.|date=May 11, 1953|newspaper=Lethbridge Herald|location=Lethbridge, Alberta|page=6 |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-may-11-1953-1559073/}}{{free access}}</ref> He wanted the QAHA to return without any punitive damages, but with assurance there would be no recurrence of the infraction.<ref>{{cite news|title=Chastised Quebec Coming 'Home'|date=May 12, 1953|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=20|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-may-12-1953-1559075/}}{{free access}}</ref> The QAHA was reinstated, and Dudley urged for the CAHA executive to follow the rules consistently when it came to player replacements in playoffs, instead of making arbitrary decisions.<ref>{{cite news|title=CAHA Makes Some Rule Changes|last=Wheatley|first=W. R.|date=May 13, 1953|newspaper=Lethbridge Herald |location=Lethbridge, Alberta|page=10|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-may-13-1953-1559079/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\n===1954 World Championships===\n[[File:1954 World Ice Hockey Championships Canada vs Soviet.jpg|thumb|Canada versus the Soviet Union at the 1954 Ice Hockey World Championships|alt=Hockey action photo]]\n\nThe CAHA planned on returning to the Ice Hockey World Championships in 1954, but Dudley had difficulties again in finding a team willing to represent Canada. He eventually arranged for the [[East York Lyndhursts]] from a senior B-level league in Ontario to attend the [[1954 Ice Hockey World Championships]], after several A-level senior teams declined due to the financial strain of travel, and players being away from work. The announcement was made in October 1953, and received little press coverage at the time.<ref>''Young, Scott (1989)'', pp. 218\u2013219</ref> In January 1954, he sent reinforcements from higher-level senior teams to strengthen the roster, including [[Don Lockhart]], [[Eric Unger]], [[Tom Jamieson]], and [[Bill Shill]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Lyndhursts Whip Germany Reinforcements On Way|date=January 15, 1954|newspaper=Medicine Hat News|location=Medicine Hat, Alberta|page=16|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jan-15-1954-1560208/}}{{free access}}</ref> Dudley said that choosing the national representative was an annual problem, and the cost of sending A-level teams was getting prohibitive. He arranged an exhibition schedule in Europe to acclimatize the team to the international rules of play, and raise funds from tickets to exhibition games to cover travel costs. The 1954 Ice Hockey World Championships was the first time the [[Soviet Union national ice hockey team|Soviet Union national team]] would participate, and he speculated they would finish no better than fourth place.<ref>{{cite news|title=Thistles To Tour In Japan|date=January 11, 1954|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=14|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jan-11-1954-1560194/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nCanada lost in the final game by a 7\u20132 score to the Soviets. The loss was described as a \"black eye\" to Canada, a \"catastrophe\" and \"a national calamity\". The CAHA and Dudley were highly criticized by the media in Canada for sending a B-level senior team to international competition. Dudley invited suggestions on how to better form the team, and reiterated the prohibitive costs of sending A-level teams. He stated that the timing of the world championships coincided with playoffs in Canada, and that no A-level team would agree to leave at a critical team in their season. He also said that the profits from the Allan Cup and Memorial Cup playoffs would not sustain the annual cost of flying a team to Europe to shorten the time away from playing in Canada.<ref>{{cite news|title=CAHA Comes Under Brisk Criticism|date=March 9, 1954|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=18|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-mar-09-1954-1560227/}}{{free access}}</ref> He also considered inviting the Soviet Union national ice hockey team to tour Canada as a goodwill gesture, and since increased interest in seeing the Soviet team play would make it profitable.<ref>{{cite news|title=Red Invasion Possible: Players May Tour Canada|date=March 10, 1954|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=1|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-mar-10-1954-1560234/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\n===1955 World Championships===\n[[Image:IIHFChampionshipTrophy19531959.jpg|right|thumb|upright=0.7|Trophy awarded for winning the Ice Hockey World Championships during the 1950s|alt=World Championship trophy]]\n\nIn July 1954, Dudley was confident the criticism of choosing the national team would end, after he announced that the [[1954 Allan Cup]] champion [[Penticton Vees (senior)|Penticton Vees]] were chosen to represent Canada at the [[1955 Ice Hockey World Championships]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Penticton V's To Represent Canada In World Hockey|date=July 19, 1954|newspaper=Brandon Daily Sun|location=Brandon, Manitoba|page=4|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jul-19-1954-1560313/}}{{free access}}</ref> He predicted that Penticton would win regain the championship for Canada, and that there would be more pressure on the Soviet team than Canada's team.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dudley Says That Russians Have to Win, or Else|date=September 27, 1954 |newspaper=Lethbridge Herald|location=Lethbridge, Alberta|page=6|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-sep-27-1954-1560320/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nIn November 1954, the CAHA received an invitation for a Canadian team to tour the Soviet Union. Dudley said the request came too late to change existing schedules to accommodate the request.<ref>{{cite news|title=Find Too Late Change Schedule|date=November 24, 1954|newspaper=Medicine Hat News|location=Medicine Hat, Alberta|page=5|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-nov-24-1954-1560330/}}{{free access}}</ref> The CAHA deferred the proposal of a Canadian tour of the Soviet Union until after the World Championships which was a higher priority, despite the willingness of the [[Winnipeg Maroons (ice hockey)|Winnipeg Maroons]] to accept the Soviet invitation.<ref>{{cite news|title=CAHA Not Interested|date=December 17, 1954|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=33|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-dec-17-1954-1560341/}}{{free access}}</ref> The Penticton Vees won all eight played the 1955 Ice Hockey World Championships to regain the title for Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hockeyarchives.info/mondial1955.htm|title=Championnats du monde 1955|website=Hockey Archives|language=fr|access-date=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAt the CAHA general meeting in May 1955, Dudley proposed regulations to include television broadcasts rights in addition to the radio broadcast fees the CAHA collects for amateur games.<ref>{{cite news|title=CAHA To Govern Minor Hockey TV|date=May 23, 1955|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=15|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-may-23-1955-1561496/}}{{free access}}</ref> He proposed a 10 cent-per-ticket fee for all games in Canada towards the national team's fund. He reported interest by private company to sponsor the team, and that the CAHA's insurance company proposed to sponsor the printing of CAHA rule books. Dudley said he was not enthusiastic about sending teams to international events, but felt obligated to send a team to the upcoming Winter Olympics.<ref>{{cite news|title=CAHA Cuts Expected Olympic Help Seen |last=Hanright|first=Don|date=May 24, 1955|newspaper=Medicine Hat News|location=Medicine Hat, Alberta|page=6 |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-may-24-1955-1561505/}}{{free access}}</ref> In regards to whether the IOC would accept a Canadian senior team, he mentioned it was possible to have university and college players quickly registered with the CAHA if needed.<ref>{{cite news|title=Canadian Olympic Team Has Problems|date=May 27, 1955|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=33|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-may-27-1955-1561563/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\n===1956 Winter Olympics===\nIn August 1955, Dudley announced that the [[1955 Allan Cup]] champions [[Berlin Dutchmen|Kitchener-Waterloo Dutchmen]] were selected to represent Canada in [[ice hockey at the 1956 Winter Olympics]]. The customary exhibition tour would be omitted, and the team would fly to Europe. Plans to finance the trip included a national hockey week in Canada during the Olympics, in which 10 cents from each ticket sold would go to the CAHA.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dutchmen Get Olympic Berth|date=August 22, 1955|newspaper=Lethbridge Herald|location=Lethbridge, Alberta|page=6|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-aug-22-1955-1561587/}}{{free access}}</ref> The Soviets invited Canada to play an exhibition series in Moscow after the Olympics, and Dudley replied that the Soviet Union would need to pay more of Canada's expenses to make it worthwhile.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dutchies Interested In Playing In Soviet|date=January 14, 1956|newspaper=Lethbridge Herald|location=Lethbridge, Alberta|page=6|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jan-14-1956-1562001/}}{{free access}}</ref> The Dutchmen won six games during the Olympic hockey tournament, but losses to the Soviet Union and the United States earned a bronze medal for Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hockeyarchives.info/JO1956.htm|title=Jeux Olympiques de Cortina d'Ampezzo 1956|website=Hockey Archives|language=fr|access-date=March 19, 2020}}</ref> Despite the result, Dudley felt that the Dutchmen were the best team Canada had sent to the Olympics since World War II. In response to calls for an all-star team being sent instead, he stated that 90 per cent of senior hockey teams in Canada operated at a deficit, and taking away their best players for an all-star team would be detrimental to their ticket sales. He again mentioned the possibility of hosting the Soviet national team on a tour of Canada.<ref>{{cite news|title=CAHA May Ask Reds Tour Canada in '56|date=February 6, 1956|newspaper=Lethbridge Herald|location=Lethbridge, Alberta|page=7|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-feb-06-1956-1562018/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\n===1956 to 1957===\n[[File:Szent Istv\u00e1n k\u00f6r\u00fat a Falk Miksa (N\u00e9phadsereg) utca fel\u0151l a Honv\u00e9d utca fel\u00e9 n\u00e9zve. A szovjet csapatok ideiglenes kivonul\u00e1sa 1956. okt\u00f3ber 31-\u00e9n. Fortepan 24787.jpg|thumb|Soviet invasion of Hungary in October 1956|alt=Soviet tanks in Budapest]]\n\nAt the May 1956 general meeting of the CAHA, Dudley stated that development fees received from the NHL amounted to $27,000 in the past season. He encouraged the provincial branches to set aside their differences in the playing rules, as per agreements with the NHL to use similar rules as the professionals.<ref>{{cite news|title=Icing Rule Change Stalls CAHA Meet|date=May 23, 1956|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=26|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-may-23-1956-1562048/}}{{free access}}</ref> The CAHA agreed to send a team to the next Winter Olympics, as long as it was not burdened with the whole cost.<ref>{{cite news|title=Canada Will Be Represented If CAHA Not Saddled with Expense|date=May 24, 1956|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=24|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-may-24-1956-1562055/}}{{free access}}</ref> An agreement was reached in principle to send an all-star team to the 1957 World Championships, based on a core of players from the [[1956 Allan Cup]] champion [[Vernon Canadians]].<ref name=\"may-25-1956\">{{cite news|title=CAHA to Send All-Star Team to Olympic Games|date=May 25, 1956|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=37|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-may-25-1956-1562112/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nDudley felt it was important that Canadians agreed the best possible team was being sent, and that the CAHA should negotiate the best financial arrangements to play abroad.<ref name=\"may-25-1956\" /> He believed an all-star team from senior teams would give the best results at the Olympics and the World Championships, but funding was an issue. A sponsored team based in one city was more cost efficient than combining players from different cities. In an interview with the ''[[Toronto Telegram]]'' he said, \"If we could get the Allan Cup team of the previous year as a nucleus that would be even better, but we'd have to pry the best players loose from other clubs\".<ref>''Oliver, Greg (2017)'', p. 30</ref>\n\nThe CAHA sought $75,000 for training and travel costs for a full-time national team, which Dudley hoped a private sector sponsorship would cover.<ref>{{cite news|title=$75,000 Needed For Puck Meet Expenses|date=August 31, 1956|newspaper=Lethbridge Herald|location=Lethbridge, Alberta|page=6|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-aug-31-1956-1562153/}}{{free access}}</ref> In September 1956, Dudley stated that the offer by a private company was withdrawn.<ref>{{cite news|title=CAHA Has No Sponsor|date=September 8, 1956|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=43|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-sep-08-1956-1562170/}}{{free access}}</ref> The CAHA appealed for donations of $100 from 750 sportspersons to cover the costs.<ref>{{cite news|title=CAHA Seeks Donations|date=September 12, 1956|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=24|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-sep-12-1956-1562177/}}{{free access}}</ref> Dudley stated in October 1956, that fundraising was delayed due to searching for a sponsor.<ref>{{cite news|title=CAHA Asks For Funds|date=October 17, 1956|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=34|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-oct-17-1956-1562183/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nDudley made the announcement in November 1956, that Canada would not send its national team to the 1957 Ice Hockey World Championships due to recent changes in international affairs.<ref>{{cite news|title=Canada To Miss Tourney|date=November 14, 1956|newspaper=Medicine Hat News|location=Medicine Hat, Alberta|page=1|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-nov-14-1956-1562201/}}{{free access}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Canada Out of World Tourney|date=November 15, 1956|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=36|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-nov-15-1956-1562204/}}{{free access}}</ref> Canada and the United States boycotted the World Championships due to the [[Hungarian Revolution of 1956|1956 Soviet invasion of Hungary]].<ref>''McKinley, Michael (2014)'', p. 115</ref>\n\nDudley attended the 1957 IIHF summer congress and made arrangements for a Soviet national team tour of Canada during November and December 1957. The CAHA agreed to pay Soviet travel within Canada and return fare, and a reciprocal Canadian tour of the Soviet Union in 1958.<ref>{{cite news|title=Red Pucksters To Tour Canada|date=August 26, 1957|newspaper=Medicine Hat News|location= Medicine Hat, Alberta|page=7|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-aug-26-1957-1562362/}}{{free access}}</ref> Dudley announced the tour would be seven games played under international rules,<ref>{{cite news|title=Canadian Press Sports Camera|last=Andrews|first=Ron|date=November 20, 1957|newspaper=Drumheller Mail|location=Drumheller, Alberta|page=14 |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-nov-20-1957-1562383/}}{{free access}}</ref> and only include cities in Ontario and Quebec due to limits on the Soviet's available travel time.<ref>{{cite news|title=Soviet Puck Team Unable Play In West|date=October 9, 1957|newspaper=Lethbridge Herald|location=Lethbridge, Alberta|page=10|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-oct-09-1957-1562366/}}{{free access}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Expect Large Crowd For Soviet Debut In Canada|last=Sullivan|first=Jack|date=October 10, 1957|newspaper=Lethbridge Herald|location=Lethbridge, Alberta|page=7 |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-oct-10-1957-1562368/}}{{free access}}</ref> He expected a sold-out crowd at Maple Leaf Gardens for the first game of the tour, and thought the Soviet team might be stronger than its Olympic version.<ref>{{cite news|title=Russian Pucksters Should Get Record Amateur Crowd|last=Sullivan|first=Jack|date=October 5, 1957|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=42|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-oct-05-1957-1562365/}}{{free access}}</ref> The tour reached on 62,000 in attendance. Dudley he felt the Soviets displayed a different way in which hockey could be played scientifically with sportsmanship. He wanted to see games in Western Canada on future tours, and mentioned the possibility of inviting Swedish or Czechoslovakian teams. He felt the event was good for international hockey, despite existing political differences.<ref>{{cite news|title=221 Teams Entered In MAHA Playoffs|date=January 14, 1958|newspaper=Brandon Daily Sun|location=Brandon, Manitoba|page=11|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jan-14-1958-1563387/}}{{free access}}</ref> The CAHA profited more than $22,000 from the Soviet tour.<ref name=\"may-19-1958\">{{cite news|title=Canadian Hockey Teams Go to Russia, Olympics|date=May 19, 1958|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=15|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-may-19-1958-1563408/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\n===1958 to 1959===\n[[Image:Belleville Memorial Arena.JPG|thumb|The Belleville Memorial Arena (''pictured'') was home to the McFarlands, and its facade displays the 1958 Allan Cup and 1959 World Championship teams.|alt=Belleville Memorial Arena facade]]\n\nThe CAHA chose to participate in the [[1958 Ice Hockey World Championships]], and Dudley announced that the [[1957 Allan Cup]] champions [[Whitby Dunlops]] would represent Canada and play a European exhibition schedule.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dunlops Will Sail January 29|date=August 17, 1957|newspaper=Lethbridge Herald|location=Lethbridge, Alberta|page=6 |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-aug-17-1957-1562360/}}{{free access}}</ref> Whitby won all seven games played at the World Championships to give Canada the title.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hockeyarchives.info/mondial1958.htm|title=Championnats du monde 1958|website=Hockey Archives|language=fr|access-date=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nDudley advocated for using the profits from the Soviet tour of Canada to send team on a reciprocal tour of the Soviet Union. In May 1958, the CAHA approved sending its first Canadian team on an exhibition tour of the Soviet Union.<ref name=\"may-19-1958\" /> The 1958 Allan Cup finalists [[Kelowna Packers]] were chosen for the five-game tour, and Dudley arranged for three subsequent games in Sweden.<ref>{{cite news|title=Kelowna To Play 5 Games, Red Capital|date=October 11, 1958|newspaper=Lethbridge Herald|location=Lethbridge, Alberta|page=9|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-oct-11-1958-1563453/}}{{free access}}</ref> He hoped that the Kelowna tour would promote future cultural exchanges with Eastern Europe.<ref name=\"may-18-1959\">{{cite news|title=International Hockey OK: Japanese Team Coming|date=May 18, 1959|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=15 |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-may-18-1959-1563507/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nDudley reported in May 1958, that the CAHA and NHL were close to signing a new deal. The previous professional-amateur agreement had expired in 1955, and the groups had operated on a gentleman's agreement since.<ref name=\"may-21-1958\">{{cite news|title=Allan Cup Champions To Defend World Ice Crown|last=Sullivan|first=Jack|date=May 21, 1958|newspaper=Brandon Daily Sun|location=Brandon, Manitoba|page=11|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-may-21-1958-1563414/}}{{free access}}</ref> He announced a new agreement in January 1959, in which the NHL contribution increased to $40,000 from $27,000. The agreement set out rules for negotiation lists and reserve lists, and professional teams agreed to an earlier deadline to decide which players might be moved from a junior team to a professional team. The CAHA agreed that amateurs aged 17 and older would use same rules as the professionals except for [[Overtime (ice hockey)|overtime]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Pro-Amateur Agreement Reached|date=January 3, 1959|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=38|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jan-03-1959-1563481/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nThe [[1958 Allan Cup]] champions [[Belleville McFarlands]] were chosen to represent Canada at the [[1959 Ice Hockey World Championships]].<ref name=\"may-21-1958\" /> In the exhibition tour before the championships, Finnish newspaper ''[[Helsingin Sanomat]]'' published that Canada showed poor sportsmanship. Dudley's response was to advise the team to use discretion in future games and to avoid incidents.<ref>{{cite news|title=Canadian Hockey Circles Worried By Newspapers|date=February 21, 1959|newspaper=St. John's Daily News|location=St. John's, Newfoundland|page=8|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-feb-21-1959-1563496/}}{{free access}}</ref> The McFarlands won seven of eight games played at the 1959 Ice Hockey World Championships to retain the world title for Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hockeyarchives.info/mondial1959.htm|title=Championnats du monde 1959|website=Hockey Archives|language=fr|access-date=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nDudley scheduled the May 1959 CAHA general meeting to be hosted in [[Detroit]], in conjunction with the AHAUS general meeting. He said that no CAHA branch offered to host delegates, which would typically cost $1,000.<ref>{{cite news|title='Punch' Wants No Part Of Lady Byng Winners|last=Sullivan|first=Jack|date=May 6, 1959|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=26 |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-may-06-1959-1563503/}}{{free access}}</ref> The Kitchener-Waterloo Dutchmen had been chosen to represent Canada at the upcoming Olympics, and Dudley announced that CAHA would pay for uniforms, and traveling expenses.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dutchies To Represent Canada At Squaw Valley|date=January 3, 1959|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=38|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jan-03-1959-1563483/}}{{free access}}</ref> At the meeting, the CAHA approved an increase in the roster size for the national team. It allowed the Dutchmen to take an additional 10 players from other teams, and would assist the teams which loaned players by granting roster replacements and $500 compensation.<ref name=\"may-20-1959\">{{cite news|title=Canada Plans Hold Tight To World Amateur Hockey Title|date=May 20, 1959|newspaper=Lethbridge Herald|location=Lethbridge, Alberta|page=12|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-may-20-1959-1563514/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\n===1960 Winter Olympics===\n[[File:Squaw-Valley-Blyth-Arena-1960.jpg|thumb|Blyth Arena at the Squaw Valley Ski Resort|alt=Blyth Arena]]\n\nDudley arranged a tour of Canada in January and February 1960 for the Russian Selects, an all-star team of players from clubs in Moscow.<ref>{{cite news|title=Russian Team Tours Canada|date=January 6, 1960|newspaper=St. John's Daily News|location=St. John's, Newfoundland and Labrador|page=8|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jan-06-1960-1536257/}}{{free access}}</ref> He stated the CAHA would decide at the upcoming general meeting whether to send a team on a reciprocal tour of Russia next winter. The CAHA was invited to send a team by the coach of the Russian Selects.<ref>{{cite news|title=Canadian To Tour Russia|date=January 19, 1960|newspaper=St. John's Daily News|location=St. John's, Newfoundland and Labrador|page=11|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jan-19-1960-1536272/}}{{free access}}</ref> Dudley also arranged a [[Japan men's national ice hockey team|Japan men's national team]] tour in Canada prior to the Olympics.<ref name=\"may-18-1959\" />\n\nDudley oversaw [[ice hockey at the 1960 Winter Olympics]] on behalf of the IIHF.<ref name=\"Legends\" /><ref name=\"Ferguson\" /><ref name=\"MOSHOF\" /> He arranged a qualification round to determine whether the [[Germany men's national ice hockey team|West Germany]] or [[East Germany national ice hockey team|East Germany national team]] would play in the Olympic tournament, hosted at the [[Blyth Arena]] at the [[Squaw Valley Ski Resort]] in California. The [[Australia men's national ice hockey team|Australia men's national team]] made its Olympic debut at the tournament, in which the [[United States men's national ice hockey team|United States men's national team]] won its first gold medal in hockey.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hockeyarchives.info/JO1960.htm|title=Jeux Olympiques de Squaw Valley 1960|website=Hockey Archives|language=fr|access-date=2020-02-03}}</ref> After the games, Dudley stated that the Kitchener-Waterloo Dutchmen who won the silver medal representing Canada \"cannot be blamed for not winning the title\". He also hoped for the national consciousness of Canada to awake before the 1964 games, to avoid similar disappointments of not winning the gold medal in hockey.<ref>{{cite news|title=CAHA Heads Praise K-W|date=February 29, 1960|newspaper=Winnipeg Tribune|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=14|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-feb-29-1960-1536352/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nIn April 1960, Dudley stated that Europeans were anxious to see Canadian teams play tours abroad, despite comments by [[Arnold Heeney]] the [[List of ambassadors of Canada to the United States|Canadian Ambassador to the United States]], who said that Canada was unpopular in Olympic hockey.<ref>{{cite news|title=Canada's Ambassador To United States Hardly Has Good Will Of Hockey Men|last=Sullivan|first=Jack|date=April 26, 1960|newspaper=Brandon Sun|location=Brandon, Manitoba|page=7 |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-apr-26-1960-1544697/}}{{free access}}</ref> In May 1960, Dudley wished to see a new method for choosing the Canadian national team which had less of an impact on domestic leagues, but produced results.<ref>{{cite news|title=Juckes Against All-Star Idea|date=May 2, 1960|newspaper=Lethbridge Herald|location=Lethbridge, Alberta|page=7|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-may-02-1960-1544701/}}{{free access}}</ref> He stated of the Canadian roster that, \"Ours are the best 17 after 500 have gone to supply the needs to the pro leagues in Canada and the United States, and at the Olympics another 500 are eliminated because they are reinstated professionals\".<ref>''Oliver, Greg (2017)'', p. 33</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nDudley became a member of Caledonian Lodge 249, the local [[Masonic lodge]] in 1915.<ref name=\"FreePress-p7\">{{cite news|title=Court, hockey officials, MPP pay tribute to G. S. Dudley|date=May 11, 1960|newspaper=Midland Free Press|location=Midland, Ontario|page=7}}</ref> He married Lulu Gidley in 1921.<ref name=\"CP-obit\" /><ref name=\"may-09-1960\">{{cite news|title=George Dudley, Known As Mr. Hockey, Dies|date=May 9, 1960|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=25|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-may-09-1960-1545603}}{{free access}}</ref> The couple never had children.<ref name=\"FreePress-p11\" /> He served 49 years on the [[Simcoe East]] riding association, and was affiliated with the [[Progressive Conservative Party of Ontario]].<ref name=\"FreePress-p12\" /> He was a member of St. Paul's United Church in Midland, a member of the [[Orange Order in Canada]], and chairman of the local Victory Bond committee in 1945.<ref name=\"FreePress-p11\" />\n\n==Death==\n[[File:George S Dudley grave stone.jpg|thumb|Dudley family gravestone at Lakeview Cemetery in Midland|alt=Dudley's gravestone]]\n\nDudley had a stroke on May 6, 1960. He died on May 8, at St. Andrew's hospital in Midland.<ref name=\"FreePress-p11\" /><ref name=\"may-09-1960\" /> He was interred in the family plot at Lakeview Cemetery in Midland, with his parents.<ref>{{Citation|title=Interment Directory|place=Midland, Ontario|publisher=Lakeview Cemetery|year=2019}}</ref>\n\nAt the time of his death, Dudley was expected to become the next president of the IIHF.<ref name=\"MOSHOF\" /><ref name=\"FreePress-p12\" /> [[Robert Lebel (ice hockey)|Robert Lebel]] who was a past-president of the CAHA, succeeded Dudley and became president of the IIHF in July 1960.<ref>{{cite news|title=Name Canuck Hockey Prexy|newspaper=Lethbridge Herald|location=Lethbridge, Alberta|date=July 27, 1960|page=14|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jul-27-1960-734440/}}{{free access}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iihf.com/iihf-home/history/the-iihf/presidents/|title=History of IIHF Presidents|website=International Ice Hockey Federation|access-date=June 26, 2018}}</ref> [[Gordon Juckes]] who was the current CAHA president, succeeded Dudley as secretary-manager of the CAHA when the position became a full-time paid role.<ref name=\"CAHA-p117\" /><ref>{{cite news|title=CAHA Flourishes Under Gordon Juckes' Guidance|date=January 23, 1968|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=18|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jan-23-1968-1526436/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\n==Honours and awards==\nDudley was made a life member of the CAHA in November 1944.<ref>{{cite news|title=Canadian Sport Snapshorts|last=Thomas|first=Syd|date=November 11, 1944|newspaper=Brandon Daily Sun|location=Brandon, Manitoba|page=4|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-nov-11-1944-1553000/}}{{free access}}</ref> He received the OHA Gold Stick award in 1949, in recognition of service to hockey in Ontario.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ohahockey.ca/view/oha/about-us/association-awards/gold-stick|title=Gold Stick|year=2018|website=Ontario Hockey Association|access-date=2019-02-16}}</ref> He received the AHAUS citation award in 1950 for service to amateur hockey in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usahockey.com/layout_container/show_layout_tab?layout_container_id=27569776&page_node_id=837446&tab_element_id=54968|title=Citation Award|website=USA Hockey|access-date=2019-02-01}}</ref> Dudley and W. A. Hewitt were honoured with a dinner by the OHA in December 1950, and Dudley received a silver tea service in recognition of 26 years of service to the OHA.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hockey Officials Honored|date=December 6, 1950|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|page=24|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-dec-06-1950-1555518/}}{{free access}}</ref> He was made a life member of the OHA in 1952.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ohahockey.ca/view/oha/about-us/association-awards/oha-life-members|title=OHA Life Members|year=2018|website=Ontario Hockey Association|access-date=2019-02-16}}</ref> He was inducted to the builder category of the Hockey Hall of Fame in 1958.<ref name=\"Legends\" /><ref>{{cite news|title=Puck Hall of Fame Officially Open|last=Sullivan|first=Jack|date=April 28, 1958|newspaper=Medicine Hat News|location=Medicine Hat, Alberta|page=12|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-apr-28-1958-1563396/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nAfter his death in 1960, the CAHA observed a moment of silence at that year's general meeting.<ref>{{cite news|title=CAHA Honors George Dudley|date=May 24, 1960|newspaper=Brandon Sun|location=Brandon, Manitoba|page=6|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-may-24-1960-1545656/}}{{free access}}</ref> He was posthumously inducted into the Midland Sports Hall of Fame on October 12, 1996.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.midlandonsportshalloffame.com/builders-2|title=Builders|website=Midland Sports Hall of Fame|access-date=2020-02-01}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n[[File:Dudley Hewitt Cup.png|thumb|Dudley Hewitt Cup|alt=Dudley Hewitt Cup trophy]]\n\nDudley was known as Mr. Hockey.<ref name=\"MOSHOF\" /><ref name=\"CP-obit\" /><ref name=\"may-09-1960\" /> He and W. A. Hewitt are the namesakes of the [[Dudley Hewitt Cup]]. It was first awarded by the [[Canadian Junior Hockey League]] in 1971 to the Central Canada Junior A champion team, who moves on to the national [[Centennial Cup]] competition.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thunderbaybusiness.ca/article/the-dudley-hewitt-cup--and-the-business--of-hockey-416.asp|title=The Dudley Hewitt Cup and the Business of Hockey|last=Aalto|first=Sherry|year=2012|website=Thunder Bay Business|access-date=2019-02-18}}</ref><ref name=\"CCC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.centralcanadianchampionship.com/view/dudleyhewitt/about-the-cup-3|title=Dudley Hewitt Cup|website=Canadian Junior Hockey League|access-date=2019-02-16}}</ref>\n\nDudley's death led to multiple tributes from the hockey community. CAHA president Gordon Juckes stated, \"to sportsmen national and internationally, his death will mean the personal loss of an experienced, impartial and able administrator\". CAHA vice-president Jack Roxburgh described him as, \"the best man hockey ever knew\". Toronto Maple Leafs coach [[Punch Imlach]] said that, \"he did more for hockey than any living man\".<ref name=\"CP-obit\" /><ref name=\"FreePress-p7\" /> Journalist Jack Sullivan described Dudley as a staunch and shrewd hockey official, a problem solver, and a slow-talking person who stayed away from the limelight.<ref>{{cite news|title=George Dudley Is Laid To Rest: Hockey Loses Valuable Official|last=Sullivan|first=Jack|date=May 13, 1960|newspaper=Lethbridge Herald|location=Lethbridge, Alberta|page=9|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-may-13-1960-1545620/}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nCanadian journalist and hockey historian [[Scott Young (writer)|Scott Young]] mentioned Dudley frequently in the book, ''100 Years of Dropping the Puck: A History of the OHA''. Young described Dudley as a low-key figure at first who grew to prominence by his reputation as being one the busiest and most able volunteers in the OHA.<ref name=\"Young-p157\" /><ref>''Young, Scott (1989)'', p. 290</ref> Young further stated that Dudley was a forward thinker,<ref>''Young, Scott (1989)'', p. 158</ref> a man who always had a solution to problems in hockey,<ref>''Young, Scott (1989)'', p. 156</ref> and had the ability to listen to a conversation and find a compromise without forcing anyone to change his mind.<ref name=\"Young-p172\" /> Young credited Dudley for dealing with reforms to amateurism, and regulations on player salaries and transfers, which led to increased interest in hockey.<ref name=\"Young-p191\" /> Young also credited Dudley's management skills as a primary factor in the improvement of OHA finances during the 1950s.<ref>''Young, Scott (1989)'', p. 217</ref>\n\n==References==\n'''General'''\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Ellison|first1=Jenny|last2=Anderson|first2=Jennifer|title=Hockey: Challenging Canada\u2019s Game|publisher=Canadian Museum of History|date=2018|location=Ottawa, Ontario|pages=116|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=BeBVDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA116|isbn=978-0-7766-2771-7|via=Google Books}}\n*{{cite book|last=Oliver|first=Greg|title=Father Bauer and the Great Experiment: The Genesis of Canadian Olympic Hockey|publisher=ECW Press|date=2017|location=Toronto, Ontario|isbn=978-1-77041-249-1}}\n*{{Citation|last=Ladouceur|first=Denise & John|title=Lakeview Cemetery Tombstone Index|place=Midland, Ontario|publisher=North Simcoe Geneaology Society|year=2006|series=Midland 125 Cemetery Project}}\n*{{cite book|last=McKinley|first=Michael|title=It's Our Game: Celebrating 100 Years Of Hockey Canada|publisher=Viking|date=2014|location=Toronto, Ontario|isbn=978-0-670-06817-3}}\n*{{cite book|last=Duplacey|first=James|title=Total Hockey: The official encyclopedia of the National Hockey League|year=1998|publisher=Total Sports|isbn=0-8362-7114-9|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/totalhockeyoffic0000unse/page/503}}\n*{{cite book|last=Ferguson|first=Bob|title=Who's Who in Canadian Sport, Volume 4|publisher=Fitzhenry & Whiteside Ltd.|date=2005|location=Markham, Ontario|isbn=1-55041-855-6}}\n*{{cite book|last=Young|first=Scott|author-link1=Scott Young (writer)|title=100 Years of Dropping the Puck|publisher=McClelland & Stewart Inc.|date=1989|location=Toronto, Ontario|isbn=0-7710-9093-5}}\n*{{cite book|title=Constitution, By-laws, Regulations, History|publisher=Canadian Amateur Hockey Association|date=May 1990|location=Gloucester, Ontario}}\n{{refend}}\n\n'''Specific'''\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dudley, George}}\n[[Category:1894 births]]\n[[Category:1960 deaths]]\n[[Category:Burials in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Canadian Amateur Hockey Association presidents]]\n[[Category:Canadian Freemasons]]\n[[Category:Canadian Queen's Counsel]]\n[[Category:Hockey Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:Ice hockey people from Ontario]]\n[[Category:International Ice Hockey Federation executives]]\n[[Category:Lawyers in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Members of the Orange Order]]\n[[Category:Ontario Hockey Association executives]]\n[[Category:Osgoode Hall Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Midland, Ontario]]\n[[Category:Solicitors]]\n", "name_user": "GiantSnowman", "label": "safe", "comment": "date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_Dudley"}
{"title_page": "Lamborghini (song)", "text_new": "{{Short description|2015 song by KSI featuring P Money}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2015}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Lamborghini\n| cover      = KSI - Lamborghini cover art.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[KSI (entertainer)|KSI]] featuring [[P Money]]\n| EP=[[Keep Up (EP)|Keep Up]]\n| released   = 23 March 2015\n| format     =\n* [[Music download|Digital download]]\n* [[Streaming media|streaming]]\n| recorded   =2014-2015\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      =\n* [[British hip hop]]\n* [[Grime music|grime]]\n| length     = 2:56\n| label      =\n* [[Dcypha Productions|Dcypha]]\n* [[Island Records|Island]]\n| writer     =\n* [[KSI (entertainer)|Olajide Olatunji]]\n* [[P Money|Paris Moore-Williams]]\n* [[Sway (musician)|Derek Safo]]\n* Tumai Salih<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web |title=Lamborghini by KSI featuring P Money |url=https://listen.tidal.com/album/86036682/track/86036683 |website=Tidal |accessdate=16 February 2020}}</ref>\n| producer   = DJ Turkish<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n| chronology = [[KSI (entertainer)|KSI]]\n| prev_title = No Sleep\n| prev_year  = 2013\n| next_title = [[Keep Up (KSI song)|Keep Up]]\n| next_year  = 2015\n| misc       = {{Extra chronology\n | artist     = [[P Money]]\n | type       = Singles\n | prev_title = Reload\n | prev_year  = 2012\n | title      = Lamborghini\n | year       = 2015\n | next_title = 10/10\n | next_year  = 2015\n}}\n{{External music video|{{YouTube|708mjaHTwKc|\"Lamborghini\"}}}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Lamborghini'''\" is the debut song by British YouTube personality and rapper [[KSI (entertainer)|KSI]], featuring British grime MC [[P Money]]. The song is produced by DJ Turkish. It was released on 23 March 2015 through [[Dcypha Productions]]. The song charted at number 30 on the [[UK Singles Chart]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/jess-glynne-scores-her-first-solo-number-1__8805/|title=\u201cIt\u2019s a pretty insane feeling!\u201d Jess Glynne scores first solo Number 1|website=www.officialcharts.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-16}}</ref> A remix of the song, which does not feature P Money and instead features new verses by KSI and British rappers [[Sway (musician)|Sway]], Youngs Teflon and [[Scrufizzer]], appears on KSI's 2016 debut extended play, [[Keep Up (EP)|''Keep Up'']], under the name \"'''Lambo Refuelled'''\".\n\n== Commercial performance ==\nThe song entered the UK Singles Chart at number 30, making it KSI's first UK top 40 single and his third highest charting single in the UK to date.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/artist/48106/ksi/|title=KSI {{!}} full Official Chart History {{!}} Official Charts Company|website=www.officialcharts.com|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> It dropped to number 68 and number 96 over the following two weeks before dropping out of the top 100.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/charts/singles-chart/20150405/7501/|title=Official Singles Chart Top 100 {{!}} Official Charts Company|website=www.officialcharts.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/charts/singles-chart/20150412/7501/|title=Official Singles Chart Top 100 {{!}} Official Charts Company|website=www.officialcharts.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-16}}</ref> KSI reacted to the commercial success of the song on [[Twitter]], saying \"yo thanks to everyone who listened to Lamborghini on Spotify and bought on iTunes!!! Didn't even think I would get in the top 40 man\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://teneightymagazine.com/2015/04/04/ksi-enters-uk-top-40/|title=KSI Enters UK Top 40 \u2013 TenEighty \u2014 YouTube News, Features, and Interviews|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-02-16}}</ref>\n\n==Music video==\nThe music video, directed by Jak X, was uploaded to KSI's YouTube channel on 25 March 2015, two days after the release of the song. KSI's purple [[Lamborghini Aventador]] prominently appears in the video. As of April 2020, the music video has 110 million views, making it KSI's most-viewed music video on YouTube to date.<ref name=\"Music video\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=708mjaHTwKc|title=KSI - Lamborghini (Explicit) feat. P Money|publisher=[[YouTube]] |date=25 March 2015|accessdate=26 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Track listing ==\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Digital download<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n| title6 = \n| length10 = \n| title10 = \n| length9 = \n| title9 = \n| length8 = \n| title8 = \n| length7 = \n| title7 = \n| length6 = \n| length5 = \n| title1 = Lamborghini\n| title5 = \n| length4 = \n| title4 = \n| length3 = \n| title3 = \n| length2 = \n| title2 = \n| all_writing = \n| length1 = 2:56\n| note1 = featuring [[P Money]]\n| total_length = \n}}\n\n== Credits and personnel ==\nCredits adapted from [[Tidal (service)|Tidal]].<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n{{div col}}\n*[[KSI (entertainer)|KSI]] \u2013 vocals, songwriter\n*[[P Money]] \u2013 vocals, songwriter\n*[[Sway (musician)|Sway]] \u2013 songwriter\n*DJ Turkish \u2013 producer, songwriter\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Charts==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!Chart (2015)\n!Peak<br>position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Ireland|61|artist=KSI Feat. P Money|song=Lamborghini|week=13|year=2015|rowheader=true|accessdate=9 May 2015}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Scotland|28|date=2015-03-29|rowheader=true|accessdate=29 March 2015}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|UK|30|date=2015-03-29|rowheader=true|accessdate=29 March 2015}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|UKindie|2|date=2015-03-29|rowheader=true|accessdate=6 April 2015}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|UKrandb|7|date=2015-03-29|rowheader=true|accessdate=29 March 2015}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==Release history==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n! scope=\"col\" |Region\n! scope=\"col\" |Date\n! scope=\"col\" |Format\n! scope=\"col\" |Label\n! scope=\"col\" |Ref.\n|-\n! 